{"title_page": "Swraj Paul, Baron Paul", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name               = The Lord Paul\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]]\n| image              = Official portrait of Lord Paul.jpg\n| birth_name         = Swraj Paul\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1931|02|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Jalandhar]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab Province]], [[British India]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = London, UK\n| nationality        = [[Indian British]]\n| citizenship        = British\n| education          = Doaba College Jalandhar, Punjab; \n[[Forman Christian College]], Lahore; \n[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n| occupation         = Businessman\n| known_for          = \n| net_worth          = \u00a32 billion<ref name=BirminghamPost>{{cite web|title=Birmingham Post Rich List 2014: No.2 - Lord Paul of Marylebone and family (\u00a32bn)|url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/manufacturing/birmingham-post-rich-list-2014-6530631|website=Birmingham Post|access-date=8 November 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108144641/http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/manufacturing/birmingham-post-rich-list-2014-6530631|archive-date=8 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| party              = Independent\n| spouse             = \n| children           = 4, including [[Angad Paul]] (deceased)\n| website            = \n}}\n \n'''Swraj Paul, Baron Paul''', [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] (born 18 February 1931) is an [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Indian-born]], British-based business magnate and philanthropist.  In 1996 he was appointed a [[life peer]] by Conservative Prime Minister John Major,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Interview: Swraj Paul, Engineering magnate puts his faith in British steeliness|url = https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/21/swraj-paul-caparo-london-zoo|website = the Guardian|access-date = 6 October 2015|first = Abhinav|last = Ramnarayan|url-status = live|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151006181444/http://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/21/swraj-paul-caparo-london-zoo|archive-date = 6 October 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref> and sits in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[crossbencher]] with the title '''Baron Paul''', of [[Marylebone]], in the [[City of Westminster]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{London Gazette |issue=54553 |date=16 October 1996 |page=13737}}</ref> In December 2008 he was appointed [[deputy speaker]] [[Lord Speaker|of the Lords]]; in October 2009 he was [[List of current members of the British Privy Council|appointed to]] [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|the Privy Council.]] <ref name=\"TheyWorkForYou\">{{Cite web|title = TheyWorkForYou|url = https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/13603/lord_paul|website = www.theyworkforyou.com|access-date = 8 October 2015|url-status = live|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150910031237/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/13603/lord_paul|archive-date = 10 September 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAccording to his official biography, Swraj Paul was born in [[Jalandhar]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab Province]] in 1931, in what was then [[British India]].  His father Payare Lal ran a small [[foundry]], making steel buckets and farming equipment. His mother's name was Mongwati. The site of his childhood home is now [[Apeejay School]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caparo.com/en-gb/about/board-member-profile.aspx?bmid=0a2157f3-539b-4178-bd3d-67bbfabcfac9 |title=Caparo \u2014 Caparo is a global group wholly owned and managed by the Paul family. Caparo is chaired by Lord Paul of Marylebone |publisher=Caparo.com |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920092323/http://www.caparo.com/en-gb/about/board-member-profile.aspx?bmid=0a2157f3-539b-4178-bd3d-67bbfabcfac9 |archive-date=20 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSwraj Paul completed his [[high school]] education at Labbu Ram Doaba School. Paul was educated at [[Forman Christian College]] in [[Lahore]], and [[Doaba College]] in [[Jalandhar]]. He went to the United States to study [[mechanical engineering]], obtaining BSc, MSc and MechE degrees from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite web |author=Abhinav Ramnarayan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/21/swraj-paul-caparo-london-zoo |title=Interview: Swraj Paul, Engineering magnate puts his faith in British steeliness &#124; Business |publisher=The Guardian |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006181444/http://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/21/swraj-paul-caparo-london-zoo |archive-date=6 October 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Business career ==\nAfter leaving MIT, he returned to India to work for the family business, Apeejay Group, which was founded by his father, and was, at the time, managed by his two older brothers, Stya Paul and Jit Paul.\n\n===Caparo Group ===\nIn 1966 he relocated to the United Kingdom to get medical treatment for his young daughter, who had [[leukaemia]].<ref name=\"Asian Woman Awards website\">[http://www.theasianwomanawards.com/lifetimeach-2008.html]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009125148/http://www.theasianwomanawards.com/lifetimeach-2008.html|date=9 October 2011}}</ref> He spent a year grieving her death, after which he founded Natural Gas Tubes.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/> Starting with one steel unit, he went on to acquire more. This led to his founding the [[Caparo plc|Caparo Group]] in 1968, which became one of the UK's largest steel conversion and distribution businesses, manufacturing an extensive range of structural steels, precision tube, spirally welded tube, special bar qualities, industrial wires, cold rolled strip and spring steel strip. Lord Paul stepped down from the management of the Caparo Group in 1996.<ref name=\"economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/features/the-global-indian-takeover/Swraj-Paul-Humane-capital/articleshow/2618496.cms |title=Swraj Paul: Humane capital - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=13 December 2007 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/features/the-global-indian-takeover/Swraj-Paul-Humane-capital/articleshow/2618496.cms |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nUp until Autumn 2015, Caparo employed over 10,000 people across North America, Europe, India and, the Middle East. In October 2015, 16 of the 20 limited companies that formed most of Caparo Group UK collapsed into administration,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34574982 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-11-09 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025011414/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34574982 |archive-date=25 October 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and on 8 November his son [[Angad Paul]], the Group's CEO, died in an apparent suicide from his eighth-floor penthouse flat.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34765572 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-11-09 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109110134/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34765572 |archive-date=9 November 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Public role and philanthropy ==\nLord Paul has held many public positions. In 2006, as part of his parliamentary work, he made a declaration of interest;<ref name=\"publications.parliament.uk\"/> he was involved with more than a dozen organisations outside his family business and foundation. This [[Foundation (nonprofit)#United Kingdom|foundation]], named in memory of his daughter,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nriinternet.com/NRIcharity/UK/Ambika_Paul_Foundation/index.htm |title=The Ambika Paul Foundation, UK- in memory of Lord Paul's daughter Ambika |publisher=Nriinternet.com |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083412/http://www.nriinternet.com/NRIcharity/UK/Ambika_Paul_Foundation/index.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> channels profits from Caparo India into charitable endeavours.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caparo.co.in/about_corporate_responsibility.html |title=Caparo |publisher=Caparo |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928041031/http://www.caparo.co.in/about_corporate_responsibility.html |archive-date=28 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> For example, Paul is an honorary patron of the [[Zoological Society of London]] and has funded major projects at the [[Regent's Park]] site, including the Ambika Paul [[children's zoo]].<ref>[http://www.zsl.org/zsl-london-zoo/news/childrens-zoo-at-london-zoo,200,NS.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420164941/http://www.zsl.org/zsl-london-zoo/news/childrens-zoo-at-london-zoo,200,NS.html|date=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nThe Foundation has established the Ambika Paul School of Technology in Jalandhar, India.\n\nLord Paul held the [[Pro-Chancellor]]ship of [[Thames Valley University]] in 1997, and Chancellorship in 1998.\n\nHe has been the [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Wolverhampton]] since 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wlv.ac.uk/Default.aspx?page=7220 |title=Chancellor - University of Wolverhampton |publisher=Wlv.ac.uk |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906121229/https://www.wlv.ac.uk/Default.aspx?page=7220 |archive-date=6 September 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2010 the [[Student union building|student union centre]] was renamed \"The Ambika Paul Student Union Centre\", following his donation towards its refurbishment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wlv.ac.uk/default.aspx?page=25362 |title=November 2010 - New Student Union Centre opened by Chancellor - University of Wolverhampton |publisher=Wlv.ac.uk |date=26 November 2010 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207080452/http://www.wlv.ac.uk/default.aspx?page=25362 |archive-date=7 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2015 he gave, through his family foundation, \u00a31 million, the largest single donation in the university's history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolverhampton University receives \u00a31m - the biggest donation in its history|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2015/04/12/wolverhampton-university-receives-1m-the-biggest-donation-in-its-history/|access-date=29 November 2017|publisher=Express and Star|date=12 April 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034239/https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2015/04/12/wolverhampton-university-receives-1m-the-biggest-donation-in-its-history/|archive-date=1 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLord Paul was Chancellor of [[University of Westminster]],<ref name=\"publications.parliament.uk\">{{cite web |author=The Committee Office, House of Lords |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/ldselect/ldeconaf/204/20409.htm |title=House of Lords - Economic Affairs - Sixth Report |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924145856/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/ldselect/ldeconaf/204/20409.htm |archive-date=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wmin.ac.uk/page-16504 |title=Shaping the Future - Shaping the future - University of Westminster, London |publisher=Wmin.ac.uk |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924155845/http://www.wmin.ac.uk/page-16504 |archive-date=24 September 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> from 2006 to 2014; his foundation donated \u00a3300,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charity-commission.gov.uk/registeredcharities/ScannedAccounts/Ends27/0000276127_ac_20080430_e_c.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220012008/http://www.charity-commission.gov.uk/registeredcharities/ScannedAccounts/Ends27/0000276127_ac_20080430_e_c.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 February 2009|title=Wayback Machine|author=|date=20 February 2009|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> to establish the Ambika P3 event and exhibition space.\n\nHe sat on [[MIT]]'s Mechanical Engineering Visiting Committee<!-- The MIT site for that committee ([http://web.mit.edu/corporation/visiting/mechanical-engineering.html here]) makes no mention of him, but is only \"for this year\", not historic. --> between 1998 and 2001, when he established the Ambika Paul Mezzanine and Study Space, and the Swraj Paul Scholarship fund for undergraduate and graduate students.\n\nLord Paul is a member of the President's Cabinet for [[Chapman University]] in [[Orange, California]].<ref>[https://www.chapman.edu/about/administration/trustees/members.aspx] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229093916/https://www.chapman.edu/about/administration/trustees/members.aspx|date=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===International relations===\nLord Paul has taken an interest in international relations. He was appointed by the government to act as an ambassador for British business from 1998 \u20132010.<ref>{{cite web |author=The Committee Office, House of Lords |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200203/ldselect/ldeconaf/5/510.htm |title=House of Lords - Economic Affairs - First Report |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=17 January 2003 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924145635/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200203/ldselect/ldeconaf/5/510.htm |archive-date=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was a member of the [[Foreign Policy Centre]] Advisory Council.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fpc.org.uk/fsblob/240.pdf |format=PDF |title=The Foreign Policy Centre : China has discovered its own economic consensus |author=Joshua Cooper Ramo |publisher=Fpc.org.uk |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303235022/http://fpc.org.uk/fsblob/240.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He contested for the chairmanship of the [[Commonwealth Parliamentary Association]], with an agenda to reduce the gap between the West and [[Eastern world|the East]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}. Lord Paul was Co-Chairman of the Indo-British Roundtable from 2000\u20132005.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/Indo-UK-ties-better-than-before-Lord-Paul/articleshow/45852028.cms |title=Indo-UK ties better than before: Lord Paul - The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=9 May 2003 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/Indo-UK-ties-better-than-before-Lord-Paul/articleshow/45852028.cms |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nriinternet.com/NRIpoliticians/UK/A_Z/S/Lord%20Swraj_files/2005/020605_StepDown.htm |title=Lord Paul to step down as Co-Chairman of India-UK Round Table |publisher=Nriinternet.com |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083407/http://www.nriinternet.com/NRIpoliticians/UK/A_Z/S/Lord%20Swraj_files/2005/020605_StepDown.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was a member of Panel 2000, an appointment by the Prime Minister to re-brand Britain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hansard - written answers|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200001/cmhansrd/vo001212/text/01212w13.htm|website=UK Parliament|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222010446/http://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200001/cmhansrd/vo001212/text/01212w13.htm/|archive-date=22 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===UK politics===\nLord Paul has donated \u00a3500,000 to the Labour Party,<ref>{{cite web |author=Allegra Stratton |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/11/lord-paul-denies-rule-breaking |title=MPs expenses: Lord Paul denies he broke rules on residence allowance &#124; Politics |publisher=The Guardian |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004123529/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/11/lord-paul-denies-rule-breaking |archive-date=4 October 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> being the largest donor to [[2007 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Gordon Brown's leadership campaign]]<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\" /> and offering in 2007 to give \"as much as [he] can afford\" in the case of an early election.<ref>{{cite web |last=Carlin |first=Brendan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1560325/Donors-pledge-fuels-early-election-rumours.html |title=Donor's pledge fuels early election rumours |publisher=The Daily Telegraph |date=15 August 2007 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925144141/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1560325/Donors-pledge-fuels-early-election-rumours.html |archive-date=25 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He is also close to the former UK Prime Minister's wife, [[Sarah Jane Brown|Sarah Brown]],<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/indians-abroad/Lord-Swaraj-Pauls-son-weds-at-London-Zoo/articleshow/880764.cms |title=Lord Swaraj Paul's son weds at London Zoo - The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=11 October 2004 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/indians-abroad/Lord-Swaraj-Pauls-son-weds-at-London-Zoo/articleshow/880764.cms |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> for whom he shows paternal concern<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\" /> Lord Paul was chairman and trustee of Theirworld and chairman Theirworld Projects Ltd (formerly PiggyBankKids) from 2002 to 2015; the charity was founded by Sarah Brown.<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://theirworld.org/about/history|website=Theirworld|access-date=29 November 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005143434/http://theirworld.org/about/history|archive-date=5 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe was the first [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|person of Indian origin]] to hold the post of [[deputy speaker]] [[Lord Speaker|of the House of Lords]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7776220.stm |title=South Asia &#124; UK deputy Speaker is Indian-born |publisher=BBC News |date=10 December 2008 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723190651/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7776220.stm |archive-date=23 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> one of twelve people in that post.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/the-global-indian-takeover/Lord-Paul-Speaking-his-mind/articleshow/3854513.cms |title=Lord Paul: Speaking his mind - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=18 December 2008 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/the-global-indian-takeover/Lord-Paul-Speaking-his-mind/articleshow/3854513.cms |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was sworn of the [[Privy Council]] on 15 October 2009.<ref>[http://www.privy-council.org.uk/output/page76.asp#p]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119075331/http://www.privy-council.org.uk/output/page76.asp#p|date=19 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"O15Oct09\">[http://www.privy-council.org.uk/files/word/October%2015th%202009.doc]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611043731/http://www.privy-council.org.uk/files/word/October%2015th%202009.doc|date=11 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nLord Paul was involved with the [[2012 Summer Olympics|London Olympics]] from its inception; he was a member of the board responsible for the 2005 submission of the [[London bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics|bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics]]. He travelled to Singapore as part of the bidding team that successfully persuaded the [[International Olympic Committee]] to award the games to London for 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-07-27/news/32889714_1_london-olympics-london-development-agency-mayor-ken-livingstone|title=London Olympics 2012: NRI Lord Swraj Paul played vital role in bidding and holding the Games - timesofindia-economictimes|author=|date=|publisher=Articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>  <!-- These claims are based on the ''Economic Times'' article, which incorrectly calls the IOC the \"International Olympic Association\". --> He chaired the Olympic Delivery Committee, part of the [[London Development Agency]], with the job of obtaining the land on which to build the new venues, and delivering the land on time and on budget. (See [[Legacy of the 2012 Summer Olympics]].){{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nLord Paul has received various awards and honours including 15 honorary degrees from universities in the UK, US, India, Russia and Switzerland.  In 1983 he was awarded the [[Padma Bhushan]], by [[Indira Gandhi]], the [[Prime Minister of India]],<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web |url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |access-date=21 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archive-date=15 November 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> and the [[Bharat Gaurav]] award by the [[Indian Merchants' Chamber]]. Freedom of the City of London, 1998; Asian Business Awards, Lifetime Achievement Award, 2008; Donald C. Burnham Manufacturing Management Award, Society of Manufacturing Engineers, USA, 1995; First Asian of the Year Award, Asian Who's Who, 1987; \nAsian Woman Magazine Lifetime Achievement Award, 2008.<ref name=\"Asian Woman Awards website\"/> PowerBrands Hall of Fame nominated him Global Indian of the Year, 2011.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}  Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Corporate Leadership Award, 1989.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nHe was awarded \"International Indian of Decade\" for his outstanding achievements in the fields of industry, education and philanthropy at the 20th anniversary of the publication of India Link International, a monthly magazine on 15 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/article2712301.ece |title=Swraj Paul awarded lifetime achievement prize |publisher=The Hindu |date=13 December 2011 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/article2712301.ece |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Lord Paul was presented with a Lifetime Achievement Award by the Black Country Asian Business Association for his \"outstanding achievements in the fields of industry, education and philanthropy\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indolink.com/displayArticleS.php?id=111513103008 |title=Indian Diaspora (NRI) News: 'International Indian Of The Decade' Award Given To Lord Paul |publisher=INDOlink |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924034533/http://www.indolink.com/displayArticleS.php?id=111513103008 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2014, he received a further Lifetime Achievement Award in recognition of his work in promoting India-UK educational ties from the Global Skill Tree consortium,an India Based think tank, which hopes to promote India as a global hub of international education through its \"Great Place to Study \u2013 India\" initiative.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-06-25/news/50856012_1_lord-paul-sushma-berlia-indian |title=Swraj Paul honoured for promoting India-UK educational ties - timesofindia-economictimes |publisher=Articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Lord Paul was given the \"International Icon of the Decade Award\" by the World Consulting Research Corporation at its Global Indian Excellence Summit in London,  in recognition of \"his outstanding achievements in the fields of manufacturing, education and philanthropy\".<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/states/lord-swraj-paul-hits-out-at-foreign-countries-for-unsolicited-advice/article6237079.ece |title=Lord Swraj Paul hits out at foreign countries for unsolicited advice &#124; Business Line |publisher=Thehindubusinessline.com |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Lord Paul received two awards during a trip to India: the IOD Golden Peacock Award For Lifetime Achievement in Business Leadership and the Global Punjabi Society Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianage.com/metros/delhi/080418/golden-peacock-awarded-to-industrialist-swraj-paul.html|title=Golden Peacock awarded to industrialist Swraj Lord Paul|author=|date=8 April 2018|website=The Asian Age|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> In May 2018, Lord Paul was given the Int+ WCRC International Iconic Leader Award for Lifetime Achievement, at the UK & Asia Business Awards ceremony in London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/nris-in-news/nri-industrialist-swraj-paul-wins-lifetime-achievement-award-in-uk/articleshow/64225278.cms|title=NRI industrialist Swraj Paul wins lifetime achievement award in UK|date=2018-05-18|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref> In October 2018, he was awarded the Mahatma Gandhi Honour by the NRI Institute in celebration of their 30th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/swraj-paul-gets-mahatma-gandhi-honour-in-uk-for-underlining-work-of-nris-118103101532_1.html|title=Swraj Paul gets Mahatma Gandhi Honour in UK for underlining work of NRIs|first=Press Trust of|last=India|date=31 October 2018|publisher=|accessdate=22 January 2019|via=Business Standard}}</ref> In June 2019, he was awarded an honorary scholarship at the London Zoological Society.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn October 2009  ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' reported that Lord Paul had been unable satisfactorily to explain claiming expenses of \u00a338,000 for the period January 2005 to July 2006. Lord Paul immediately requested the Clerk of the Parliaments to investigate his expenses at the same time repaying,  \u00a341,982 instead of \u00a326,988 \u2013 \u00a315,000, more than the House of Lords would have requested at the conclusion of their investigation. A refund of the difference was never issued by the House of Lords. The [[Metropolitan Police]] opened an investigation concerning these expense claims,<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7017838.ece  \"Three more peers face charges\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604200455/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7017838.ece |date=4 June 2011 }} ''The Sunday Times'' 7 February 2010</ref> but by the end of February 2010 concluded there was no case.  Lord Paul appeared before various committees for Lord's Conduct with ultimately the Privileges Committee concluding that Lord Paul had not acted dishonestly or in bad faith.  They did determine however that he had been negligent and acted in ignorance and that his actions did render him liable to sanction by the House.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=The Committee Office, House of Lords |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201011/ldselect/ldprivi/37/3703.htm |title=House of Lords - The Conduct of Lord Paul - Privileges and Conduct Committee |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924150453/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201011/ldselect/ldprivi/37/3703.htm |archive-date=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lord Paul's suspension was for four months.  Lord Paul completely disagreed with their finding, calling it \"unreasonable.\" Lord Paul gave a  [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201011/ldhansrd/text/110622-0003.htm#11062274000031<nowiki/> Speech] in the House of Lords in June 2011 calling for reform and revision of the structure of the constitution.\n\nPaul tendered his resignation as Deputy Speaker to the Lord Speaker on 1 November 2010. His letter, printed in ''[[The House Magazine]]'' a week later, expressed his reservations about the process, calling it \"a sad saga for parliamentary democracy \u2013 an unfortunate series of events having evidently been inspired by the electoral politics of the media\". He has spoken on this topic many times since the expenses scandal initially made news,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/ColumnsOthers/A-trial-by-rumour/Article1-634780.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130629091529/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/ColumnsOthers/A-trial-by-rumour/Article1-634780.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 June 2013 |title=A trial by rumour |publisher=Hindustantimes.com |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 }}</ref> and maintains that no wrongdoing had occurred in his case.<ref>{{cite web |author=Simon Hattenstone |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/11/mps-expenses-scandal-what-next |title=MPs' expenses scandal: what happened next? &#124; Politics |publisher=The Guardian |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929141107/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/11/mps-expenses-scandal-what-next |archive-date=29 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{cite web |last=McDonagh |first=Siobhain |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/mehdi-hasan/2010/03/160-status-lord-peer-tory |title=Exclusive: Lord Paul to end his non-domiciled tax status |publisher=Newstatesman.com |date=9 March 2010 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/mehdi-hasan/2010/03/160-status-lord-peer-tory |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLord Paul is on the [[Sunday Times Rich List]] as the 38th richest person in Britain,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cars.uk.msn.com/features/2013-sunday-times-motoring-rich-list?page=25 |title=Car and motoring stories and photos - Features - MSN Cars |publisher=Cars.uk.msn.com |date=27 January 2015 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213205359/http://cars.uk.msn.com/features/2013-sunday-times-motoring-rich-list?page=25 |archive-date=13 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Times article\">{{cite web |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6860211.ece |title=?? |publisher=Timesonline.co.uk |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604163017/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6860211.ece |archive-date=4 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }} {{subscription required|date=September 2015}}</ref> although he claims to take [[Transport in London|public transport in London]] \"like everybody else\".<ref name=\"economictimes.indiatimes.com\"/> Since the 1960s he has lived in [[Portland Place]], in [[central London]].<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/> He and his family own a dozen flats in the block, each one worth close to a million pounds.<ref name=\"Times article\"/> He also has a {{convert|250|acre|km2|adj=on}} country estate, in [[Beaconsfield, Buckinghamshire]].<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\">{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Barbara |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1256036/How-Sarah-Brown-charmed-Labour-Ashcroft.html |title=How Sarah Brown charmed the 'Labour Ashcroft' &#124; Daily Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date=7 March 2010 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120730231409/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1256036/How-Sarah-Brown-charmed-Labour-Ashcroft.html |archive-date=30 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHis son [[Angad Paul]], CEO of [[Caparo plc]], died after falling from his Marylebone penthouse flat on 8 November 2015. A police statement stated they considered there to be no suspicious circumstances.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34765572 article] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109110134/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34765572 |date=9 November 2015 }} published by [[British Broadcasting Corporation]]. Retrieved 9 November 2015</ref><ref>V. Ward - [http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/son-of-lord-paul-the-billionaire-steel-magnate-plunges-to-his-death-as-the-family-business-collapses/ar-CC87M8?li=AAaeUIW&ocid=U348DHPa article] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208110837/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/son-of-lord-paul-the-billionaire-steel-magnate-plunges-to-his-death-as-the-family-business-collapses/ar-CC87M8?li=AAaeUIW&ocid=U348DHPa |date=8 December 2015 }} on [[MSN|msn]] published by [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]. Retrieved 9 November 2015</ref>\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|escutcheon = Azure on each of three piles rayonny Or one issuing from the dexter and one from the sinister a pile Gules.\n|crest = Issuing from a lotus Or a girl child proper vested Azure holding aloft in the dexter hand a dove wings elevated Argent.\n|supporters = On either side an Indian elephant Azure tusked unguled and grasping with the trunk a torch enflamed Or.\n|motto = Truth, Freedom And Compassion <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=2000}}</ref>}}\n\n==Publications==\n*''Beyond Boundaries: A Memoir'', [[Penguin Books]], 1998, {{ISBN|9780140272291}}\n*''Indira Gandhi'', [[Heron Press]], 1984 \u2013 a biography of [[Indira Gandhi]], {{ISBN|9780947728182}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.caparo.com/en-gb/about/board-member-profile.aspx?bmid=0a2157f3-539b-4178-bd3d-67bbfabcfac9 Official brief biography] on the Caparo website\n* [http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/mehdi-hasan/2010/10/lord-paul-house-committee Newstatesman.com]\n\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 1980\u201389}}\n{{University of Westminster}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paul, Swraj, Baron}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:British billionaires]]\n[[Category:British people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:British Hindus]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Forman Christian College alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:British biographers]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in social work]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of West London]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Westminster]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Wolverhampton]]\n[[Category:People from Jalandhar]]\n[[Category:Indian peers]]\n[[Category:People with non-domiciled status in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n[[Category:British memoirists]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name               = The Lord Paul\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]]\n| image              = Official portrait of Lord Paul.jpg\n| birth_name         = Swraj Paul\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1931|02|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Jalandhar]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab Province]], [[British India]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = London, UK\n| nationality        = [[Indian British]]\n| citizenship        = British\n| education          = Doaba College Jalandhar, Punjab; \n[[Forman Christian College]], Lahore; \n[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n| occupation         = Businessman\n| known_for          = \n| net_worth          = \u00a32 billion<ref name=BirminghamPost>{{cite web|title=Birmingham Post Rich List 2014: No.2 - Lord Paul of Marylebone and family (\u00a32bn)|url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/manufacturing/birmingham-post-rich-list-2014-6530631|website=Birmingham Post|access-date=8 November 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141108144641/http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/manufacturing/birmingham-post-rich-list-2014-6530631|archive-date=8 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| party              = Independent\n| spouse             = \n| children           = 4, including [[Angad Paul]] (deceased)\n| website            = \n}}\n \n'''Swraj Paul, Baron Paul''', [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] (born 18 February 1931) is an [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Indian-born]], British-based business magnate and philanthropist.  In 1996 he was appointed a [[life peer]] by Conservative Prime Minister John Major,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Interview: Swraj Paul, Engineering magnate puts his faith in British steeliness|url = https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/21/swraj-paul-caparo-london-zoo|website = the Guardian|access-date = 6 October 2015|first = Abhinav|last = Ramnarayan|url-status = live|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151006181444/http://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/21/swraj-paul-caparo-london-zoo|archive-date = 6 October 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref> and sits in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[crossbencher]] with the title '''Baron Paul''', of [[Marylebone]], in the [[City of Westminster]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{London Gazette |issue=54553 |date=16 October 1996 |page=13737}}</ref> In December 2008 he was appointed [[deputy speaker]] [[Lord Speaker|of the Lords]]; in October 2009 he was [[List of current members of the British Privy Council|appointed to]] [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|the Privy Council.]] <ref name=\"TheyWorkForYou\">{{Cite web|title = TheyWorkForYou|url = https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/13603/lord_paul|website = www.theyworkforyou.com|access-date = 8 October 2015|url-status = live|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150910031237/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/13603/lord_paul|archive-date = 10 September 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAccording to his official biography, Swraj Paul was born in [[Jalandhar]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab Province]] in 1931, in what was then [[British India]].  His father Payare Lal ran a small [[foundry]], making steel buckets and farming equipment. His mother's name was Mongwati. The site of his childhood home is now [[Apeejay School]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caparo.com/en-gb/about/board-member-profile.aspx?bmid=0a2157f3-539b-4178-bd3d-67bbfabcfac9 |title=Caparo \u2014 Caparo is a global group wholly owned and managed by the Paul family. Caparo is chaired by Lord Paul of Marylebone |publisher=Caparo.com |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920092323/http://www.caparo.com/en-gb/about/board-member-profile.aspx?bmid=0a2157f3-539b-4178-bd3d-67bbfabcfac9 |archive-date=20 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSwraj Paul completed his [[high school]] education at Labbu Ram Doaba School. Paul was educated at [[Forman Christian College]] in [[Lahore]], and [[Doaba College]] in [[Jalandhar]]. He went to the United States to study [[mechanical engineering]], obtaining BSc, MSc and MechE degrees from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">{{cite web |author=Abhinav Ramnarayan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/21/swraj-paul-caparo-london-zoo |title=Interview: Swraj Paul, Engineering magnate puts his faith in British steeliness &#124; Business |publisher=The Guardian |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006181444/http://www.theguardian.com/business/2008/nov/21/swraj-paul-caparo-london-zoo |archive-date=6 October 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Business career ==\nAfter leaving MIT, he returned to India to work for the family business, Apeejay Group, which was founded by his father, and was, at the time, managed by his two older brothers, Stya Paul and Jit Paul.\n\n===Caparo Group ===\nIn 1966 he relocated to the United Kingdom to get medical treatment for his young daughter, who had [[leukaemia]].<ref name=\"Asian Woman Awards website\">[http://www.theasianwomanawards.com/lifetimeach-2008.html]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009125148/http://www.theasianwomanawards.com/lifetimeach-2008.html|date=9 October 2011}}</ref> He spent a year grieving her death, after which he founded Natural Gas Tubes.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/> Starting with one steel unit, he went on to acquire more. This led to his founding the [[Caparo plc|Caparo Group]] in 1968, which became one of the UK\u2019s largest steel conversion and distribution businesses, manufacturing an extensive range of structural steels, precision tube, spirally welded tube, special bar qualities, industrial wires, cold rolled strip and spring steel strip. Lord Paul stepped down from the management of the Caparo Group in 1996.<ref name=\"economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/features/the-global-indian-takeover/Swraj-Paul-Humane-capital/articleshow/2618496.cms |title=Swraj Paul: Humane capital - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=13 December 2007 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/features/the-global-indian-takeover/Swraj-Paul-Humane-capital/articleshow/2618496.cms |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nUp until Autumn 2015, Caparo employed over 10,000 people across North America, Europe, India and, the Middle East. In October 2015, 16 of the 20 limited companies that formed most of Caparo Group UK collapsed into administration,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34574982 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-11-09 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025011414/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34574982 |archive-date=25 October 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and on 8 November his son [[Angad Paul]], the Group's CEO, died in an apparent suicide from his eighth-floor penthouse flat.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34765572 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-11-09 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109110134/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34765572 |archive-date=9 November 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Public role and philanthropy ==\nLord Paul has held many public positions. In 2006, as part of his parliamentary work, he made a declaration of interest;<ref name=\"publications.parliament.uk\"/> he was involved with more than a dozen organisations outside his family business and foundation. This [[Foundation (nonprofit)#United Kingdom|foundation]], named in memory of his daughter,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nriinternet.com/NRIcharity/UK/Ambika_Paul_Foundation/index.htm |title=The Ambika Paul Foundation, UK- in memory of Lord Paul's daughter Ambika |publisher=Nriinternet.com |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083412/http://www.nriinternet.com/NRIcharity/UK/Ambika_Paul_Foundation/index.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> channels profits from Caparo India into charitable endeavours.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caparo.co.in/about_corporate_responsibility.html |title=Caparo |publisher=Caparo |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928041031/http://www.caparo.co.in/about_corporate_responsibility.html |archive-date=28 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> For example, Paul is an honorary patron of the [[Zoological Society of London]] and has funded major projects at the [[Regent's Park]] site, including the Ambika Paul [[children's zoo]].<ref>[http://www.zsl.org/zsl-london-zoo/news/childrens-zoo-at-london-zoo,200,NS.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420164941/http://www.zsl.org/zsl-london-zoo/news/childrens-zoo-at-london-zoo,200,NS.html|date=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nThe Foundation has established the Ambika Paul School of Technology in Jalandhar, India.\n\nLord Paul held the [[Pro-Chancellor]]ship of [[Thames Valley University]] in 1997, and Chancellorship in 1998.\n\nHe has been the [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Wolverhampton]] since 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wlv.ac.uk/Default.aspx?page=7220 |title=Chancellor - University of Wolverhampton |publisher=Wlv.ac.uk |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906121229/https://www.wlv.ac.uk/Default.aspx?page=7220 |archive-date=6 September 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2010 the [[Student union building|student union centre]] was renamed \"The Ambika Paul Student Union Centre\", following his donation towards its refurbishment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wlv.ac.uk/default.aspx?page=25362 |title=November 2010 - New Student Union Centre opened by Chancellor - University of Wolverhampton |publisher=Wlv.ac.uk |date=26 November 2010 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207080452/http://www.wlv.ac.uk/default.aspx?page=25362 |archive-date=7 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2015 he gave, through his family foundation, \u00a31 million, the largest single donation in the university's history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolverhampton University receives \u00a31m - the biggest donation in its history|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2015/04/12/wolverhampton-university-receives-1m-the-biggest-donation-in-its-history/|access-date=29 November 2017|publisher=Express and Star|date=12 April 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034239/https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2015/04/12/wolverhampton-university-receives-1m-the-biggest-donation-in-its-history/|archive-date=1 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLord Paul was Chancellor of [[University of Westminster]],<ref name=\"publications.parliament.uk\">{{cite web |author=The Committee Office, House of Lords |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/ldselect/ldeconaf/204/20409.htm |title=House of Lords - Economic Affairs - Sixth Report |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924145856/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/ldselect/ldeconaf/204/20409.htm |archive-date=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wmin.ac.uk/page-16504 |title=Shaping the Future - Shaping the future - University of Westminster, London |publisher=Wmin.ac.uk |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924155845/http://www.wmin.ac.uk/page-16504 |archive-date=24 September 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> from 2006 to 2014; his foundation donated \u00a3300,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charity-commission.gov.uk/registeredcharities/ScannedAccounts/Ends27/0000276127_ac_20080430_e_c.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220012008/http://www.charity-commission.gov.uk/registeredcharities/ScannedAccounts/Ends27/0000276127_ac_20080430_e_c.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=20 February 2009|title=Wayback Machine|author=|date=20 February 2009|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> to establish the Ambika P3 event and exhibition space.\n\nHe sat on [[MIT]]'s Mechanical Engineering Visiting Committee<!-- The MIT site for that committee ([http://web.mit.edu/corporation/visiting/mechanical-engineering.html here]) makes no mention of him, but is only \"for this year\", not historic. --> between 1998 and 2001, when he established the Ambika Paul Mezzanine and Study Space, and the Swraj Paul Scholarship fund for undergraduate and graduate students.\n\nLord Paul is a member of the President's Cabinet for [[Chapman University]] in [[Orange, California]].<ref>[https://www.chapman.edu/about/administration/trustees/members.aspx] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229093916/https://www.chapman.edu/about/administration/trustees/members.aspx|date=29 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===International relations===\nLord Paul has taken an interest in international relations. He was appointed by the government to act as an ambassador for British business from 1998 \u20132010.<ref>{{cite web |author=The Committee Office, House of Lords |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200203/ldselect/ldeconaf/5/510.htm |title=House of Lords - Economic Affairs - First Report |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=17 January 2003 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924145635/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200203/ldselect/ldeconaf/5/510.htm |archive-date=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was a member of the [[Foreign Policy Centre]] Advisory Council.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fpc.org.uk/fsblob/240.pdf |format=PDF |title=The Foreign Policy Centre : China has discovered its own economic consensus |author=Joshua Cooper Ramo |publisher=Fpc.org.uk |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303235022/http://fpc.org.uk/fsblob/240.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He contested for the chairmanship of the [[Commonwealth Parliamentary Association]], with an agenda to reduce the gap between the West and [[Eastern world|the East]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}. Lord Paul was Co-Chairman of the Indo-British Roundtable from 2000\u20132005.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/Indo-UK-ties-better-than-before-Lord-Paul/articleshow/45852028.cms |title=Indo-UK ties better than before: Lord Paul - The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=9 May 2003 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/Indo-UK-ties-better-than-before-Lord-Paul/articleshow/45852028.cms |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nriinternet.com/NRIpoliticians/UK/A_Z/S/Lord%20Swraj_files/2005/020605_StepDown.htm |title=Lord Paul to step down as Co-Chairman of India-UK Round Table |publisher=Nriinternet.com |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083407/http://www.nriinternet.com/NRIpoliticians/UK/A_Z/S/Lord%20Swraj_files/2005/020605_StepDown.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was a member of Panel 2000, an appointment by the Prime Minister to re-brand Britain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hansard - written answers|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200001/cmhansrd/vo001212/text/01212w13.htm|website=UK Parliament|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222010446/http://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200001/cmhansrd/vo001212/text/01212w13.htm/|archive-date=22 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===UK politics===\nLord Paul has donated \u00a3500,000 to the Labour Party,<ref>{{cite web |author=Allegra Stratton |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/11/lord-paul-denies-rule-breaking |title=MPs expenses: Lord Paul denies he broke rules on residence allowance &#124; Politics |publisher=The Guardian |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004123529/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/11/lord-paul-denies-rule-breaking |archive-date=4 October 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> being the largest donor to [[2007 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|Gordon Brown's leadership campaign]]<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\" /> and offering in 2007 to give \"as much as [he] can afford\" in the case of an early election.<ref>{{cite web |last=Carlin |first=Brendan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1560325/Donors-pledge-fuels-early-election-rumours.html |title=Donor's pledge fuels early election rumours |publisher=The Daily Telegraph |date=15 August 2007 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925144141/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1560325/Donors-pledge-fuels-early-election-rumours.html |archive-date=25 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He is also close to the former UK Prime Minister's wife, [[Sarah Jane Brown|Sarah Brown]],<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/indians-abroad/Lord-Swaraj-Pauls-son-weds-at-London-Zoo/articleshow/880764.cms |title=Lord Swaraj Paul's son weds at London Zoo - The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=11 October 2004 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/indians-abroad/Lord-Swaraj-Pauls-son-weds-at-London-Zoo/articleshow/880764.cms |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> for whom he shows paternal concern<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\" /> Lord Paul was chairman and trustee of Theirworld and chairman Theirworld Projects Ltd (formerly PiggyBankKids) from 2002 to 2015; the charity was founded by Sarah Brown.<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://theirworld.org/about/history|website=Theirworld|access-date=29 November 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005143434/http://theirworld.org/about/history|archive-date=5 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe was the first [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|person of Indian origin]] to hold the post of [[deputy speaker]] [[Lord Speaker|of the House of Lords]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7776220.stm |title=South Asia &#124; UK deputy Speaker is Indian-born |publisher=BBC News |date=10 December 2008 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723190651/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7776220.stm |archive-date=23 July 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> one of twelve people in that post.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/the-global-indian-takeover/Lord-Paul-Speaking-his-mind/articleshow/3854513.cms |title=Lord Paul: Speaking his mind - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=18 December 2008 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/the-global-indian-takeover/Lord-Paul-Speaking-his-mind/articleshow/3854513.cms |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was sworn of the [[Privy Council]] on 15 October 2009.<ref>[http://www.privy-council.org.uk/output/page76.asp#p]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119075331/http://www.privy-council.org.uk/output/page76.asp#p|date=19 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"O15Oct09\">[http://www.privy-council.org.uk/files/word/October%2015th%202009.doc]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611043731/http://www.privy-council.org.uk/files/word/October%2015th%202009.doc|date=11 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nLord Paul was involved with the [[2012 Summer Olympics|London Olympics]] from its inception; he was a member of the board responsible for the 2005 submission of the [[London bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics|bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics]]. He travelled to Singapore as part of the bidding team that successfully persuaded the [[International Olympic Committee]] to award the games to London for 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-07-27/news/32889714_1_london-olympics-london-development-agency-mayor-ken-livingstone|title=London Olympics 2012: NRI Lord Swraj Paul played vital role in bidding and holding the Games - timesofindia-economictimes|author=|date=|publisher=Articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>  <!-- These claims are based on the ''Economic Times'' article, which incorrectly calls the IOC the \"International Olympic Association\". --> He chaired the Olympic Delivery Committee, part of the [[London Development Agency]], with the job of obtaining the land on which to build the new venues, and delivering the land on time and on budget. (See [[Legacy of the 2012 Summer Olympics]].){{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nLord Paul has received various awards and honours including 15 honorary degrees from universities in the UK, US, India, Russia and Switzerland.  In 1983 he was awarded the [[Padma Bhushan]], by [[Indira Gandhi]], the [[Prime Minister of India]],<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web |url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |access-date=21 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archive-date=15 November 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> and the [[Bharat Gaurav]] award by the [[Indian Merchants' Chamber]]. Freedom of the City of London, 1998; Asian Business Awards, Lifetime Achievement Award, 2008; Donald C. Burnham Manufacturing Management Award, Society of Manufacturing Engineers, USA, 1995; First Asian of the Year Award, Asian Who's Who, 1987; \nAsian Woman Magazine Lifetime Achievement Award, 2008.<ref name=\"Asian Woman Awards website\"/> PowerBrands Hall of Fame nominated him Global Indian of the Year, 2011.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}  Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Corporate Leadership Award, 1989.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nHe was awarded \"International Indian of Decade\" for his outstanding achievements in the fields of industry, education and philanthropy at the 20th anniversary of the publication of India Link International, a monthly magazine on 15 November 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/article2712301.ece |title=Swraj Paul awarded lifetime achievement prize |publisher=The Hindu |date=13 December 2011 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/article2712301.ece |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Lord Paul was presented with a Lifetime Achievement Award by the Black Country Asian Business Association for his \"outstanding achievements in the fields of industry, education and philanthropy\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indolink.com/displayArticleS.php?id=111513103008 |title=Indian Diaspora (NRI) News: 'International Indian Of The Decade' Award Given To Lord Paul |publisher=INDOlink |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924034533/http://www.indolink.com/displayArticleS.php?id=111513103008 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2014, he received a further Lifetime Achievement Award in recognition of his work in promoting India-UK educational ties from the Global Skill Tree consortium,an India Based think tank, which hopes to promote India as a global hub of international education through its \"Great Place to Study \u2013 India\" initiative.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-06-25/news/50856012_1_lord-paul-sushma-berlia-indian |title=Swraj Paul honoured for promoting India-UK educational ties - timesofindia-economictimes |publisher=Articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Lord Paul was given the \"International Icon of the Decade Award\" by the World Consulting Research Corporation at its Global Indian Excellence Summit in London,  in recognition of \"his outstanding achievements in the fields of manufacturing, education and philanthropy\".<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/states/lord-swraj-paul-hits-out-at-foreign-countries-for-unsolicited-advice/article6237079.ece |title=Lord Swraj Paul hits out at foreign countries for unsolicited advice &#124; Business Line |publisher=Thehindubusinessline.com |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Lord Paul received two awards during a trip to India: the IOD Golden Peacock Award For Lifetime Achievement in Business Leadership and the Global Punjabi Society Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianage.com/metros/delhi/080418/golden-peacock-awarded-to-industrialist-swraj-paul.html|title=Golden Peacock awarded to industrialist Swraj Lord Paul|author=|date=8 April 2018|website=The Asian Age|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> In May 2018, Lord Paul was given the Int+ WCRC International Iconic Leader Award for Lifetime Achievement, at the UK & Asia Business Awards ceremony in London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/nris-in-news/nri-industrialist-swraj-paul-wins-lifetime-achievement-award-in-uk/articleshow/64225278.cms|title=NRI industrialist Swraj Paul wins lifetime achievement award in UK|date=2018-05-18|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref> In October 2018, he was awarded the Mahatma Gandhi Honour by the NRI Institute in celebration of their 30th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/swraj-paul-gets-mahatma-gandhi-honour-in-uk-for-underlining-work-of-nris-118103101532_1.html|title=Swraj Paul gets Mahatma Gandhi Honour in UK for underlining work of NRIs|first=Press Trust of|last=India|date=31 October 2018|publisher=|accessdate=22 January 2019|via=Business Standard}}</ref> In June 2019, he was awarded an honorary scholarship at the London Zoological Society.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn October 2009  ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' reported that Lord Paul had been unable satisfactorily to explain claiming expenses of \u00a338,000 for the period January 2005 to July 2006. Lord Paul immediately requested the Clerk of the Parliaments to investigate his expenses at the same time repaying,  \u00a341,982 instead of \u00a326,988 \u2013 \u00a315,000, more than the House of Lords would have requested at the conclusion of their investigation. A refund of the difference was never issued by the House of Lords. The [[Metropolitan Police]] opened an investigation concerning these expense claims,<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7017838.ece  \"Three more peers face charges\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604200455/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7017838.ece |date=4 June 2011 }} ''The Sunday Times'' 7 February 2010</ref> but by the end of February 2010 concluded there was no case.  Lord Paul appeared before various committees for Lord's Conduct with ultimately the Privileges Committee concluding that Lord Paul had not acted dishonestly or in bad faith.  They did determine however that he had been negligent and acted in ignorance and that his actions did render him liable to sanction by the House.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=The Committee Office, House of Lords |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201011/ldselect/ldprivi/37/3703.htm |title=House of Lords - The Conduct of Lord Paul - Privileges and Conduct Committee |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924150453/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201011/ldselect/ldprivi/37/3703.htm |archive-date=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lord Paul's suspension was for four months.  Lord Paul completely disagreed with their finding, calling it \"unreasonable.\" Lord Paul gave a  [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201011/ldhansrd/text/110622-0003.htm#11062274000031<nowiki/> Speech] in the House of Lords in June 2011 calling for reform and revision of the structure of the constitution.\n\nPaul tendered his resignation as Deputy Speaker to the Lord Speaker on 1 November 2010. His letter, printed in ''[[The House Magazine]]'' a week later, expressed his reservations about the process, calling it \"a sad saga for parliamentary democracy \u2013 an unfortunate series of events having evidently been inspired by the electoral politics of the media\". He has spoken on this topic many times since the expenses scandal initially made news,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/ColumnsOthers/A-trial-by-rumour/Article1-634780.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130629091529/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/ColumnsOthers/A-trial-by-rumour/Article1-634780.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 June 2013 |title=A trial by rumour |publisher=Hindustantimes.com |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 }}</ref> and maintains that no wrongdoing had occurred in his case.<ref>{{cite web |author=Simon Hattenstone |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/11/mps-expenses-scandal-what-next |title=MPs' expenses scandal: what happened next? &#124; Politics |publisher=The Guardian |date= |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929141107/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2012/may/11/mps-expenses-scandal-what-next |archive-date=29 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{cite web |last=McDonagh |first=Siobhain |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/mehdi-hasan/2010/03/160-status-lord-peer-tory |title=Exclusive: Lord Paul to end his non-domiciled tax status |publisher=Newstatesman.com |date=9 March 2010 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114215037/http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/mehdi-hasan/2010/03/160-status-lord-peer-tory |archive-date=14 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLord Paul is on the [[Sunday Times Rich List]] as the 38th richest person in Britain,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cars.uk.msn.com/features/2013-sunday-times-motoring-rich-list?page=25 |title=Car and motoring stories and photos - Features - MSN Cars |publisher=Cars.uk.msn.com |date=27 January 2015 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213205359/http://cars.uk.msn.com/features/2013-sunday-times-motoring-rich-list?page=25 |archive-date=13 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Times article\">{{cite web |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6860211.ece |title=?? |publisher=Timesonline.co.uk |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604163017/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6860211.ece |archive-date=4 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }} {{subscription required|date=September 2015}}</ref> although he claims to take [[Transport in London|public transport in London]] \"like everybody else\".<ref name=\"economictimes.indiatimes.com\"/> Since the 1960s he has lived in [[Portland Place]], in [[central London]].<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/> He and his family own a dozen flats in the block, each one worth close to a million pounds.<ref name=\"Times article\"/> He also has a {{convert|250|acre|km2|adj=on}} country estate, in [[Beaconsfield, Buckinghamshire]].<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\">{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Barbara |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1256036/How-Sarah-Brown-charmed-Labour-Ashcroft.html |title=How Sarah Brown charmed the 'Labour Ashcroft' &#124; Daily Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date=7 March 2010 |access-date=21 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120730231409/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1256036/How-Sarah-Brown-charmed-Labour-Ashcroft.html |archive-date=30 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHis son [[Angad Paul]], CEO of [[Caparo plc]], died after falling from his Marylebone penthouse flat on 8 November 2015. A police statement stated they considered there to be no suspicious circumstances.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34765572 article] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109110134/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34765572 |date=9 November 2015 }} published by [[British Broadcasting Corporation]]. Retrieved 9 November 2015</ref><ref>V. Ward - [http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/son-of-lord-paul-the-billionaire-steel-magnate-plunges-to-his-death-as-the-family-business-collapses/ar-CC87M8?li=AAaeUIW&ocid=U348DHPa article] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208110837/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/son-of-lord-paul-the-billionaire-steel-magnate-plunges-to-his-death-as-the-family-business-collapses/ar-CC87M8?li=AAaeUIW&ocid=U348DHPa |date=8 December 2015 }} on [[MSN|msn]] published by [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]. Retrieved 9 November 2015</ref>\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|escutcheon = Azure on each of three piles rayonny Or one issuing from the dexter and one from the sinister a pile Gules.\n|crest = Issuing from a lotus Or a girl child proper vested Azure holding aloft in the dexter hand a dove wings elevated Argent.\n|supporters = On either side an Indian elephant Azure tusked unguled and grasping with the trunk a torch enflamed Or.\n|motto = Truth, Freedom And Compassion <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=2000}}</ref>}}\n\n==Publications==\n*''Beyond Boundaries: A Memoir'', [[Penguin Books]], 1998, {{ISBN|9780140272291}}\n*''Indira Gandhi'', [[Heron Press]], 1984 \u2013 a biography of [[Indira Gandhi]], {{ISBN|9780947728182}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.caparo.com/en-gb/about/board-member-profile.aspx?bmid=0a2157f3-539b-4178-bd3d-67bbfabcfac9 Official brief biography] on the Caparo website\n* [http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/mehdi-hasan/2010/10/lord-paul-house-committee Newstatesman.com]\n\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 1980\u201389}}\n{{University of Westminster}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paul, Swraj, Baron}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:British billionaires]]\n[[Category:British people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:British Hindus]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople of 