{"title_page": "Iain McNicol", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name        = The Lord McNicol of West Kilbride\n|image       = Official portrait of Lord McNicol of West Kilbride crop 2.jpg\n|caption     = McNicol in 2019\n|office      = [[General Secretary of the Labour Party]]\n|leader      = [[Ed Miliband]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start  = 19 July 2011\n|term_end    = 20 March 2018\n|predecessor = [[Ray Collins, Baron Collins of Highbury|Ray Collins]]\n|successor   = [[Jennie Formby]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=y|1969|8|17}}\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|spouse      = \n|children    = 2\n|alma_mater  = [[Abertay University]]\n}}\n'''Iain Mackenzie McNicol, Baron McNicol of West Kilbride''' (born 17 August 1969) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician and [[trade union]]ist. From 2011 to 2018 he was [[General Secretary of the Labour Party]], the most senior employee of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"Stewart\">{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Heather|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/feb/23/labour-general-secretary-stands-down-from-position|title=Labour party general secretary stands down from position|work=The Guardian|date=23 February 2018|accessdate=23 February 2018}}</ref> Previously he was National Political Officer of the [[GMB Union]], and has a long history of organising in both the Labour Party and the [[trade unions in the United Kingdom|trade union movement]].<ref name=bbc-20110719>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-14204368 |title=Iain McNicol named as new Labour general secretary |publisher=BBC |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nMcNicol began his involvement in political organising as president of the Student Union at [[Dundee Institute of Technology]] in 1991.<ref name=observer-20160709>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/09/labour-leaders-mp-collision-course-partys-soul-election-jeremy-corbyn |title=Labour leader and MPs set on collision course in a battle for party's soul |author=Daniel Boffey |newspaper=The Observer |date=9 July 2016 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe then moved to the Labour Party, first in an elected role as National Campaigns and Membership Officer for [[Labour Students]],<ref name=progress-20110720>{{cite news |url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2011/07/20/labours-new-general-secretary/ |title=Labour 's new general secretary |author=Luke Akehurst |publisher=Progress Online |date=20 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> and then variously as an organiser and agent in south and east England from 1994 to 1997.<ref name=progress-20110720/><ref name=progress-20120525>{{cite news |url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2012/05/25/changing-to-win/ |title=Changing to win |author=Iain McNicol |publisher=Progress Online |date=25 May 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=ph-20120927>{{cite news |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/social-affairs/politics/house/67381/street-fighting-man |title=Street Fighting Man |author=Paul Waugh, Sam Macrory |website=PoliticsHome |date=27 September 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[1997 United Kingdom general election]] at which Labour returned to office, McNicol served as a research, organisation, and political officer with the [[GMB Union]], and in 1998 he was appointed as a regional organiser for its Southern Region.<ref name=hp-20110726>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2011/07/26/labours-new-general-secre_n_908642.html |title=Labour's New General Secretary: His Dramatic Win And Why He Is The Insurgency Candidate |author=Dina Rickman |publisher=Huffington Post |date=26 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> McNicol continued in that role until 2004, when he was promoted to National Political Officer. He served in that capacity through to 2011, coordinating the political strategy of the union and representing its members\u2019 interests in both the public and private sector.<ref name=hp-20110726/><ref name=newstatesman-20110719>{{cite news |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-staggers/2011/07/labour-party-mcnicol-general |title=Iain McNicol is the right man for the job |author=Will Straw |newspaper=New Statesman |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 July 2011, Labour's [[National Executive Committee]] selected McNicol to become the party's next General Secretary under leader [[Ed Miliband]].<ref name=bbc-20110719 />\n\nMcNicol's intention to stand down as General Secretary of the Labour Party was announced on 23 February 2018.<ref name=\"Stewart\"/> On 20 March 2018 he was succeeded by [[Jennie Formby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/93790/jennie-formby-appointed-labour-general-secretary|title=Jennie Formby appointed Labour general secretary in huge boost for Jeremy Corbyn|first=|last=PoliticsHome.com|date=20 March 2018|publisher=|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 2018, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron McNicol of West Kilbride''', ''of West Kilbride in the County of Ayrshire''.<ref name=ph-20180518>{{cite news |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/constitution/house-lords-reform/news/95306/former-labour-general-secretary-iain-mcnicol |title=Former Labour general secretary Iain McNicol given peerage by Jeremy Corbyn |last=Schofield |first=Kevin |website=PoliticsHome |date=18 May 2018 |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62337|date=27 June 2018|page=11404}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019 [[Jon Lansman]] the founder of [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]] writing in the [[LabourList]] blog accused McNicol and his team of delaying action on handling [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism cases]] while he was General Secretary, and allowing a backlog of cases to build up that would damage the party and [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s leadership.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jeremy Corbyn pushed for action on antisemitism \u2013 but was held back by bureaucracy |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/05/jeremy-corbyn-pushed-for-action-on-antisemitism-but-was-held-back-by-bureaucracy/ |publisher=Labourlist |accessdate=12 July 2019 |date=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2016 Labour Party leadership election==\nIn June and July 2016, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported that the office of the Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] believed that McNicol tried to prevent Corbyn from attending a key [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC) meeting, and was alleged to be complicit in trying to exclude Corbyn from entering the second leadership election. It reported that senior figures in the trade union movement were discussing replacement options for McNicol in his General Secretary role.<ref name=ft-20160713>{{cite news |url=https://next.ft.com/content/b05f39a2-490b-11e6-b387-64ab0a67014c |title=Labour's McNicol targeted over role in coup |author=Jim Pickard |newspaper=Financial Times |date=13 July 2016 |accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20160725>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/25/labour-leadership-contest-legal-documents-reveal-depth-of-split/ |title=Labour leadership contest: Legal documents reveal depth of split between Jeremy Corbyn and party 's general secretary |author=Ben Riley-Smith |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=25 July 2016 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nA civil [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] legal challenge was brought by Labour donor and former parliamentary candidate [[Michael Foster (agent)|Michael Foster]], to contest the decision to allow Corbyn to be a candidate without having to secure any nominations from Labour MPs. The case went to court on 26 July 2016. McNicol was the first defendant on behalf of the members of the Labour Party. Corbyn applied to the court, and was accepted, to be a second defendant with his own legal team as Corbyn was \"particularly affected and particularly interested in the proper construction of the rules\" and that McNicol was \"being expected to vigorously defend a position which he regarded as incorrect prior to the NEC decision\".<ref name=telegraph-20160725/><ref name=guardian-20160720>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/20/jeremy-corbyn-wins-right-to-be-defendant-in-leadership-court-case |title=Jeremy Corbyn wins right to be defendant in leadership court case |author=Jessica Elgot |newspaper=The Guardian |date=20 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> The High Court ruled that the NEC's decision that Corbyn should automatically be on the ballot was a correct interpretation of the [[Labour Party Rule Book]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/28/jeremy-corbyn-fights-off-court-challenge-labour-leadership-ballot|title=Jeremy Corbyn fights off court challenge over Labour leadership ballot|newspaper=The Guardian |last1=Walker|first1=Peter |last2=Syal|first2=Rajeev |last3=Mason|first3=Rowena |date=28 July 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=highcourt-20160728>>{{cite report |url=https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/judgment-foster-v-mcnicol-and-corbyn-20160728.pdf |title=Between: MICHAEL FOSTER and IAIN McNICOL (1) (sued on behalf of all other members of the Labour Party except the Claimant and the Second Defendant) and THE RT HON JEREMY CORBYN MP (2) |author=Mr Justice Foskett |publisher=Royal Courts of Justice id&#61;[2016] EWHC 1966 (QB) Case HQ16X02502 |date=28 July 2016 |accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAn additional [[Evangelou v McNicol|court case]] was brought against McNicol in August 2016 regarding the NEC's decision to disallow party members who had joined after 12 January 2016 from voting in the leadership election. The claimants won their case in the High Court, but this decision was overturned on [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|appeal]].<ref>BBC - [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/37077672 \"Labour leadership: Members drop voting legal challenge\"] 14 August 2016</ref> In late September, it was reported that a Labour party member was lodging a claim at the County Court in response to her suspension by the NEC and that it would cite McNicol as claimant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecanary.co/2016/09/21/latest-twist-labour-purge-truly-astonishing-images/|title=The latest twist in the Labour 'purge' is truly astonishing [IMAGES]|date=2016-09-21|website=The Canary|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMcNicol is married and has a son and daughter.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} He holds a black belt in [[karate]].<ref name=ph-20120927/> He attended Ardrossan Academy.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://labourlist.org/2012/07/iain-mcnicol-q-a/ Iain McNicol \u2013 Q & A], [[LabourList]], 19 July 2012\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ray Collins, Baron Collins of Highbury|Ray Collins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[General Secretary of the Labour Party]]|years=2011\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jennie Formby]]}} \n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baron McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown|The Lord McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron McNicol of West Kilbride'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Alan Haselhurst|The Lord Haselhurst]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Labour Party}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United Kingdom|Organised labour}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McNicol, Iain}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Abertay Dundee]]\n[[Category:British trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Jeremy Corbyn]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name        = The Lord McNicol of West Kilbride\n|image       = Official portrait of Lord McNicol of West Kilbride crop 2.jpg\n|caption     = McNicol in 2019\n|office      = [[General Secretary of the Labour Party]]\n|leader      = [[Ed Miliband]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start  = 19 July 2011\n|term_end    = 20 March 2018\n|predecessor = [[Ray Collins, Baron Collins of Highbury|Ray Collins]]\n|successor   = [[Jennie Formby]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=y|1969|8|17}}\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|spouse      = \n|children    = 2\n|alma_mater  = [[Abertay University]]\n}}\n'''Iain Mackenzie McNicol, Baron McNicol of West Kilbride''' (born 17 August 1969) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician and [[trade union]]ist. From 2011 to 2018 he was [[General Secretary of the Labour Party]], the most senior employee of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"Stewart\">{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Heather|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/feb/23/labour-general-secretary-stands-down-from-position|title=Labour party general secretary stands down from position|work=The Guardian|date=23 February 2018|accessdate=23 February 2018}}</ref> Previously he was National Political Officer of the [[GMB Union]], and has a long history of organising in both the Labour Party and the [[trade unions in the United Kingdom|trade union movement]].<ref name=bbc-20110719>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-14204368 |title=Iain McNicol named as new Labour general secretary |publisher=BBC |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nMcNicol began his involvement in political organising as president of the Student Union at [[Dundee Institute of Technology]] in 1991.<ref name=observer-20160709>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/09/labour-leaders-mp-collision-course-partys-soul-election-jeremy-corbyn |title=Labour leader and MPs set on collision course in a battle for party's soul |author=Daniel Boffey |newspaper=The Observer |date=9 July 2016 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe then moved to the Labour Party, first in an elected role as National Campaigns and Membership Officer for [[Labour Students]],<ref name=progress-20110720>{{cite news |url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2011/07/20/labours-new-general-secretary/ |title=Labour 's new general secretary |author=Luke Akehurst |publisher=Progress Online |date=20 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> and then variously as an organiser and agent in south and east England from 1994 to 1997.<ref name=progress-20110720/><ref name=progress-20120525>{{cite news |url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2012/05/25/changing-to-win/ |title=Changing to win |author=Iain McNicol |publisher=Progress Online |date=25 May 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=ph-20120927>{{cite news |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/social-affairs/politics/house/67381/street-fighting-man |title=Street Fighting Man |author=Paul Waugh, Sam Macrory |website=PoliticsHome |date=27 September 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[1997 United Kingdom general election]] at which Labour returned to office, McNicol served as a research, organisation, and political officer with the [[GMB Union]], and in 1998 he was appointed as a regional organiser for its Southern Region.<ref name=hp-20110726>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2011/07/26/labours-new-general-secre_n_908642.html |title=Labour's New General Secretary: His Dramatic Win And Why He Is The Insurgency Candidate |author=Dina Rickman |publisher=Huffington Post |date=26 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> McNicol continued in that role until 2004, when he was promoted to National Political Officer. He served in that capacity through to 2011, coordinating the political strategy of the union and representing its members\u2019 interests in both the public and private sector.<ref name=hp-20110726/><ref name=newstatesman-20110719>{{cite news |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-staggers/2011/07/labour-party-mcnicol-general |title=Iain McNicol is the right man for the job |author=Will Straw |newspaper=New Statesman |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 July 2011, Labour\u2019s [[National Executive Committee]] selected McNicol to become the party\u2019s next General Secretary under leader [[Ed Miliband]].<ref name=bbc-20110719 />\n\nMcNicol's intention to stand down as General Secretary of the Labour Party was announced on 23 February 2018.<ref name=\"Stewart\"/> On 20 March 2018 he was succeeded by [[Jennie Formby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/93790/jennie-formby-appointed-labour-general-secretary|title=Jennie Formby appointed Labour general secretary in huge boost for Jeremy Corbyn|first=|last=PoliticsHome.com|date=20 March 2018|publisher=|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 2018, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron McNicol of West Kilbride''', ''of West Kilbride in the County of Ayrshire''.<ref name=ph-20180518>{{cite news |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/constitution/house-lords-reform/news/95306/former-labour-general-secretary-iain-mcnicol |title=Former Labour general secretary Iain McNicol given peerage by Jeremy Corbyn |last=Schofield |first=Kevin |website=PoliticsHome |date=18 May 2018 |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62337|date=27 June 2018|page=11404}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019 [[Jon Lansman]] the founder of [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]] writing in the [[LabourList]] blog accused McNicol and his team of delaying action on handling [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism cases]] while he was General Secretary, and allowing a backlog of cases to build up that would damage the party and [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s leadership.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jeremy Corbyn pushed for action on antisemitism \u2013 but was held back by bureaucracy |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/05/jeremy-corbyn-pushed-for-action-on-antisemitism-but-was-held-back-by-bureaucracy/ |publisher=Labourlist |accessdate=12 July 2019 |date=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2016 Labour Party leadership election==\nIn June and July 2016, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported that the office of the Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] believed that McNicol tried to prevent Corbyn from attending a key [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC) meeting, and was alleged to be complicit in trying to exclude Corbyn from entering the second leadership election. It reported that senior figures in the trade union movement were discussing replacement options for McNicol in his General Secretary role.<ref name=ft-20160713>{{cite news |url=https://next.ft.com/content/b05f39a2-490b-11e6-b387-64ab0a67014c |title=Labour's McNicol targeted over role in coup |author=Jim Pickard |newspaper=Financial Times |date=13 July 2016 |accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20160725>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/25/labour-leadership-contest-legal-documents-reveal-depth-of-split/ |title=Labour leadership contest: Legal documents reveal depth of split between Jeremy Corbyn and party 's general secretary |author=Ben Riley-Smith |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=25 July 2016 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nA civil [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] legal challenge was brought by Labour donor and former parliamentary candidate [[Michael Foster (agent)|Michael Foster]], to contest the decision to allow Corbyn to be a candidate without having to secure any nominations from Labour MPs. The case went to court on 26 July 2016. McNicol was the first defendant on behalf of the members of the Labour Party. Corbyn applied to the court, and was accepted, to be a second defendant with his own legal team as Corbyn was \"particularly affected and particularly interested in the proper construction of the rules\" and that McNicol was \"being expected to vigorously defend a position which he regarded as incorrect prior to the NEC decision\".<ref name=telegraph-20160725/><ref name=guardian-20160720>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/20/jeremy-corbyn-wins-right-to-be-defendant-in-leadership-court-case |title=Jeremy Corbyn wins right to be defendant in leadership court case |author=Jessica Elgot |newspaper=The Guardian |date=20 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> The High Court ruled that the NEC's decision that Corbyn should automatically be on the ballot was a correct interpretation of the [[Labour Party Rule Book]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/28/jeremy-corbyn-fights-off-court-challenge-labour-leadership-ballot|title=Jeremy Corbyn fights off court challenge over Labour leadership ballot|newspaper=The Guardian |last1=Walker|first1=Peter |last2=Syal|first2=Rajeev |last3=Mason|first3=Rowena |date=28 July 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=highcourt-20160728>>{{cite report |url=https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/judgment-foster-v-mcnicol-and-corbyn-20160728.pdf |title=Between: MICHAEL FOSTER and IAIN McNICOL (1) (sued on behalf of all other members of the Labour Party except the Claimant and the Second Defendant) and THE RT HON JEREMY CORBYN MP (2) |author=Mr Justice Foskett |publisher=Royal Courts of Justice id&#61;[2016] EWHC 1966 (QB) Case HQ16X02502 |date=28 July 2016 |accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAn additional [[Evangelou v McNicol|court case]] was brought against McNicol in August 2016 regarding the NEC's decision to disallow party members who had joined after 12 January 2016 from voting in the leadership election. The claimants won their case in the High Court, but this decision was overturned on [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|appeal]].<ref>BBC - [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/37077672 \"Labour leadership: Members drop voting legal challenge\"] 14 August 2016</ref> In late September, it was reported that a Labour party member was lodging a claim at the County Court in response to her suspension by the NEC and that it would cite McNicol as claimant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecanary.co/2016/09/21/latest-twist-labour-purge-truly-astonishing-images/|title=The latest twist in the Labour 'purge' is truly astonishing [IMAGES]|date=2016-09-21|website=The Canary|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMcNicol is married and has a son and daughter.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} He holds a black belt in [[karate]].<ref name=ph-20120927/> He attended Ardrossan Academy.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://labourlist.org/2012/07/iain-mcnicol-q-a/ Iain McNicol \u2013 Q & A], [[LabourList]], 19 July 2012\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ray Collins, Baron Collins of Highbury|Ray Collins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[General Secretary of the Labour Party]]|years=2011\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jennie Formby]]}} \n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baron McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown|The Lord McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron McNicol of West Kilbride'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Alan Haselhurst|The Lord Haselhurst]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Labour Party}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United Kingdom|Organised labour}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McNicol, Iain}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Abertay Dundee]]\n[[Category:British trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Jeremy Corbyn]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iain_McNicol"}
{"title_page": "Mark Malloch Brown, Baron Malloch-Brown", "text_new": "{{short description|Former British Labour politician and Chair of the Best for Britain campaign}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG|PC}}\n|name             = The Lord Malloch-Brown\n|image            = Lord Malloch Brown 2.jpg\n|office           = [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Minister of State for Africa, Asia and the United Nations]]\n|term_start       = 28 June 2007\n|term_end         = 24 July 2009\n|primeminister    = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|predecessor      = Position established\n|successor        = [[Glenys Kinnock|The Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead]] {{small|(Africa and the United Nations)}}<br />[[Chris Bryant]] {{small|([[Minister for Europe|Undersecretary of State for Europe and Asia]])}}\n|office2          = 2nd [[Deputy Secretary-General of the United Nations]]\n|term_start2      = 1 April 2006\n|term_end2        = 31 December 2006\n|1blankname2      = {{nowrap|Secretary-General}}\n|1namedata2       = [[Kofi Annan]]\n|predecessor2     = [[Louise Fr\u00e9chette]]\n|successor2       = [[Asha-Rose Migiro]]\n|office3          = Administrator of the [[United Nations Development Programme]]\n|1blankname3      = {{nowrap|Secretary-General}}\n|1namedata3       = [[Kofi Annan]]\n|term_start3      = 1 July 1999\n|term_end3        = 15 August 2005\n|predecessor3     = [[James Speth]]\n|successor3       = [[Kemal Dervi\u015f]]\n|office4          = Member of the [[House of Lords]]\n|term_start4      = 9 July 2007\n|term_end4        = 7 September 2015<br /><small>on Leave of Absence</small>\n|birth_name=George Mark Malloch Brown\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1953|9|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Marylebone]], [[London]], England\n|death_date       =\n|death_place      =\n|party            = None ([[Crossbencher]])\n|otherparty       = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (former)\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Patricia Cronan|1989}}\n|children         = 4\n|education        = [[Marlborough College]]\n|alma_mater       = {{ubl|[[Magdalene College, Cambridge]]|[[University of Michigan|University of Michigan, Ann Arbor]]}}\n}}\n'''George Mark Malloch Brown, Baron Malloch-Brown''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KCMG|PC}} (born 16 September 1953)<ref name=\"whoswho\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.59527|title=Malloch-Brown, Baron, ((George) Mark Malloch Brown) (born 16 Sept. 1953)|journal=[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]]|year=2007}}</ref> is a former UK government minister (2007 \u2013 2009) and [[United Nations Deputy Secretary-General]] (2006), as well as development specialist at the World Bank and United Nations (1994 \u2013 2005), and a communications consultant and journalist. He was [[Minister of State]] in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] of the British Labour party government with responsibility for Africa, Asia and the United Nations (June 2007 - July 2009). Following his appointment to government, Malloch Brown was created a [[life peer]] on 9 July 2007 as '''Baron Malloch-Brown''', of St Leonard's Forest in the County of [[West Sussex]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58391 |date=13 July 2007 |page=10139}}</ref> (his title is hyphenated but his surname is not). Malloch Brown was previously at the [[World Bank]] (1994\u20131999), the Administrator of the [[United Nations Development Programme]] (1999\u20132005) and briefly [[United Nations Deputy Secretary-General]] (April to December 2006). He had previously worked at the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] (1979\u20131983). He is also a former journalist for ''[[The Economist]]'', development specialist, and communications consultant. He has served as Chair of the [[Royal African Society]],<ref>[[Royal African Society]], [http://www.royalafricansociety.org/council Council]</ref> among other non-governmental and private sector roles, such as membership of the Executive Committee of the [[International Crisis Group]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMalloch Brown was born in [[Marylebone]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=svlnGcQUkpi8kocjQCOdSA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=8 June 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=15 September 2008 |title=Lord Malloch-Brown: You Ask The Questions |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/lord-malloch-brown-you-ask-the-questions-930883.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hasan |first=Mehdi |author-link=Mehdi Hasan |date=31 March 2011 |title=The NS Interview: Mark Malloch Brown, former UN deputy secretary general |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/international-politics/2011/03/interview-libya-arab-france |newspaper=[[New Statesman]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref> to an exiled South African diplomat.<ref>tfstevenson.com, 20 October 2012, [http://tfstevenson.com/2012/10/20/an-interview-with-lord-malloch-brown/ An Interview with Lord Malloch-Brown] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911231012/http://tfstevenson.com/2012/10/20/an-interview-with-lord-malloch-brown/ |date=11 September 2013 }}</ref> He was educated at [[Marlborough College]],<ref name=BBCprofile/> and earned a [[British undergraduate degree classification|First Class Honours]] Degree in History from [[Magdalene College, Cambridge]] and a master's degree in [[Political Science]] from the [[University of Michigan]].<ref>BusinessWeek, [http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=34164870&ticker=FCN Mark Malloch-Brown]</ref> He is an only child, but has four children with his wife.<ref name=\"whoswho\"/>\n\n==Early career==\nHe was the political correspondent at ''[[The Economist]]'' between 1977 and 1979.<ref name=UNbio/> Following this he worked for the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] from 1979 to 1983, where he worked for [[Kofi Annan]], and was stationed in [[Thailand]] (1979 to 1981)<ref name=UNbio/> where he was in charge of field operations for Cambodian [[refugees]] and supervised the construction of camps at [[Sa Kaeo Refugee Camp|Sa Kaeo]] and [[Khao-I-Dang]].<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0786445297 Thompson, Larry Clinton. ''Refugee Workers in the Indochina Exodus, 1975-1982.'' Jefferson, NC: McFarland, 2010.]</ref> In this period the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] was awarded the 1981 [[Nobel Peace Prize]], the second time it had been awarded the prize.<ref name=Yalebio/>\n\nMalloch Brown contemplated running for the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]] in the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 UK general election]] but was not selected as a candidate.<ref name=GuardianRamesh>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,,1388153,00.html |first=Randeep |last=Ramesh |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |title=Meet Kofi Annan's right hand man |date=12 January 2005 |access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, Malloch Brown returned to ''[[The Economist]]'' as the founding editor of the ''[[Economist Development Report]]'', a position he retained until 1986.<ref name=UNbio/><ref name=Yalebio/>\n\n==Sawyer-Miller (1986\u20131994)==\nMalloch Brown was the lead international partner at the US-based [[Sawyer-Miller Group]] communications consultancy from 1986 to 1994;<ref name=UNbio/> he ultimately co-owned the Group with three other partners.<ref name=Yalebio/> The Group was among the first communication consultants to use US-style election campaign methods for foreign governments, companies, and public policy debates.<ref name=GuardianRamesh/> Malloch Brown \"worked extensively on privatisation and other economic reform issues with leaders in Eastern Europe and Russia\".<ref name=Yalebio/>\n\n===Latin America===\nMalloch Brown focused much of his public relations energies on advising politicians in Latin America.<ref name=Yalebio/>\n\nHe advised [[Gonzalo S\u00e1nchez de Lozada]]'s [[1989 Bolivian presidential election|1989 presidential campaign]] in Bolivia.<ref name=Barker>Michael Barker, zmag.org, 26 November 2007, {{cite web|url=http://www.zmag.org/znet/viewArticle/17277 |title=The United Nations and Polyarchy |accessdate=2013-05-24 |url-status = bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828083449/http://www.zmag.org/znet/viewArticle/17277 |archivedate=28 August 2008 |df= }}</ref> In [[Peru]], he assisted [[Mario Vargas Llosa]] with his [[1990 Peruvian general election|1990 presidential campaign]], though Vargas Llosa did not heed his advice and lost to [[Alberto Fujimori]] despite having an initial lead in polls.<ref>{{cite news |last=Preston |first=Peter |author-link=Peter Preston |date=9 August 2008 |title=Masters of worldwide spin |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/aug/10/politicalbooks |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=9 March 2017}}</ref> In [[Chile]], Malloch Brown advised the opposition in its successful challenge to former dictator [[Augusto Pinochet]].<ref name=UNbio>United Nations, {{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/News/ossg/sg/stories/dsgbio.asp |title=Mark Malloch Brown |accessdate=2013-05-24 |url-status = bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070426123127/http://www.un.org/News/ossg/sg/stories/dsgbio.asp |archivedate=26 April 2007 |df= }}</ref><ref name=GuardianTran>{{cite news |last=Tran |first=Mark |date=28 June 2007 |title=Profile: Lord Malloch Brown |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/jun/28/politics.labour1 |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Siegel |first=Barry |author-link=Barry Siegel |date=24 November 1991 |title=Spin Doctors To The World : The Sawyer Miller Group Uses The Tricks Of Political Campaigns To Change The Way You Think About Foreign Governments, Big Business And Any Client In Need Of An Image Lift |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1991-11-24/magazine/tm-417_1_sawyer-miller |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>  In [[Colombia]], he advised the government on how to shed \"its image as the political wing of the Medellin cartel\"<ref name=GuardianTran/>\n\n===Philippines===\nIn the [[Philippines]], Malloch Brown worked with [[Corazon Aquino]] in the campaign against the communist, Malloch Brown wrote Aquino's victory speech which she recited days before voting results were to be released since her campaign assumed that Marcos claim victory as well.<ref name=\"MANILA2015\">{{cite news|title=Smartmatic chairman: Cory\u2019s close-in media adviser|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/smartmatic-chairman-corys-close-in-media-adviser/231878/|accessdate=9 March 2017|work=[[The Manila Times]]|date=29 November 2015}}</ref>  He stated that an \"outstanding accomplishment during the Cory campaign was to produce an exit poll that indicated that she had won\"<ref name=\"IBONsmart\">{{cite web|title=Automated Polls: Privatized elections, foreign-controlled democracy (Part 2)|url=http://ibon.org/2016/05/automated-polls-privatized-elections-foreign-controlled-democracy/|website=[[IBON Foundation]]|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> since other polls released showed that Aquino had been less popular than Marcos.\n\n==World Bank (1994\u20131999)==\nIn 1994, Malloch Brown joined the [[World Bank]] as Vice-President for External Affairs, which included responsibility for relations with the United Nations. He used his experience to good effect at the bank, helping to transform its reputation: \"under his guidance, the bank blitzed opinion-makers with full-page newspaper advertisements and a television campaign to change perceptions of it as an arrogant institution unwilling to heed outsiders. To his credit, the institution gradually gained a reputation as a 'listening bank', unlike its more aloof sister institution, the International Monetary Fund.\"<ref name=GuardianTran/>\n\n==United Nations (1999\u20132006)==\nMalloch Brown moved back to the United Nations as Administrator of the [[United Nations Development Programme]] (UNDP) in July 1999, remaining in this position until August 2005.<ref name=BBCprofile>[[BBC]], 28 June 2007, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6249980.stm Profile: Mark Malloch Brown]</ref>\n\nHe led the UN's creation of the [[Millennium Development Goals]] which were adopted at the UN [[Millennium Summit]] in December 2000,<ref name=Yalebio>http://www.ycsg.yale.edu, {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723214620/http://www.ycsg.yale.edu/center/forms/biographyBrown.pdf |date=23 July 2008 |title=Mark Malloch Brown }}</ref> later recounting that the draft had gone to the printers without an environmental goal when Malloch Brown passed the head of the UN environment programme in a corridor, leading to the rapid addition of MDG number 7.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tran |first=Mark |date=16 November 2012 |title=Mark Malloch-Brown: developing the MDGs was a bit like nuclear fusion |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2012/nov/16/mark-malloch-brown-mdgs-nuclear |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2002, Malloch Brown offered to assist talks between [[Hugo Chavez]]'s Bolivarian government and the opposition, who was seeking to begin the process of attempting to recall Ch\u00e1vez a year later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Venezuelan official appeals for international help|work=[[Knight Ridder|Knight Ridder Tribune News Service]]|date=19 August 2002|ref=Page 1}}</ref> His UNDP observers were chosen by Venezuela's [[National Electoral Council (Venezuela)|National Electoral Council (CNE)]] to supervise the signature collection for the [[2004 Venezuela recall]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Int'l observers to supervise signature collection in Venezuela|work=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=1 November 2003|ref=Page 1}}</ref>\n\nIn this role Malloch Brown co-ordinated the UN's response to the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami]].<ref name=BBCprofile/> Internally at UNDP, which was facing increased competition from the World Bank in its areas of responsibility such as capacity building, governance and emergency recovery, he tried to re orient UNDP's activities (sometimes controversially), because of competition with other UN agencies who were also adapting to the demands of a globalising world. Compared with his predecessor, he improved resource mobilisation from donor countries.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}\n\nIn January 2005 he was appointed ''[[Chef de Cabinet (UN)|Chef de Cabinet]]'' to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan, whilst retaining his position as Administrator of UNDP for much of 2005.<ref name=Yalebio/><ref>{{cite news |last=Borger |first=Julian |author-link=Julian Borger |date=4 January 2005 |title=UN appoints Briton as new chief of staff |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/jan/04/unitednations |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Deputy Secretary-General (2006)===\nMalloch Brown succeeded [[Louise Fr\u00e9chette]] as [[United Nations Deputy Secretary-General]] on 1 April 2006, retaining the position until December 2006.<ref name=BBCprofile/>\n\n==== Oil for food ====\nMalloch Brown publicly defended handling of the [[Oil-for-Food Programme]] by the UN in general, and Kofi Annan in particular. While he countered critics that \"Not a penny was lost from the organization,\"<ref name=\"opinionjournal.com\">[http://www.opinionjournal.com/editorial/feature.html?id=110010050 ''Wall Street Journal'', \"Axis of Soros\", 9 May 2007]</ref> an internal UN audit of the Oil-for-Food programme revealed that there had been overcompensation amounting to $557 million.<ref>[http://www.usunnewyork.usmission.gov/oversight/OIOS_reports/Report58.pdf ''United Nations Office of Internal Oversight'', \"Findings Resulting From Oversight Activities of the Oil-for-Food Programme\", 2004]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060924040427/http://www.usunnewyork.usmission.gov/oversight/OIOS_reports/Report58.pdf |date=24 September 2006 }}</ref> A separate audit of UN peacekeeping procurement concluded that at least $310 million from a budget of $1.6 billion could not be accounted for.<ref name=\"opinionjournal.com\"/>\n\nMalloch Brown, briefing the Security Council, argued that, while the situation uncovered by the audit was \"alarming\", and that nearly $300 million out of a $1.6 billion budget was involved, it showed more that there was significant waste with only narrow instances of fraud. He noted that the UN Secretariat, based on the reservations expressed by the department being audited, did not entirely accept the auditor's conclusions.<ref>[https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2006/sc8645.doc.htm ''UN Security Council'', \"SC/8645 UN Security Council Minutes 5376 Meeting (AM)\", 22 February 2006]</ref>\n\n====Criticisms of the George W. Bush administration====\nOn 6 June 2006, while addressing a conference in New York City, he criticised the United States administration for allowing \"too much unchecked UN-bashing and stereotyping\". He stated that much of the political dialogue in the US about the UN had been abdicated to its most strident critics, such as conservative talk-show host [[Rush Limbaugh]] and the [[Fox News]] cable channel and, as a result of this, the true role and value of the UN has become \"a mystery in Middle America\".<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2006/06/08/wun08.xml Alec Russell in ''The Telegraph'', \"US failing to aid the UN, says Annan's deputy\", 8 June 2006]</ref> These remarks resulted in a backlash from the White House and some US conservative commentators, culminating in a call for an apology by the US envoy to the United Nations [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]]. Bolton added to reporters, \"I spoke to the secretary-general this morning, I said \"I've known you since 1989 and I'm telling you this is the worst mistake by a senior U.N. official that I have seen in that entire time.\"<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,198535,00.html ''Fox News'', \"Speech by U.N. Leader Draws Angry Response From U.S.\", 7 June 2006]</ref>\n\n[[John Podesta]] and Richard C. Leone wrote that Bolton's comment \"distorted Mr. Malloch Brown's remarks by calling them an attack on 'the American people', and ...  by conflating Rush Limbaugh and Fox News with the American people. ...\nMr. Malloch Brown had to break with the niceties of diplomatic tradition to plead for such leadership. ... Mr. Malloch Brown is surely correct: the people of the United States deserve better leadership and diplomacy to represent their interests in the world\u2019s most important international body.\"<ref>[http://www.tcf.org/list.asp?type=TN&pubid=1335 John Podesta and Richard C. Leone in ''The Century Foundation'', \"Time for U.S. Leadership, Not Bullying at the United Nations\", 16 June 2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809015243/http://www.tcf.org/list.asp?type=TN&pubid=1335 |date=9 August 2007 }}</ref> Malloch Brown himself rejected the need to apologise, and received the support of Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who said that his deputy's comments \"should be read in the right spirit\".<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,11069-2217839,00.html James Bone and Richard Beeston in ''The Times'', \"Apologise or we'll cut your funding, US envoy tells UN\", 9 June 2006]</ref>\n\nIn July 2006, during the [[2006 Israel-Lebanon conflict|Israel-Hezbollah]] crisis in Lebanon, Malloch Brown said America should allow others to \"share the lead\" in solving the Lebanon crisis, and also advised that Britain adopt a lower profile in solving the crisis, lest the international community see the negotiations as being led by the same team that instigated the [[Iraq War|invasion of Iraq]]. These comments again drew criticism from some American officials, including the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]], a spokesman from which stated \"We are seeing a troubling pattern of a high official of the UN who seems to be making it his business to criticize member states and, frankly, with misplaced and misguided criticisms.\"<ref>[http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=worldNews&storyID=2006-08-02T231347Z_01_N02314381_RTRUKOC_0_US-MIDEAST-UN-MALLOCH.xml ''Reuters'', 2 August 2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070331061726/http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=worldNews |date=31 March 2007 }}</ref>\n\nMalloch Brown responded in an interview with [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]:\n:\"I don't think the US has anything to object to in the comments. I was really in fact in the interview calling for the US to reach out to France and others to make sure it was demonstrating a broad multilateral coalition and within a single news cycle of my calling for that, it was doing it.\" He added \"I may be prophetic but I wasn't critical\".<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/middle_east/july-dec06/brown_08-02.html ''PBS'' ''NewsHour'', \"Talks for International Force in Lebanon Stall in U.N.\", 2 August 2006]</ref>\n\nWhen Bolton later announced his own resignation in early December, Malloch Brown made his delight clear, telling reporters \"No comment \u2013 and you can say he said it with a smile\".<ref>Edith M. Lederer 5 December 2006;  \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/05/AR2006120500209.html Bush Agenda Came 1st for Bolton at U.N.]\"; ''[[The Associated Press]]''.  Retrieved on 3 December 2007</ref>\n\n==UK Minister (2007\u20132009)==\nOn 27 June 2007 it was announced that Malloch Brown was joining the Government of incoming Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] as Minister of State at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] (FCO) with responsibility for Africa, Asia and the United Nations.<ref name=GuardianTran/> It was also announced that Malloch Brown would receive a [[Life peerage|peerage]] to enable him to sit in the House of Lords; he was also appointed to the [[Privy Council]]. Plans for his appointment and peerage had been leaked to ''[[The Observer]]'''s Pendennis column in November 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last=Marre |first=Oliver |date=12 November 2006 |title=Pendennis: Brown's found a new friend ... called Brown |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/nov/12/1 |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref> At the time ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' said that he \"While the aid agencies and liberals were still toasting the arrival of 'Saint Mark' to Whitehall, the neo-cons on both sides of the Atlantic were throwing darts at photographs of their devil. [He] divides opinion between those who see him as the great hope for Africa and a principled opponent of the war in Iraq, and those who believe that he is an anti-American egotist who defended Kofi Annan over the oil-for-food scandal.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sylvester |first1=Rachel |author-link1=Rachel Sylvester |last2=Thomson |first2=Alice |author-link2=Alice Thomson |date=14 July 2007 |title=Mark Malloch Brown: 'Let's not rely just on US' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1557402/Mark-Malloch-Brown-Lets-not-rely-just-on-US.html |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the decision by the [[Scottish Criminal Cases Review Commission]] ([[SCCRC]]) to refer the case of [[Abdelbaset al-Megrahi]] back for a second appeal against conviction, Dr [[Hans K\u00f6chler]], UN-appointed international observer at the [[Pan Am Flight 103 bombing trial|Lockerbie trial]], wrote on 4 July 2007 to Malloch Brown reiterating his call for a \"full and independent public inquiry of the Lockerbie case\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Kelbie |first=Paul |date=8 July 2007 |title=UN observer calls for fresh Lockerbie probe |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/jul/08/lockerbie.theobserver |newspaper=The Observer |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref> K\u00f6chler addressed the letter also to First Minister of Scotland, [[Alex Salmond]], Foreign Secretary, [[David Miliband]] and Home Secretary, [[Jacqui Smith]].<ref>[http://i-p-o.org/IPO-nr-Lockerbie-04July07.htm K\u00f6chler calls for independent inquiry into Lockerbie]</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, the conservative British magazine ''[[The Spectator]]'' drew some attention with its criticism of the Malloch Brown family's occupancy of a government-owned, so-called \"grace and favour\" apartment in London, previously used by the former Deputy Prime Minister, [[John Prescott]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rosett |first1=Claudia |author-link1=Claudia Rosett |last2=Forsyth |first2=James |author-link2=James Forsyth (journalist) |date=7 November 2007 |title=The taxpayer is being stung so this Lord can live in Admiralty House |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2007/11/the-taxpayer-is-being-stung-so-this-lord-can-live-in-admiralty-house/ |newspaper=[[The Spectator]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref> On 18 November 2007 ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' fuelled the controversy by reporting that \"some see the hand of [[David Miliband|Miliband]] behind the savaging of Malloch Brown in ''The Spectator''\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile: Lord Malloch-Brown |date=18 November 2007 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/profile-lord-malloch-brown-7hg72tlc3wb |newspaper=The Times |access-date=8 June 2018 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nOn 7 July 2009, Lord Malloch Brown announced he was stepping down from his position as Minister of State for Africa, Asia and the United Nations at the end of July 2009, citing personal and family reasons.<ref>BBC UK News, 8 July 2009, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8139632.stm Foreign Office minister resigns]</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Riddell |first=Mary |author-link=Mary Riddell |date=22 July 2009 |title=Lord Malloch-Brown interview: 'This dangerous gridlock that taints our politics' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/onthefrontline/5881753/Lord-Malloch-Brown-interview-This-dangerous-gridlock-that-taints-our-politics.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Post-ministerial career==\nMalloch Brown was appointed chairman of global affairs for [[FTI Consulting]] in September 2010.<ref>FTI Consulting (2010). {{cite web|url=http://www.fticonsulting.com/about-fti/news/press-releases/fti-consulting-appoints-lord-malloch-brown-as-chairman-global-affairs.aspx |title=FTI Consulting Appoints Lord Malloch-Brown as Chairman, Global Affairs |accessdate=2011-07-13 |url-status = bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124020906/http://www.fticonsulting.com/about-fti/news/press-releases/fti-consulting-appoints-lord-malloch-brown-as-chairman-global-affairs.aspx |archivedate=24 November 2010 |df= }}. Retrieved 13 July 2011.</ref> Consultancy appointments to oil companies [[Vitol]] and [[SouthWest Energy Ltd]] (both approved by the relevant parliamentary committee) were reported in 2010.<ref>[[The Guardian]], 30 July 2010, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/jul/30/africa-malloch-brown-oil-vitol Former Africa minister Malloch-Brown advises oil firm on African expansion]</ref>\n\nHe was a member of ''[[The Guardian]]'''s global development advisory panel. Malloch Brown contributed to the panel beside [[U2]]'s [[Bono]], the [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]]'s [[Ha-Joon Chang]] and [[Mark Weisbrot]], [[Paul Collier]] and others.<ref>{{cite news|title=Global development advisory panel|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2010/sep/14/global-development-advisory-panel|accessdate=9 March 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=14 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nMalloch Brown became chairman of the board of directors of [[SGO Corporation Limited]], a [[holding company]] whose primary asset is the election technology and [[voting machine]] manufacturer [[Smartmatic]], in 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ahmed |first=Murad |author-link=Murad Ahmed |date=24 November 2014 |title=Lord Mark Malloch-Brown to chair election technology group SGO |url=https://www.ft.com/content/ddf42272-7308-11e4-907b-00144feabdc0 |newspaper=[[Financial Times]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.sgo.com/about/|website=SGO|accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref> Citing Malloch Brown's former and present relationship with politicians in the Philippines as well as his role in Smartmatic, the [[IBON Foundation]], a non-profit research organization based in the Philippines, criticized him as being \"a foreigner who made a career out of influencing elections\".<ref name=\"IBONsmart\"/>\n\n==Other==\nMalloch Brown was listed 7th in the Leaders & Revolutionaries Section of the [[Time 100]] in 2005.<ref name=UNbio/><ref>http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/completelist/0,29569,1972656,00.html</ref>\n\nOn 15 December 2006, he was named a visiting fellow at the [[Yale Center for the Study of Globalization]] and announced plans to focus on writing a book on changing leadership in a globalised world while in residence during the spring semester.<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/12/15/america/NA_GEN_US_UN_Official_Yale.php AP in ''The International Herald Tribune'', \"U.N. official named fellow at Yale\", 15 December 2006]</ref>\n\nMalloch Brown was appointed [[Order of St Michael and St George|Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) in the [[2007 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58196 |date=30 December 2006 |page=2 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nHis book ''[[The Unfinished Global Revolution]]''<ref name=\"book\">Carnegiecouncil.org, {{cite web|url=http://www.carnegiecouncil.org/resources/transcripts/0361.html |title=The Unfinished Global Revolution: discussion |accessdate=2011-03-08 |url-status = bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310020325/http://www.carnegiecouncil.org/resources/transcripts/0361.html |archivedate=10 March 2011 |df= }}, 23 February 2011</ref> came out early 2011 on Penguin Press.<ref>Robert Weiner, [http://www.unomaha.edu/idj/Issue1/Review_Weiner-UnfinishedGlobalRevel.pdf Review] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025042840/http://www.unomaha.edu/idj/Issue1/Review_Weiner-UnfinishedGlobalRevel.pdf |date=25 October 2014 }}, ID: International Dialogue, A Multidisciplinary Journal of World Affairs 1 2011</ref>\n\n===Association with George Soros===\nMalloch Brown has been closely associated with billionaire speculator [[George Soros]]. Working for [[Refugees International]], he was part of the Soros Advisory Committee on Bosnia in 1993\u201394, formed by [[George Soros]]. He has since kept cordial relations with Soros, and rented an apartment owned by Soros while working in New York on UN assignments.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nysun.com/article/15593|title=An Annan Deputy Is a Soros Tenant|newspaper=The New York Sun|date=15 June 2005|accessdate=13 July 2007}}</ref> While serving as United Nations Development Fund Administrator, Malloch Brown spoke beside Soros in 2002 suggesting that United Nations and Soros's Open Society Institute, as well as other organizations, work together to fund humanitarian functions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Press Conference \"Foreign Minister of Mexico and UNDP Administrator - March 18, 2002\"|url=https://www.un.org/ffd/pressconf/19a.htm|website=www.un.org|publisher=[[United Nations]]|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, Soros's [[Quantum Group of Funds|Quantum Fund]] announced the appointment of Malloch Brown as vice-president.<ref>[http://www.nysun.com/article/53955 Benny Avni in ''The New York Sun'', \"Ex-Deputy U.N. Chief Joins With Soros\", 7 May 2007]</ref> In September 2007, ''[[The Observer]]'' reported that he had resigned this position on becoming a government minister in the UK.<ref>[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/7days/story/0,,2170143,00.html Och, look. A new rich friend for Mr Brown] ''[[The Observer]]'', 16 September 2007</ref> Also in May 2007, Malloch Brown was named vice-chairman of [[Soros Fund Management]] and the [[Open Society Institute]], two other important Soros organisations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gppi.net/news/detail/article/mark-malloch-brown-appointed-vice-chairman-of-soros-fund-management-open-society-institute|title=Mark Malloch Brown appointed Vice-Chairman of Soros Fund Management, Open Society Institute|publisher=[[Global Public Policy Institute]]|date=21 May 2007|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120194558/http://www.gppi.net/news/detail/article/mark-malloch-brown-appointed-vice-chairman-of-soros-fund-management-open-society-institute/|archivedate=20 November 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Malloch Brown and [[FTI Consulting]] came to a legal settlement with Israeli mining billionaire [[Beny Steinmetz]], who had sued them claiming Malloch Brown had given confidential information to Soros which led to a smear campaign against Steinmetz's mining company. The out-of-court settlement of \u20ac90,000 plus costs was without any determination of liability.<ref name=telegraph-20130611>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/mining/10112694/FTI-and-Lord-Malloch-Brown-settle-out-of-court-with-mining-billionaire-Beny-Steinmetz.html |title=FTI and Lord Malloch-Brown settle out of court with mining billionaire Beny Steinmetz |last=Clancy |first=Rebecca |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=11 June 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nMalloch Brown is a member of the Executive Committee of the [[International Crisis Group]],<ref>ICG, [http://www.crisisgroup.org/en/about/board.aspx Crisis Group's Board of Trustees] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110203082846/http://www.crisisgroup.org/en/about/board.aspx |date=3 February 2011 }}</ref> and played a key role in its foundation in 1993\u20135. In July 2014 he became Co-Chair of the Board of Trustees.<ref name=bl-cv-2017>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=34164870&privcapId=139205423 |title=Executive Profile - George Mark Malloch-Brown BA (Hons) History, MA (Political Science), KCMG |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other honours===\n* Eminent member, [[Sergio Vieira de Mello Foundation]]\n* Honorary Patron, [[University Philosophical Society]], [[Trinity College, Dublin]].\n* Honorary President, [[London International Model United Nations|London International Model United Nations Foundation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mark Malloch Brown, Baron Malloch-Brown}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n* {{UK Peer links|parliament=lords/lord-malloch-brown/3774|hansard=|hansardcurr=5249|guardian=|publicwhip=Lord_Malloch-Brown|theywork=lord_malloch-brown|record=Mark-Malloch-Brown/1946|bbc=61505.stm|journalisted=mark-malloch-brown}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Mark Malloch Brown}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-intgov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Speth]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Administrator of the [[United Nations Development Programme]]|years=1999\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kemal Dervi\u015f]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before={{flagicon|Canada}} [[Louise Fr\u00e9chette]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Deputy Secretary-General of the United Nations]]|years=2006}}\n{{s-aft|after={{flagicon|Tanzania}} [[Asha-Rose Migiro]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new|rows=2|office}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Minister of State for Africa, Asia and the United Nations]]|years=2007\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Glenys Kinnock, Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead|Glenys Kinnock]]|as=Minister of State for Africa and the United Nations}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chris Bryant]]|as=[[Minister for Europe|Undersecretary of State for Europe and Asia]]}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baron Mawson|The Lord Mawson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron Malloch-Brown'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Baron West of Spithead|The Lord West of Spithead]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{UNDeputySG}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mallochbrown, Mark Malloch Brown, Baron}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Administrators of the United Nations Development Programme]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalene College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marlborough College]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:British officials of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Deputy Secretaries-General of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:English people of South African descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Former British Labour politician and Chair of the Best for Britain campaign}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG|PC}}\n|name             = The Lord Malloch-Brown\n|image            = Lord Malloch Brown 2.jpg\n|office           = [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Minister of State for Africa, Asia and the United Nations]]\n|term_start       = 28 June 2007\n|term_end         = 24 July 2009\n|primeminister    = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|predecessor      = Position established\n|successor        = [[Glenys Kinnock|The Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead]] {{small|(Africa and the United Nations)}}<br />[[Chris Bryant]] {{small|([[Minister for Europe|Undersecretary of State for Europe and Asia]])}}\n|office2          = 2nd [[Deputy Secretary-General of the United Nations]]\n|term_start2      = 1 April 2006\n|term_end2        = 31 December 2006\n|1blankname2      = {{nowrap|Secretary-General}}\n|1namedata2       = [[Kofi Annan]]\n|predecessor2     = [[Louise Fr\u00e9chette]]\n|successor2       = [[Asha-Rose Migiro]]\n|office3          = Administrator of the [[United Nations Development Programme]]\n|1blankname3      = {{nowrap|Secretary-General}}\n|1namedata3       = [[Kofi Annan]]\n|term_start3      = 1 July 1999\n|term_end3        = 15 August 2005\n|predecessor3     = [[James Speth]]\n|successor3       = [[Kemal Dervi\u015f]]\n|office4          = Member of the [[House of Lords]]\n|term_start4      = 9 July 2007\n|term_end4        = 7 September 2015<br /><small>on Leave of Absence</small>\n|birth_name=George Mark Malloch Brown\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1953|9|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Marylebone]], [[London]], England\n|death_date       =\n|death_place      =\n|party            = None ([[Crossbencher]])\n|otherparty       = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (former)\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Patricia Cronan|1989}}\n|children         = 4\n|education        = [[Marlborough College]]\n|alma_mater       = {{ubl|[[Magdalene College, Cambridge]]|[[University of Michigan|University of Michigan, Ann Arbor]]}}\n}}\n'''George Mark Malloch Brown, Baron Malloch-Brown''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KCMG|PC}} (born 16 September 1953)<ref name=\"whoswho\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.59527|title=Malloch-Brown, Baron, ((George) Mark Malloch Brown) (born 16 Sept. 1953)|journal=[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]]|year=2007}}</ref> is a former UK government minister (2007 \u2013 2009) and [[United Nations Deputy Secretary-General]] (2006), as well as development specialist at the World Bank and United Nations (1994 \u2013 2005), and a communications consultant and journalist. He was [[Minister of State]] in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] of the British Labour party government with responsibility for Africa, Asia and the United Nations (June 2007 - July 2009). Following his appointment to government, Malloch Brown was created a [[life peer]] on 9 July 2007 as '''Baron Malloch-Brown''', of St Leonard's Forest in the County of [[West Sussex]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58391 |date=13 July 2007 |page=10139}}</ref> (his title is hyphenated but his surname is not). Malloch Brown was previously at the [[World Bank]] (1994\u20131999), the Administrator of the [[United Nations Development Programme]] (1999\u20132005) and briefly [[United Nations Deputy Secretary-General]] (April to December 2006). He had previously worked at the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] (1979\u20131983). He is also a former journalist for ''[[The Economist]]'', development specialist, and communications consultant. He has served as Chair of the [[Royal African Society]],<ref>[[Royal African Society]], [http://www.royalafricansociety.org/council Council]</ref> among other non-governmental and private sector roles, such as membership of the Executive Committee of the [[International Crisis Group]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMalloch Brown was born in [[Marylebone]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=svlnGcQUkpi8kocjQCOdSA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=8 June 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=15 September 2008 |title=Lord Malloch-Brown: You Ask The Questions |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/lord-malloch-brown-you-ask-the-questions-930883.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hasan |first=Mehdi |author-link=Mehdi Hasan |date=31 March 2011 |title=The NS Interview: Mark Malloch Brown, former UN deputy secretary general |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/international-politics/2011/03/interview-libya-arab-france |newspaper=[[New Statesman]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref> to an exiled South African diplomat.<ref>tfstevenson.com, 20 October 2012, [http://tfstevenson.com/2012/10/20/an-interview-with-lord-malloch-brown/ An Interview with Lord Malloch-Brown] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911231012/http://tfstevenson.com/2012/10/20/an-interview-with-lord-malloch-brown/ |date=11 September 2013 }}</ref> He was educated at [[Marlborough College]],<ref name=BBCprofile/> and earned a [[British undergraduate degree classification|First Class Honours]] Degree in History from [[Magdalene College, Cambridge]] and a master's degree in [[Political Science]] from the [[University of Michigan]].<ref>BusinessWeek, [http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=34164870&ticker=FCN Mark Malloch-Brown]</ref> He is an only child, but has four children with his wife.<ref name=\"whoswho\"/>\n\n==Early career==\nHe was the political correspondent at ''[[The Economist]]'' between 1977 and 1979.<ref name=UNbio/> Following this he worked for the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] from 1979 to 1983, where he worked for [[Kofi Annan]], and was stationed in [[Thailand]] (1979 to 1981)<ref name=UNbio/> where he was in charge of field operations for Cambodian [[refugees]] and supervised the construction of camps at [[Sa Kaeo Refugee Camp|Sa Kaeo]] and [[Khao-I-Dang]].<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0786445297 Thompson, Larry Clinton. ''Refugee Workers in the Indochina Exodus, 1975-1982.'' Jefferson, NC: McFarland, 2010.]</ref> In this period the [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees]] was awarded the 1981 [[Nobel Peace Prize]], the second time it had been awarded the prize.<ref name=Yalebio/>\n\nMalloch Brown contemplated running for the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]] in the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 UK general election]] but was not selected as a candidate.<ref name=GuardianRamesh>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/g2/story/0,,1388153,00.html |first=Randeep |last=Ramesh |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |title=Meet Kofi Annan's right hand man |date=12 January 2005 |access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, Malloch Brown returned to ''[[The Economist]]'' as the founding editor of the ''[[Economist Development Report]]'', a position he retained until 1986.<ref name=UNbio/><ref name=Yalebio/>\n\n==Sawyer-Miller (1986\u20131994)==\nMalloch Brown was the lead international partner at the US-based [[Sawyer-Miller Group]] communications consultancy from 1986 to 1994;<ref name=UNbio/> he ultimately co-owned the Group with three other partners.<ref name=Yalebio/> The Group was among the first communication consultants to use US-style election campaign methods for foreign governments, companies, and public policy debates.<ref name=GuardianRamesh/> Malloch Brown \"worked extensively on privatisation and other economic reform issues with leaders in Eastern Europe and Russia\".<ref name=Yalebio/>\n\n===Latin America===\nMalloch Brown focused much of his public relations energies on advising politicians in Latin America.<ref name=Yalebio/>\n\nHe advised [[Gonzalo S\u00e1nchez de Lozada]]'s [[1989 Bolivian presidential election|1989 presidential campaign]] in Bolivia.<ref name=Barker>Michael Barker, zmag.org, 26 November 2007, {{cite web|url=http://www.zmag.org/znet/viewArticle/17277 |title=The United Nations and Polyarchy |accessdate=2013-05-24 |url-status = bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828083449/http://www.zmag.org/znet/viewArticle/17277 |archivedate=28 August 2008 |df= }}</ref> In [[Peru]], he assisted [[Mario Vargas Llosa]] with his [[1990 Peruvian general election|1990 presidential campaign]], though Vargas Llosa did not heed his advice and lost to [[Alberto Fujimori]] despite having an initial lead in polls.<ref>{{cite news |last=Preston |first=Peter |author-link=Peter Preston |date=9 August 2008 |title=Masters of worldwide spin |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/aug/10/politicalbooks |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=9 March 2017}}</ref> In [[Chile]], Malloch Brown advised the opposition in its successful challenge to former dictator [[Augusto Pinochet]].<ref name=UNbio>United Nations, {{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/News/ossg/sg/stories/dsgbio.asp |title=Mark Malloch Brown |accessdate=2013-05-24 |url-status = bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070426123127/http://www.un.org/News/ossg/sg/stories/dsgbio.asp |archivedate=26 April 2007 |df= }}</ref><ref name=GuardianTran>{{cite news |last=Tran |first=Mark |date=28 June 2007 |title=Profile: Lord Malloch Brown |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/jun/28/politics.labour1 |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Siegel |first=Barry |author-link=Barry Siegel |date=24 November 1991 |title=Spin Doctors To The World : The Sawyer Miller Group Uses The Tricks Of Political Campaigns To Change The Way You Think About Foreign Governments, Big Business And Any Client In Need Of An Image Lift |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1991-11-24/magazine/tm-417_1_sawyer-miller |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>  In [[Colombia]], he advised the government on how to shed \"its image as the political wing of the Medellin cartel\"<ref name=GuardianTran/>\n\n===Philippines===\nIn the [[Philippines]], Malloch Brown worked with [[Corazon Aquino]] in the campaign against the communist, Malloch Brown wrote Aquino's victory speech which she recited days before voting results were to be released since her campaign assumed that Marcos claim victory as well.<ref name=\"MANILA2015\">{{cite news|title=Smartmatic chairman: Cory\u2019s close-in media adviser|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/smartmatic-chairman-corys-close-in-media-adviser/231878/|accessdate=9 March 2017|work=[[The Manila Times]]|date=29 November 2015}}</ref>  He stated that an \"outstanding accomplishment during the Cory campaign was to produce an exit poll that indicated that she had won\"<ref name=\"IBONsmart\">{{cite web|title=Automated Polls: Privatized elections, foreign-controlled democracy (Part 2)|url=http://ibon.org/2016/05/automated-polls-privatized-elections-foreign-controlled-democracy/|website=[[IBON Foundation]]|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> since other polls released showed that Aquino had been less popular than Marcos.\n\n==World Bank (1994\u20131999)==\nIn 1994, Malloch Brown joined the [[World Bank]] as Vice-President for External Affairs, which included responsibility for relations with the United Nations. He used his experience to good effect at the bank, helping to transform its reputation: \"under his guidance, the bank blitzed opinion-makers with full-page newspaper advertisements and a television campaign to change perceptions of it as an arrogant institution unwilling to heed outsiders. To his credit, the institution gradually gained a reputation as a 'listening bank', unlike its more aloof sister institution, the International Monetary Fund.\"<ref name=GuardianTran/>\n\n==United Nations (1999\u20132006)==\nMalloch Brown moved back to the United Nations as Administrator of the [[United Nations Development Programme]] (UNDP) in July 1999, remaining in this position until August 2005.<ref name=BBCprofile>[[BBC]], 28 June 2007, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6249980.stm Profile: Mark Malloch Brown]</ref>\n\nHe led the UN's creation of the [[Millennium Development Goals]] which were adopted at the UN [[Millennium Summit]] in December 2000,<ref name=Yalebio>http://www.ycsg.yale.edu, {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723214620/http://www.ycsg.yale.edu/center/forms/biographyBrown.pdf |date=23 July 2008 |title=Mark Malloch Brown }}</ref> later recounting that the draft had gone to the printers without an environmental goal when Malloch Brown passed the head of the UN environment programme in a corridor, leading to the rapid addition of MDG number 7.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tran |first=Mark |date=16 November 2012 |title=Mark Malloch-Brown: developing the MDGs was a bit like nuclear fusion |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2012/nov/16/mark-malloch-brown-mdgs-nuclear |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2002, Malloch Brown offered to assist talks between [[Hugo Chavez]]'s Bolivarian government and the opposition, who was seeking to begin the process of attempting to recall Ch\u00e1vez a year later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Venezuelan official appeals for international help|work=[[Knight Ridder|Knight Ridder Tribune News Service]]|date=19 August 2002|ref=Page 1}}</ref> His UNDP observers were chosen by Venezuela's [[National Electoral Council (Venezuela)|National Electoral Council (CNE)]] to supervise the signature collection for the [[2004 Venezuela recall]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Int'l observers to supervise signature collection in Venezuela|work=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|date=1 November 2003|ref=Page 1}}</ref>\n\nIn this role Malloch Brown co-ordinated the UN's response to the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami]].<ref name=BBCprofile/> Internally at UNDP, which was facing increased competition from the World Bank in its areas of responsibility such as capacity building, governance and emergency recovery, he tried to re orient UNDP's activities (sometimes controversially), because of competition with other UN agencies who were also adapting to the demands of a globalising world. Compared with his predecessor, he improved resource mobilisation from donor countries.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}\n\nIn January 2005 he was appointed ''[[Chef de Cabinet (UN)|Chef de Cabinet]]'' to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan, whilst retaining his position as Administrator of UNDP for much of 2005.<ref name=Yalebio/><ref>{{cite news |last=Borger |first=Julian |author-link=Julian Borger |date=4 January 2005 |title=UN appoints Briton as new chief of staff |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/jan/04/unitednations |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Deputy Secretary-General (2006)===\nMalloch Brown succeeded [[Louise Fr\u00e9chette]] as [[United Nations Deputy Secretary-General]] on 1 April 2006, retaining the position until December 2006.<ref name=BBCprofile/>\n\n==== Oil for food ====\nMalloch Brown publicly defended handling of the [[Oil-for-Food Programme]] by the UN in general, and Kofi Annan in particular. While he countered critics that \"Not a penny was lost from the organization,\"<ref name=\"opinionjournal.com\">[http://www.opinionjournal.com/editorial/feature.html?id=110010050 ''Wall Street Journal'', \"Axis of Soros\", 9 May 2007]</ref> an internal UN audit of the Oil-for-Food programme revealed that there had been overcompensation amounting to $557 million.<ref>[http://www.usunnewyork.usmission.gov/oversight/OIOS_reports/Report58.pdf ''United Nations Office of Internal Oversight'', \"Findings Resulting From Oversight Activities of the Oil-for-Food Programme\", 2004]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060924040427/http://www.usunnewyork.usmission.gov/oversight/OIOS_reports/Report58.pdf |date=24 September 2006 }}</ref> A separate audit of UN peacekeeping procurement concluded that at least $310 million from a budget of $1.6 billion could not be accounted for.<ref name=\"opinionjournal.com\"/>\n\nMalloch Brown, briefing the Security Council, argued that, while the situation uncovered by the audit was \"alarming\", and that nearly $300 million out of a $1.6 billion budget was involved, it showed more that there was significant waste with only narrow instances of fraud. He noted that the UN Secretariat, based on the reservations expressed by the department being audited, did not entirely accept the auditor's conclusions.<ref>[https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2006/sc8645.doc.htm ''UN Security Council'', \"SC/8645 UN Security Council Minutes 5376 Meeting (AM)\", 22 February 2006]</ref>\n\n====Criticisms of the George W. Bush administration====\nOn 6 June 2006, while addressing a conference in New York City, he criticised the United States administration for allowing \"too much unchecked UN-bashing and stereotyping\". He stated that much of the political dialogue in the US about the UN had been abdicated to its most strident critics, such as conservative talk-show host [[Rush Limbaugh]] and the [[Fox News]] cable channel and, as a result of this, the true role and value of the UN has become \"a mystery in Middle America\".<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2006/06/08/wun08.xml Alec Russell in ''The Telegraph'', \"US failing to aid the UN, says Annan's deputy\", 8 June 2006]</ref> These remarks resulted in a backlash from the White House and some US conservative commentators, culminating in a call for an apology by the US envoy to the United Nations [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]]. Bolton added to reporters, \"I spoke to the secretary-general this morning, I said \"I've known you since 1989 and I'm telling you this is the worst mistake by a senior U.N. official that I have seen in that entire time.\"<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,198535,00.html ''Fox News'', \"Speech by U.N. Leader Draws Angry Response From U.S.\", 7 June 2006]</ref>\n\n[[John Podesta]] and Richard C. Leone wrote that Bolton's comment \"distorted Mr. Malloch Brown's remarks by calling them an attack on 'the American people', and ...  by conflating Rush Limbaugh and Fox News with the American people. ...\nMr. Malloch Brown had to break with the niceties of diplomatic tradition to plead for such leadership. ... Mr. Malloch Brown is surely correct: the people of the United States deserve better leadership and diplomacy to represent their interests in the world\u2019s most important international body.\"<ref>[http://www.tcf.org/list.asp?type=TN&pubid=1335 John Podesta and Richard C. Leone in ''The Century Foundation'', \"Time for U.S. Leadership, Not Bullying at the United Nations\", 16 June 2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809015243/http://www.tcf.org/list.asp?type=TN&pubid=1335 |date=9 August 2007 }}</ref> Malloch Brown himself rejected the need to apologise, and received the support of Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who said that his deputy's comments \"should be read in the right spirit\".<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,11069-2217839,00.html James Bone and Richard Beeston in ''The Times'', \"Apologise or we'll cut your funding, US envoy tells UN\", 9 June 2006]</ref>\n\nIn July 2006, during the [[2006 Israel-Lebanon conflict|Israel-Hezbollah]] crisis in Lebanon, Malloch Brown said America should allow others to \"share the lead\" in solving the Lebanon crisis, and also advised that Britain adopt a lower profile in solving the crisis, lest the international community see the negotiations as being led by the same team that instigated the [[Iraq War|invasion of Iraq]]. These comments again drew criticism from some American officials, including the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]], a spokesman from which stated \"We are seeing a troubling pattern of a high official of the UN who seems to be making it his business to criticize member states and, frankly, with misplaced and misguided criticisms.\"<ref>[http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=worldNews&storyID=2006-08-02T231347Z_01_N02314381_RTRUKOC_0_US-MIDEAST-UN-MALLOCH.xml ''Reuters'', 2 August 2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070331061726/http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=worldNews |date=31 March 2007 }}</ref>\n\nMalloch Brown responded in an interview with [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]:\n:\"I don't think the US has anything to object to in the comments. I was really in fact in the interview calling for the US to reach out to France and others to make sure it was demonstrating a broad multilateral coalition and within a single news cycle of my calling for that, it was doing it.\" He added \"I may be prophetic but I wasn't critical\".<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/middle_east/july-dec06/brown_08-02.html ''PBS'' ''NewsHour'', \"Talks for International Force in Lebanon Stall in U.N.\", 2 August 2006]</ref>\n\nWhen Bolton later announced his own resignation in early December, Malloch Brown made his delight clear, telling reporters \"No comment \u2013 and you can say he said it with a smile\".<ref>Edith M. Lederer 5 December 2006;  \"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/05/AR2006120500209.html Bush Agenda Came 1st for Bolton at U.N.]\"; ''[[The Associated Press]]''.  Retrieved on 3 December 2007</ref>\n\n==UK Minister (2007\u20132009)==\nOn 27 June 2007 it was announced that Malloch Brown was joining the Government of incoming Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] as Minister of State at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] (FCO) with responsibility for Africa, Asia and the United Nations.<ref name=GuardianTran/> It was also announced that Malloch Brown would receive a [[Life peerage|peerage]] to enable him to sit in the House of Lords; he was also appointed to the [[Privy Council]]. Plans for his appointment and peerage had been leaked to ''[[The Observer]]'''s Pendennis column in November 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last=Marre |first=Oliver |date=12 November 2006 |title=Pendennis: Brown's found a new friend ... called Brown |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/nov/12/1 |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref> At the time ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' said that he \"While the aid agencies and liberals were still toasting the arrival of 'Saint Mark' to Whitehall, the neo-cons on both sides of the Atlantic were throwing darts at photographs of their devil. [He] divides opinion between those who see him as the great hope for Africa and a principled opponent of the war in Iraq, and those who believe that he is an anti-American egotist who defended Kofi Annan over the oil-for-food scandal.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sylvester |first1=Rachel |author-link1=Rachel Sylvester |last2=Thomson |first2=Alice |author-link2=Alice Thomson |date=14 July 2007 |title=Mark Malloch Brown: 'Let's not rely just on US' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1557402/Mark-Malloch-Brown-Lets-not-rely-just-on-US.html |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the decision by the [[Scottish Criminal Cases Review Commission]] ([[SCCRC]]) to refer the case of [[Abdelbaset al-Megrahi]] back for a second appeal against conviction, Dr [[Hans K\u00f6chler]], UN-appointed international observer at the [[Pan Am Flight 103 bombing trial|Lockerbie trial]], wrote on 4 July 2007 to Malloch Brown reiterating his call for a \"full and independent public inquiry of the Lockerbie case\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Kelbie |first=Paul |date=8 July 2007 |title=UN observer calls for fresh Lockerbie probe |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/jul/08/lockerbie.theobserver |newspaper=The Observer |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref> K\u00f6chler addressed the letter also to First Minister of Scotland, [[Alex Salmond]], Foreign Secretary, [[David Miliband]] and Home Secretary, [[Jacqui Smith]].<ref>[http://i-p-o.org/IPO-nr-Lockerbie-04July07.htm K\u00f6chler calls for independent inquiry into Lockerbie]</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, the conservative British magazine ''[[The Spectator]]'' drew some attention with its criticism of the Malloch Brown family's occupancy of a government-owned, so-called \"grace and favour\" apartment in London, previously used by the former Deputy Prime Minister, [[John Prescott]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rosett |first1=Claudia |author-link1=Claudia Rosett |last2=Forsyth |first2=James |author-link2=James Forsyth (journalist) |date=7 November 2007 |title=The taxpayer is being stung so this Lord can live in Admiralty House |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2007/11/the-taxpayer-is-being-stung-so-this-lord-can-live-in-admiralty-house/ |newspaper=[[The Spectator]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref> On 18 November 2007 ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' fuelled the controversy by reporting that \"some see the hand of [[David Miliband|Miliband]] behind the savaging of Malloch Brown in ''The Spectator''\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile: Lord Malloch-Brown |date=18 November 2007 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/profile-lord-malloch-brown-7hg72tlc3wb |newspaper=The Times |access-date=8 June 2018 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nOn 7 July 2009, Lord Malloch Brown announced he was stepping down from his position as Minister of State for Africa, Asia and the United Nations at the end of July 2009, citing personal and family reasons.<ref>BBC UK News, 8 July 2009, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8139632.stm Foreign Office minister resigns]</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Riddell |first=Mary |author-link=Mary Riddell |date=22 July 2009 |title=Lord Malloch-Brown interview: 'This dangerous gridlock that taints our politics' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/onthefrontline/5881753/Lord-Malloch-Brown-interview-This-dangerous-gridlock-that-taints-our-politics.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Post-ministerial career==\nMalloch Brown was appointed chairman of global affairs for [[FTI Consulting]] in September 2010.<ref>FTI Consulting (2010). {{cite web|url=http://www.fticonsulting.com/about-fti/news/press-releases/fti-consulting-appoints-lord-malloch-brown-as-chairman-global-affairs.aspx |title=FTI Consulting Appoints Lord Malloch-Brown as Chairman, Global Affairs |accessdate=2011-07-13 |url-status = bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124020906/http://www.fticonsulting.com/about-fti/news/press-releases/fti-consulting-appoints-lord-malloch-brown-as-chairman-global-affairs.aspx |archivedate=24 November 2010 |df= }}. Retrieved 13 July 2011.</ref> Consultancy appointments to oil companies [[Vitol]] and [[SouthWest Energy Ltd]] (both approved by the relevant parliamentary committee) were reported in 2010.<ref>[[The Guardian]], 30 July 2010, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/jul/30/africa-malloch-brown-oil-vitol Former Africa minister Malloch-Brown advises oil firm on African expansion]</ref>\n\nHe was a member of ''[[The Guardian]]'''s global development advisory panel. Malloch Brown contributed to the panel beside [[U2]]'s [[Bono]], the [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]]'s [[Ha-Joon Chang]] and [[Mark Weisbrot]], [[Paul Collier]] and others.<ref>{{cite news|title=Global development advisory panel|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2010/sep/14/global-development-advisory-panel|accessdate=9 March 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=14 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nMalloch Brown became chairman of the board of directors of [[SGO Corporation Limited]], a [[holding company]] whose primary asset is the election technology and [[voting machine]] manufacturer [[Smartmatic]], in 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ahmed |first=Murad |author-link=Murad Ahmed |date=24 November 2014 |title=Lord Mark Malloch-Brown to chair election technology group SGO |url=https://www.ft.com/content/ddf42272-7308-11e4-907b-00144feabdc0 |newspaper=[[Financial Times]] |access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.sgo.com/about/|website=SGO|accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref> Citing Malloch Brown's former and present relationship with politicians in the Philippines as well as his role in Smartmatic, the [[IBON Foundation]], a non-profit research organization based in the Philippines, criticized him as being \"a foreigner who made a career out of influencing elections\".<ref name=\"IBONsmart\"/>\n\n==Other==\nMalloch Brown was listed 7th in the Leaders & Revolutionaries Section of the [[Time 100]] in 2005.<ref name=UNbio/><ref>http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/completelist/0,29569,1972656,00.html</ref>\n\nOn 15 December 2006, he was named a visiting fellow at the [[Yale Center for the Study of Globalization]] and announced plans to focus on writing a book on changing leadership in a globalised world while in residence during the spring semester.<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/12/15/america/NA_GEN_US_UN_Official_Yale.php AP in ''The International Herald Tribune'', \"U.N. official named fellow at Yale\", 15 December 2006]</ref>\n\nMalloch Brown was appointed [[Order of St Michael and St George|Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) in the [[2007 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58196 |date=30 December 2006 |page=2 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nHis book ''[[The Unfinished Global Revolution]]''<ref name=\"book\">Carnegiecouncil.org, {{cite web|url=http://www.carnegiecouncil.org/resources/transcripts/0361.html |title=The Unfinished Global Revolution: discussion |accessdate=2011-03-08 |url-status = bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310020325/http://www.carnegiecouncil.org/resources/transcripts/0361.html |archivedate=10 March 2011 |df= }}, 23 February 2011</ref> came out early 2011 on Penguin Press.<ref>Robert Weiner, [http://www.unomaha.edu/idj/Issue1/Review_Weiner-UnfinishedGlobalRevel.pdf Review] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025042840/http://www.unomaha.edu/idj/Issue1/Review_Weiner-UnfinishedGlobalRevel.pdf |date=25 October 2014 }}, ID: International Dialogue, A Multidisciplinary Journal of World Affairs 1 2011</ref>\n\n===Association with George Soros===\nMalloch Brown has been closely associated with billionaire speculator [[George Soros]]. Working for [[Refugees International]], he was part of the Soros Advisory Committee on Bosnia in 1993\u201394, formed by [[George Soros]]. He has since kept cordial relations with Soros, and rented an apartment owned by Soros while working in New York on UN assignments.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nysun.com/article/15593|title=An Annan Deputy Is a Soros Tenant|newspaper=The New York Sun|date=15 June 2005|accessdate=13 July 2007}}</ref> While serving as United Nations Development Fund Administrator, Malloch Brown spoke beside Soros in 2002 suggesting that United Nations and Soros's Open Society Institute, as well as other organizations, work together to fund humanitarian functions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Press Conference \"Foreign Minister of Mexico and UNDP Administrator - March 18, 2002\"|url=https://www.un.org/ffd/pressconf/19a.htm|website=www.un.org|publisher=[[United Nations]]|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, Soros's [[Quantum Group of Funds|Quantum Fund]] announced the appointment of Malloch Brown as vice-president.<ref>[http://www.nysun.com/article/53955 Benny Avni in ''The New York Sun'', \"Ex-Deputy U.N. Chief Joins With Soros\", 7 May 2007]</ref> In September 2007, ''[[The Observer]]'' reported that he had resigned this position on becoming a government minister in the UK.<ref>[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/7days/story/0,,2170143,00.html Och, look. A new rich friend for Mr Brown] ''[[The Observer]]'', 16 September 2007</ref> Also in May 2007, Malloch Brown was named vice-chairman of [[Soros Fund Management]] and the [[Open Society Institute]], two other important Soros organisations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gppi.net/news/detail/article/mark-malloch-brown-appointed-vice-chairman-of-soros-fund-management-open-society-institute|title=Mark Malloch Brown appointed Vice-Chairman of Soros Fund Management, Open Society Institute|publisher=[[Global Public Policy Institute]]|date=21 May 2007|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120194558/http://www.gppi.net/news/detail/article/mark-malloch-brown-appointed-vice-chairman-of-soros-fund-management-open-society-institute/|archivedate=20 November 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Malloch Brown and [[FTI Consulting]] came to a legal settlement with Israeli mining billionaire [[Beny Steinmetz]], who had sued them claiming Malloch Brown had given confidential information to Soros which led to a smear campaign against Steinmetz's mining company. The out-of-court settlement of \u20ac90,000 plus costs was without any determination of liability.<ref name=telegraph-20130611>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/industry/mining/10112694/FTI-and-Lord-Malloch-Brown-settle-out-of-court-with-mining-billionaire-Beny-Steinmetz.html |title=FTI and Lord Malloch-Brown settle out of court with mining billionaire Beny Steinmetz |last=Clancy |first=Rebecca |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=11 June 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nMalloch Brown is a member of the Executive Committee of the [[International Crisis Group]],<ref>ICG, [http://www.crisisgroup.org/en/about/board.aspx Crisis Group's Board of Trustees] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110203082846/http://www.crisisgroup.org/en/about/board.aspx |date=3 February 2011 }}</ref> and played a key role in its foundation in 1993-5. In July 2014 he became Co-Chair of the Board of Trustees.<ref name=bl-cv-2017>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=34164870&privcapId=139205423 |title=Executive Profile - George Mark Malloch-Brown BA (Hons) History, MA (Political Science), KCMG |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Other honours===\n* Eminent member, [[Sergio Vieira de Mello Foundation]]\n* Honorary Patron, [[University Philosophical Society]], [[Trinity College, Dublin]].\n* Honorary President, [[London International Model United Nations|London International Model United Nations Foundation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mark Malloch Brown, Baron Malloch-Brown}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n* {{UK Peer links|parliament=lords/lord-malloch-brown/3774|hansard=|hansardcurr=5249|guardian=|publicwhip=Lord_Malloch-Brown|theywork=lord_malloch-brown|record=Mark-Malloch-Brown/1946|bbc=61505.stm|journalisted=mark-malloch-brown}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Mark Malloch Brown}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-intgov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Speth]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Administrator of the [[United Nations Development Programme]]|years=1999\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kemal Dervi\u015f]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before={{flagicon|Canada}} [[Louise Fr\u00e9chette]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Deputy Secretary-General of the United Nations]]|years=2006}}\n{{s-aft|after={{flagicon|Tanzania}} [[Asha-Rose Migiro]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new|rows=2|office}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Minister of State for Africa, Asia and the United Nations]]|years=2007\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Glenys Kinnock, Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead|Glenys Kinnock]]|as=Minister of State for Africa and the United Nations}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chris Bryant]]|as=[[Minister for Europe|Undersecretary of State for Europe and Asia]]}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baron Mawson|The Lord Mawson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron Malloch-Brown'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Baron West of Spithead|The Lord West of Spithead]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{UNDeputySG}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mallochbrown, Mark Malloch Brown, Baron}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Administrators of the United Nations Development Programme]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalene College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marlborough College]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:British officials of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Deputy Secretaries-General of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:English people of South African descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAssociation with George Soros:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1993-5 \u2192 1993\u20135", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Malloch_Brown,_Baron_Malloch-Brown"}
{"title_page": "Spencer Livermore, Baron Livermore", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Lord Livermore\n|image = \n|caption = \n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1975|06|12}}\n|birth_place = [[Slough]], UK\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|alma_mater = [[London School of Economics]]\n|occupation = [[Life Peer]] and political strategist\n|nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|spouse = [[Seb Dance]]\n}}\n\n'''Spencer Elliot Livermore, Baron Livermore''' (born 12 June 1975) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] strategy and communications professional. On 21 October 2015 he was created a [[life peer]], taking the title '''Baron Livermore''', of [[Rotherhithe]] in the [[London Borough of Southwark]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61391 |date=27 October 2015 |page=21054}}</ref>\n\nHe served as an adviser to the New Labour government from 1997 to 2008, as Director of Strategy to the [[Prime Minister]] in [[10 Downing Street]] and as Chief Strategy Adviser to the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] in the [[Treasury]].\n\nHe also served as a senior adviser on four [[General Election]] campaigns: 1997, 2001, 2005, and 2015, with ''[[The Guardian]]'' describing him as one of the most experienced election campaigners in the Labour Party.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ex-Labour campaign chief calls for report into defeat to be made public|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/19/ex-labour-campaign-chief-calls-for-report-into-defeat-to-be-made-public|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-11-22|first = Patrick Wintour Political|last = editor}}</ref> [[Philip Gould]] described him in ''The Unfinished Revolution'' as one of seven people who devised the strategy for the election-winning 2001 and 2005 general election campaigns.\n\nHe is now a partner at Britain Thinks, an international insight and strategy consultancy. He is the founder of strategic consultancy Thirty Six Strategy and was Director of Strategy at London-based communications consultancy [[Blue Rubicon]]. Previously he was Senior Strategist at advertising agency [[Saatchi & Saatchi]].\n\n== Early life ==\nLivermore grew up in [[Wickford]], [[Essex]] and attended [[Beauchamps High School]] there and [[Thurrock and Basildon College|Basildon College]], before taking a [[BSc]] (Econ) in Government at the [[London School of Economics]], whence he graduated in 1996.\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from LSE, Livermore worked for [[Gordon Brown]], then Labour's Shadow Chancellor, during the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] campaign in which the Labour Party under the leadership of [[Tony Blair]] returned to power following 18 years in opposition to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].  After the campaign he was appointed a Special Adviser in the [[Treasury]], working as a key political aide to Gordon Brown, who was then [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]. In 1998, he stood unsuccessfully as a Labour candidate for Lancaster Gate on [[Westminster City Council]], which was a safe Conservative ward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.election.demon.co.uk/wcc/lag.html|title=Lancaster Gate Ward|last=Boothroyd|first=David|date=n.d.|website=Westminster City Council Election Results|access-date=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the run-up to the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], at the request of the Chancellor, who was Chair of Strategy for the election campaign, Livermore went to work alongside the General Election co-ordinator [[Douglas Alexander]], Member of Parliament, at the Labour Party's [[Millbank Tower]] headquarters, helping to run the campaign as Director of Research.  When he returned to the Treasury after the 2001 general election, Livermore was appointed as [[Special advisers in the United Kingdom|Special Adviser]] to the Chancellor of the Exchequer.\n\nLivermore helped run the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] campaign, acting as Brown's campaign strategist, and working closely with [[Philip Gould, Baron Gould of Brookwood|Philip Gould]], after which Livermore was appointed as the most senior of Brown's advisers, as Chief Strategy Adviser to the Chancellor of the Exchequer, responsible for planning strategic communications, managing qualitative and quantitative research, and developing the Government's economic messaging. During this time, Livermore also worked on a number of US congressional campaigns.\n\nIt was subsequently reported that as Chief Strategy Adviser to the Chancellor, Livermore opposed the abolition of the 10p rate of income tax in the 2007 Budget, but was over-ruled by the Chancellor.<ref>http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/money/tax/article3934693.ece</ref>\n\nFollowing Tony Blair's resignation as Prime Minister on 27 June 2007, Gordon Brown, as the new [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]], became Prime Minister. Gordon Brown appointed Livermore to 10 Downing Street as Director of Strategy, attending [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] meetings and with responsibility for strategic planning.  He devised the strategy for Gordon Brown's leadership transition in 2007 and Brown's subsequent first 100 days.\n\nIn November 2007 ''[[Gay Times]]'' described him as the \"most powerful\" [[gay man]] in [[UK|Britain]]. In December 2007, ''Pink News'' listed him as the most powerful gay person in British politics.<ref>[http://iaindale.blogspot.com/2007/12/pink-news-publishes-top-gayers-in.html Iain Dale's Diary: Pink News Publishes 'Top Gayers in Politics' List]. Iaindale.blogspot.com (26 December 2007).</ref><ref>Writer, Staff. (27 December 2007) [http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-6417.html Profile: The most powerful gay man in British politics]. PinkNews.co.uk.</ref>\nLivermore was the first of Gordon Brown's advisers to advocate holding an early General Election in the autumn of 2007, writing the initial strategy memo to the Prime Minister setting out this course of action.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/feb/21/gordon-brown-rage-despair \"Rage, despair, indecision. Inside Gordon Brown's Number 10\"]. ''The Observer''.</ref>\n\nAfter Gordon Brown failed to call a General Election, Livermore left [[Downing Street]] in 2008 and joined advertising agency Saatchi & Saatchi as Senior Strategist, shaping strategy for clients including [[Eurostar]], the [[BBC]], and [[Asda]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/mar/17/advertising.media \"Spencer Livermore joins ad industry\"]. ''The Guardian''. (17 March 2008).</ref> He was the first of Gordon Brown's senior advisers to leave Downing Street, and was replaced in Number 10 by [[David S. Muir|David Muir]] from [[WPP Group|WPP]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/nickrobinson/2008/03/team_browns_ach.html \"Nick Robinson's Newslog: Team Brown's a-changing\"]. BBC (17 March 2008).</ref>\n\nIn September 2009 it was reported that Livermore had been asked by [[Peter Mandelson]] to return to Downing Street as Chief of Staff, and by Gordon Brown to run the planning of Labour's election campaign, but that he had declined both offers.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130505095740/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23743677-no-10-turns-to-alastair-campbell-and-gould-to-advise-inexperienced-election-team.do \"No 10 turns to Alastair Campbell and Gould to advise inexperienced election team\"]. ''London Evening Standard'' (14 September 2009).</ref>\n\nLivermore has said little publicly about his time in Downing Street, although he gave an interview to Steve Richards on [[BBC Radio 4]] in September 2010, setting out the events leading up to the 'non-election' of 2007.<ref>Grice, Andrew. (17 September 2010) [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/how-the-election-that-never-was-turned-political-allies-into-bitter-rivals-2081701.html How 'the election that never was' turned political allies into bitter rivals \u2013 UK Politics \u2013 UK]. ''The Independent''.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b00tt59k/The_Brown_Years_Episode_1/ \"The Brown Years: Episode 1\"]. BBC iPlayer (21 September 2010).</ref> He has also written on political strategy for the ''Guardian'' newspaper.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/sep/17/labour.conservatives \"Spencer Livermore: Labour's road to recovery\"]. ''The Guardian'' (13 February 2012).</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Labour\u2019s modernisers have to get beyond factionalism if they are to reclaim power {{!}} Spencer Livermore|url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/sep/27/labour-right-sect-blairites-brownites|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-11-22}}</ref>\n\nAfter Downing Street Livermore became a Director at London-based communications consultancy [[Blue Rubicon]]. He set up and had Board responsibility for the agency's Strategic Consulting arm, developing insight-based communication strategies for multinational companies, including [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]], [[Coca-Cola]], [[GlaxoSmithKline|GSK]], [[Lloyds Banking Group]], [[Centrica]], and [[McDonald's]].<ref>[http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/news/872385/Spencer-Livermore-quits-SSF-Blue-Rubicon/ Spencer Livermore quits SSF for Blue Rubicon]. Campaignlive.co.uk (9 January 2009).</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he set up Thirty Six Strategy, where he applied the techniques of political campaign strategy to advise clients on their corporate and brand positioning.<ref>[http://www.brandrepublic.com/news/1118305/blue-rubicon-launches-strategic-arm-thirty-six-strategy/ \"Blue Rubicon launches strategic arm Thirty Six Strategy\"]. ''Brand Republic''. (22 February 2012).</ref>\n\nIn December 2013 Livermore returned to the political arena when he was appointed the Labour Party's General Election Campaign Director for its unsuccessful [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]. In November 2015 he gave an interview on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[The World at One]]'', setting out why Labour lost that election.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Jeremy Corbyn not learning from Miliband defeat - Livermore|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34867129|website = BBC News|accessdate = 2015-11-22}}</ref>\n\nHe is a member of [[Labour Friends of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lfi.org.uk/in-parliament/|title=LFI Supporters in Parliament|accessdate=8 September 2019|work=Labour Friends of Israel}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSpencer is married to [[Seb Dance]], former MEP who represented the London region for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]. They live in [[Rotherhithe]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Livermore, Spencer}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:People from Slough]]\n[[Category:British special advisers]]\n[[Category:Gay peers]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Ed Miliband]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:People from Wickford]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Lord Livermore\n|image = \n|caption = \n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1975|06|12}}\n|birth_place = [[Slough]], UK\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|alma_mater = [[London School of Economics]]\n|occupation = [[Life Peer]] and political strategist\n|nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|spouse = [[Seb Dance]]\n}}\n\n'''Spencer Elliot Livermore, Baron Livermore''' (born 12 June 1975) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] strategy and communications professional. On 21 October 2015 he was created a [[life peer]], taking the title '''Baron Livermore''', of [[Rotherhithe]] in the [[London Borough of Southwark]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61391 |date=27 October 2015 |page=21054}}</ref>\n\nHe served as an adviser to the New Labour government from 1997 to 2008, as Director of Strategy to the [[Prime Minister]] in [[10 Downing Street]] and as Chief Strategy Adviser to the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] in the [[Treasury]].\n\nHe also served as a senior adviser on four [[General Election]] campaigns: 1997, 2001, 2005, and 2015, with ''[[The Guardian]]'' describing him as one of the most experienced election campaigners in the Labour Party.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ex-Labour campaign chief calls for report into defeat to be made public|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/19/ex-labour-campaign-chief-calls-for-report-into-defeat-to-be-made-public|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-11-22|first = Patrick Wintour Political|last = editor}}</ref> [[Philip Gould]] described him in ''The Unfinished Revolution'' as one of seven people who devised the strategy for the election-winning 2001 and 2005 general election campaigns.\n\nHe is now a partner at Britain Thinks, an international insight and strategy consultancy. He is the founder of strategic consultancy Thirty Six Strategy and was Director of Strategy at London-based communications consultancy [[Blue Rubicon]]. Previously he was Senior Strategist at advertising agency [[Saatchi & Saatchi]].\n\n== Early life ==\nLivermore grew up in [[Wickford]], [[Essex]] and attended [[Beauchamps High School]] there and [[Thurrock and Basildon College|Basildon College]], before taking a [[BSc]] (Econ) in Government at the [[London School of Economics]], whence he graduated in 1996.\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from LSE, Livermore worked for [[Gordon Brown]], then Labour's Shadow Chancellor, during the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] campaign in which the Labour Party under the leadership of [[Tony Blair]] returned to power following 18 years in opposition to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].  After the campaign he was appointed a Special Adviser in the [[Treasury]], working as a key political aide to Gordon Brown, who was then [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]. In 1998, he stood unsuccessfully as a Labour candidate for Lancaster Gate on [[Westminster City Council]], which was a safe Conservative ward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.election.demon.co.uk/wcc/lag.html|title=Lancaster Gate Ward|last=Boothroyd|first=David|date=n.d.|website=Westminster City Council Election Results|access-date=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the run-up to the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], at the request of the Chancellor, who was Chair of Strategy for the election campaign, Livermore went to work alongside the General Election co-ordinator [[Douglas Alexander]], Member of Parliament, at the Labour Party's [[Millbank Tower]] headquarters, helping to run the campaign as Director of Research.  When he returned to the Treasury after the 2001 general election, Livermore was appointed as [[Special advisers in the United Kingdom|Special Adviser]] to the Chancellor of the Exchequer.\n\nLivermore helped run the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] campaign, acting as Brown's campaign strategist, and working closely with [[Philip Gould, Baron Gould of Brookwood|Philip Gould]], after which Livermore was appointed as the most senior of Brown's advisers, as Chief Strategy Adviser to the Chancellor of the Exchequer, responsible for planning strategic communications, managing qualitative and quantitative research, and developing the Government's economic messaging. During this time, Livermore also worked on a number of US congressional campaigns.\n\nIt was subsequently reported that as Chief Strategy Adviser to the Chancellor, Livermore opposed the abolition of the 10p rate of income tax in the 2007 Budget, but was over-ruled by the Chancellor.<ref>http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/money/tax/article3934693.ece</ref>\n\nFollowing Tony Blair\u2019s resignation as Prime Minister on 27 June 2007, Gordon Brown, as the new [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]], became Prime Minister. Gordon Brown appointed Livermore to 10 Downing Street as Director of Strategy, attending [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] meetings and with responsibility for strategic planning.  He devised the strategy for Gordon Brown's leadership transition in 2007 and Brown's subsequent first 100 days.\n\nIn November 2007 ''[[Gay Times]]'' described him as the \"most powerful\" [[gay man]] in [[UK|Britain]]. In December 2007, ''Pink News'' listed him as the most powerful gay person in British politics.<ref>[http://iaindale.blogspot.com/2007/12/pink-news-publishes-top-gayers-in.html Iain Dale's Diary: Pink News Publishes 'Top Gayers in Politics' List]. Iaindale.blogspot.com (26 December 2007).</ref><ref>Writer, Staff. (27 December 2007) [http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-6417.html Profile: The most powerful gay man in British politics]. PinkNews.co.uk.</ref>\nLivermore was the first of Gordon Brown's advisers to advocate holding an early General Election in the autumn of 2007, writing the initial strategy memo to the Prime Minister setting out this course of action.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/feb/21/gordon-brown-rage-despair \"Rage, despair, indecision. Inside Gordon Brown's Number 10\"]. ''The Observer''.</ref>\n\nAfter Gordon Brown failed to call a General Election, Livermore left [[Downing Street]] in 2008 and joined advertising agency Saatchi & Saatchi as Senior Strategist, shaping strategy for clients including [[Eurostar]], the [[BBC]], and [[Asda]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/mar/17/advertising.media \"Spencer Livermore joins ad industry\"]. ''The Guardian''. (17 March 2008).</ref> He was the first of Gordon Brown's senior advisers to leave Downing Street, and was replaced in Number 10 by [[David S. Muir|David Muir]] from [[WPP Group|WPP]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/nickrobinson/2008/03/team_browns_ach.html \"Nick Robinson's Newslog: Team Brown's a-changing\"]. BBC (17 March 2008).</ref>\n\nIn September 2009 it was reported that Livermore had been asked by [[Peter Mandelson]] to return to Downing Street as Chief of Staff, and by Gordon Brown to run the planning of Labour's election campaign, but that he had declined both offers.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130505095740/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23743677-no-10-turns-to-alastair-campbell-and-gould-to-advise-inexperienced-election-team.do \"No 10 turns to Alastair Campbell and Gould to advise inexperienced election team\"]. ''London Evening Standard'' (14 September 2009).</ref>\n\nLivermore has said little publicly about his time in Downing Street, although he gave an interview to Steve Richards on [[BBC Radio 4]] in September 2010, setting out the events leading up to the 'non-election' of 2007.<ref>Grice, Andrew. (17 September 2010) [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/how-the-election-that-never-was-turned-political-allies-into-bitter-rivals-2081701.html How 'the election that never was' turned political allies into bitter rivals \u2013 UK Politics \u2013 UK]. ''The Independent''.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b00tt59k/The_Brown_Years_Episode_1/ \"The Brown Years: Episode 1\"]. BBC iPlayer (21 September 2010).</ref> He has also written on political strategy for the ''Guardian'' newspaper.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/sep/17/labour.conservatives \"Spencer Livermore: Labour's road to recovery\"]. ''The Guardian'' (13 February 2012).</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Labour\u2019s modernisers have to get beyond factionalism if they are to reclaim power {{!}} Spencer Livermore|url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/sep/27/labour-right-sect-blairites-brownites|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-11-22}}</ref>\n\nAfter Downing Street Livermore became a Director at London-based communications consultancy [[Blue Rubicon]]. He set up and had Board responsibility for the agency's Strategic Consulting arm, developing insight-based communication strategies for multinational companies, including [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]], [[Coca-Cola]], [[GlaxoSmithKline|GSK]], [[Lloyds Banking Group]], [[Centrica]], and [[McDonald's]].<ref>[http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/news/872385/Spencer-Livermore-quits-SSF-Blue-Rubicon/ Spencer Livermore quits SSF for Blue Rubicon]. Campaignlive.co.uk (9 January 2009).</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he set up Thirty Six Strategy, where he applied the techniques of political campaign strategy to advise clients on their corporate and brand positioning.<ref>[http://www.brandrepublic.com/news/1118305/blue-rubicon-launches-strategic-arm-thirty-six-strategy/ \"Blue Rubicon launches strategic arm Thirty Six Strategy\"]. ''Brand Republic''. (22 February 2012).</ref>\n\nIn December 2013 Livermore returned to the political arena when he was appointed the Labour Party's General Election Campaign Director for its unsuccessful [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]]. In November 2015 he gave an interview on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[The World at One]]'', setting out why Labour lost that election.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Jeremy Corbyn not learning from Miliband defeat - Livermore|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34867129|website = BBC News|accessdate = 2015-11-22}}</ref>\n\nHe is a member of [[Labour Friends of Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lfi.org.uk/in-parliament/|title=LFI Supporters in Parliament|accessdate=8 September 2019|work=Labour Friends of Israel}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSpencer is married to [[Seb Dance]], former MEP who represented the London region for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]. They live in [[Rotherhithe]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Livermore, Spencer}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:People from Slough]]\n[[Category:British special advisers]]\n[[Category:Gay peers]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Ed Miliband]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:People from Wickford]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spencer_Livermore,_Baron_Livermore"}
{"title_page": "Ruth Lister, Baroness Lister of Burtersett", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox politician\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name= The Baroness Lister of Burtersett\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE|FBA|FAcSS}}\n| image= Official portrait of Baroness Lister of Burtersett crop 2, 2019.jpg\n| office = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start = 31 January 2011<br/>[[Life peer]]age\n| term_end = \n| birth_date = 3 May 1949 (age 70)\n| death_date = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| alma_mater =\n[[University of Essex]]\n}}\n'''Margot Ruth Aline Lister, Baroness Lister of Burtersett''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|CBE|FBA|FAcSS}} (born 3 May 1949<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/90403.stm|title=Baroness Lister of Burtersett|publisher=BBC Democracy|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref>), is currently Professor of Social Policy at [[Loughborough University]]. She has written or contributed to a number of books, pamphlets and articles on poverty, social security and women's citizenship.\n\n== Biography ==\nShe was born to Dr Werner Bernard and Daphne (n\u00e9e Carter) Lister. She attended a private school and then the [[University of Essex]], from which she graduated with a BA in sociology, and continued to an MA in multi-racial studies from the [[University of Sussex]]. She has also received honorary doctorates from the Caledonian University.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essex.ac.uk/events/event.aspx?e_id=4262 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829115609/http://www.essex.ac.uk/events/event.aspx?e_id=4262 |archivedate=29 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>Who's Who 2011</ref> After completing her MA she went to work for the [[Child Poverty Action Group]].<ref>A speech presented by the Baroness Lister upon her honorary doctorate from the University of Essex on 18 July 2012.</ref>\n\nShe was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[1999 Birthday Honours]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55513 |date=12 June 1999 |page=9 |supp=y}}</ref> and in 2009 she became a [[Fellow of the British Academy]]. She was appointed to the [[House of Lords]] as a [[life peer]] on 31 January 2011 as '''Baroness Lister of Burtersett''', of [[Nottingham]] in the County of [[Nottinghamshire]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59689 |date=3 February 2011 |page=1849}}</ref> (Burtersett being the village her mother originated from). She sits as a member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111121203437/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/margot-aline/90403 ]</ref>\n\n==Employment history==\n\n===Child Poverty Action Group===\n* Legal Res. Officer, 1971\u201375\n* Assistant Director, 1975\u201377\n* Deputy Director 1977\u201379\n* Director 1979\u201387\n\n===As a professor===\n* Professor of Applied Social Studies, [[University of Bradford]], 1987\u201393\n* Professor of Social Policy, Loughborough University, 1994 onwards\n* Donald Dewar Visiting Professor of Social Justice, [[University of Glasgow]], 2005\u201306\n\n===Miscellaneous===\n* Vice-Chair, NCVO, 1991\u201393\n* Member: [[Opsahl Commission]], 1992\u201393\n* Commission for Social Justice, 1992\u201394\n* Commission on Poverty, Participation and Power, 1999\u20132000\n* Fabian Commission on Life Chances and Child Poverty, 2004\u201306\n* National Equality Panel, 2008\u201310\n* The Eleanor Rathbone Memorial Lecture, University of Leeds, 1989\n* Founding Academician, Academy of Social Sciences, 1999\n\n==Publications==\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|onlinebooksby=yes|lcheading= Lister, Ruth, 1949-}}\n* Supplementary Benefit Rights, 1974\n* Welfare Benefits, 1981\n* The Exclusive Society, 1990\n* Women's Economic Dependency and Social Security, 1992\n* Citizenship: feminist perspectives, 1997, 2nd edition 2003\n* Poverty, 2004\n* Gendering Citizenship in Western Europe, 2007\n* Co-editor of Why Money Matters, 2008\n* Understanding Theories and Concepts in Social Policy, 2010\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/l/7560/%28Margot%29%20Ruth%20Aline+LISTER.aspx Debretts profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lister Of Burtersett, Ruth Lister, Baroness}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Ed Miliband]]\n[[Category:Academics of Loughborough University]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Social Sciences]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox politician\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name= The Baroness Lister of Burtersett\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE|FBA|FAcSS}}\n| image= Official portrait of Baroness Lister of Burtersett crop 2, 2019.jpg\n| office = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start = 31 January 2011<br/>[[Life peer]]age\n| term_end = \n| birth_date = 3 May 1949 (age 70)\n| death_date = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| alma_mater =\n[[University of Essex]]\n}}\n'''Margot Ruth Aline Lister, Baroness Lister of Burtersett''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|CBE|FBA|FAcSS}} (born 3 May 1949<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/90403.stm|title=Baroness Lister of Burtersett|publisher=BBC Democracy|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref>), is currently Professor of Social Policy at [[Loughborough University]]. She has written or contributed to a number of books, pamphlets and articles on poverty, social security and women\u2019s citizenship.\n\n== Biography ==\nShe was born to Dr Werner Bernard and Daphne (n\u00e9e Carter) Lister. She attended a private school and then the [[University of Essex]], from which she graduated with a BA in sociology, and continued to an MA in multi-racial studies from the [[University of Sussex]]. She has also received honorary doctorates from the Caledonian University.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essex.ac.uk/events/event.aspx?e_id=4262 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829115609/http://www.essex.ac.uk/events/event.aspx?e_id=4262 |archivedate=29 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>Who's Who 2011</ref> After completing her MA she went to work for the [[Child Poverty Action Group]].<ref>A speech presented by the Baroness Lister upon her honorary doctorate from the University of Essex on 18 July 2012.</ref>\n\nShe was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[1999 Birthday Honours]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55513 |date=12 June 1999 |page=9 |supp=y}}</ref> and in 2009 she became a [[Fellow of the British Academy]]. She was appointed to the [[House of Lords]] as a [[life peer]] on 31 January 2011 as '''Baroness Lister of Burtersett''', of [[Nottingham]] in the County of [[Nottinghamshire]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59689 |date=3 February 2011 |page=1849}}</ref> (Burtersett being the village her mother originated from). She sits as a member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111121203437/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/margot-aline/90403 ]</ref>\n\n==Employment history==\n\n===Child Poverty Action Group===\n* Legal Res. Officer, 1971\u201375\n* Assistant Director, 1975\u201377\n* Deputy Director 1977\u201379\n* Director 1979\u201387\n\n===As a professor===\n* Professor of Applied Social Studies, [[University of Bradford]], 1987\u201393\n* Professor of Social Policy, Loughborough University, 1994 onwards\n* Donald Dewar Visiting Professor of Social Justice, [[University of Glasgow]], 2005\u201306\n\n===Miscellaneous===\n* Vice-Chair, NCVO, 1991\u201393\n* Member: [[Opsahl Commission]], 1992\u201393\n* Commission for Social Justice, 1992\u201394\n* Commission on Poverty, Participation and Power, 1999\u20132000\n* Fabian Commission on Life Chances and Child Poverty, 2004\u201306\n* National Equality Panel, 2008\u201310\n* The Eleanor Rathbone Memorial Lecture, University of Leeds, 1989\n* Founding Academician, Academy of Social Sciences, 1999\n\n==Publications==\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|onlinebooksby=yes|lcheading= Lister, Ruth, 1949-}}\n* Supplementary Benefit Rights, 1974\n* Welfare Benefits, 1981\n* The Exclusive Society, 1990\n* Women\u2019s Economic Dependency and Social Security, 1992\n* Citizenship: feminist perspectives, 1997, 2nd edition 2003\n* Poverty, 2004\n* Gendering Citizenship in Western Europe, 2007\n* Co-editor of Why Money Matters, 2008\n* Understanding Theories and Concepts in Social Policy, 2010\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/l/7560/%28Margot%29%20Ruth%20Aline+LISTER.aspx Debretts profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lister Of Burtersett, Ruth Lister, Baroness}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Ed Miliband]]\n[[Category:Academics of Loughborough University]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Social Sciences]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruth_Lister,_Baroness_Lister_of_Burtersett"}
{"title_page": "True Love Ways", "text_new": "{{short description|Single by Buddy Holly}}\n{{about|a song associated with Buddy Holly|''True Love Waits''|True Love Waits (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = True Love Ways\n| cover      = Buddy Holly True Love Ways 45 Coral.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Buddy Holly]]\n| album      = [[The Buddy Holly Story, Vol. 2]]\n| B-side     = That Makes It Tough\n| released   = {{Start date|1960|06|29}}\n| format     =\n| recorded   = October 21, 1958, [[Pythian Temple (New York City)|Pythian Temple]], [[New York City]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=47}}\n| label      = [[Coral Records|Coral]] 9-62210\n| writer     = [[Buddy Holly]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Peggy Sue Got Married (song)|Peggy Sue Got Married]]\n| prev_year  = 1959\n| next_title = Reminiscing\n| next_year  = 1962\n}}\n\"'''True Love Ways'''\" is a song attributed to [[Norman Petty]] and [[Buddy Holly]], and recorded with the [[Dick Jacobs]] Orchestra in October 1958, four months before the singer's death. It was first released on the posthumous album ''[[The Buddy Holly Story, Vol. 2]]'' (Coral 57326/757326), in March 1960. The song was a hit in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in 1960, reaching number 25 on the pop singles chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/buddy%20holly/ |title=Buddy Holly Singles in the UK |publisher=Official Charts Company |accessdate=2014-12-31}}</ref> In a 1988 re-release of the recording by MCA, the single reached no. 65 on the UK singles chart in a 5 week chart run.\n\nIn the extended version of the song, in the first ten seconds Holly can be heard preparing to sing. The audio starts with audio saying \"Yeah, we're rolling.\" A piano player and a tenor saxophone player play some notes, and Holly mutters, \"Okay,\" and clears his throat. The producer yells, \"Quiet, boys!\" to everyone else in the room, and at the end of the talkback, the producer says, \"Pitch, Ernie\", to signal the piano player to give Holly his starting note, a B-flat.\n\nAlong with [[It Doesn't Matter Anymore]], [[Raining in My Heart]], and [[Moondreams (Norman Petty song)|Moondreams]], this song was recorded at Holly's last recording session before his death on February 3, 1959.\n\nThe session took place at [[Pythian Temple (New York City)|the Pythian Temple]] on October 21, 1958.<ref>[http://www.superoldies.com/buddyholly/pythian.html The Pythian Temple Sessions. superoldies.com.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924111823/http://www.superoldies.com/buddyholly/pythian.html |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref> The musicians were [[Al Caiola]] (guitar); Sanford Block (bass); Ernie Hayes (piano); Doris Johnson (harp); Abraham Richman (saxophone); Clifford Leeman (drums); Sylvan Shulman, Leo Kruczek, Leonard Posner, Irving Spice, Ray Free, Herbert Bourne, Julius Held and Paul Winter (violins); David Schwartz and Howard Kay (violas); and Maurice Brown and Maurice Bialkin (cellos).\n\nAlthough Holly's widow, [[Maria Elena Holly]], claims that the song was written for her as a wedding gift, a listing of producer Norman Petty's productions claims that Vi Petty, Norman's wife, recorded the first version of this song on June 4, 1958\u2014two weeks prior to Buddy's first meeting with Maria.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.norvajakmusic.com/o-p.html|title=NORMAN PETTY STUDIOS Productions - Discography (O-P)|website=www.norvajakmusic.com|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref> Holly biographer Bill Griggs points out that the melody borrows heavily from the gospel song \"I'll Be All Right,\" a favorite of Holly's, and one that would be played at his funeral in 1959. According to Griggs, the framework of the melody was written by Buddy, with the remainder, and lyrics, added by Petty.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicdish.com/mag/index.php3?id=8749|title=MusicDish e-Journal - Up Close With Bill Griggs: The Number One Historian of Buddy Holly and The Crickets|website=www.musicdish.com|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref> On April 29, 2011, Mrs. Holly unveiled the never-before-seen \"True Love Ways\" photo of their wedding kiss, now displayed at P.J. Clarke's above Table 53, the table where they became engaged while on their first date, on June 20, 1958.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://truegreatoriginal.com/2011/05/true-love-ways-unveiled-buddy-hollys-great-music-great-romance/ |title=True Love Ways Unveiled \u2013 Buddy Holly\u2019s Great Music, Great Romance \u00bb Listen to Me |publisher=True Great Original |date= |accessdate=2014-03-22}}</ref>\n\nTwo albums by Buddy Holly have used the title of the song. The 1989 Telstar album reached no. 8 on the UK album chart. The 2018 Decca album with the RPO reached no. 10 on the UK album chart.\n\n==Popular Culture==\nThe song was used in a series of 2010 Egyptian commercials for Panda Cheese. They're best known as [[Never Say No to Panda]].\n\n==Single releases==\n*USA: \"True Love Ways\" b/w \"That Makes It Tough\" (Coral C62210, June 29, 1960).<ref>.[http://www.45cat.com/record/962210 True Love Ways. Buddy Holly. 45cat.com.]</ref>\n*UK: \"True Love Ways\" b/w \"[[Moondreams (Norman Petty song)|Moondreams]]\" (Coral Q72397, 20 May 1960).\n\n==Mickey Gilley version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = True Love Ways\n| cover      = True Love Ways Mickey Gilley 1980.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mickey Gilley]]\n| album      = That's All That Matters to Me\n| B-side     = That's All That Matters to Me\n| released   = [[1980 in music|1980]]\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=54}}\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Buddy Holly]]\n| producer   = [[Jim Ed Norman]]\n| prev_title = A Little Gettin' Used To\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Stand by Me (Ben E. King song)|Stand by Me]]\n| next_year  = 1980\n}}\n\n[[Mickey Gilley]], country singer, released a successful cover version in 1980 (during the height of his popularity). Gilley's version reached the No. 1 spot on the ''[[Billboard magazine]]'' [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country Singles]] chart in July 1980.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book Of Top 40 Country Hits: 1944-2006, Second edition|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=551}}</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1980)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|1|artist=Mickey Gilley}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|66|artist=Mickey Gilley}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''RPM'' Country Tracks\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n\n==Cliff Richard version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = True Love Ways\n| cover      = Cliff_Richard_True_Love_Ways_single_cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cliff Richard]] with the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n| album      = [[Dressed for the Occasion (Cliff Richard album)|Dressed for the Occasion]]\n| B-side     = Galadriel\n| released   = {{startdate|1983|04|08|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cliffrichardsongs.com/cliffuksingles/index2.htm |title=The Cliff Richard Song Database website: Discography - Singles |publisher=cliffrichardsongs.com |date= |accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n| format     = [[7 inch single|7 inch]]\n| recorded   = {{startdate|1982|11|23|df=y}}\n| studio     =\n| venue      = [[Royal Albert Hall]]\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=10}}\n| label      = [[EMI Records|EMI]]\n| writer     = [[Buddy Holly]]\n| producer   = Cliff Richard, [[Richard Hewson]]\n| prev_title = [[She Means Nothing to Me]]\n| prev_year  = 1983\n| next_title = [[Never Say Die (Give a Little Bit More)]]\n| next_year  = 1983\n}}\n\nBritish [[Pop music|pop]] singer [[Cliff Richard]] released his cover as the lead single from his ''[[Dressed for the Occasion (Cliff Richard album)|Dressed for the Occasion]]'' album in April 1983. The recording is of a live performance at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in 1982 with the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]]. Richard's version reached No. 8 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and was a hit in several other countries.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes\n| title        = Dressed for the Occasion (CD Digital Remaster)\n| others       = Cliff Richard\n| year         = 2004\n| last         = Lewry\n| first        = Peter\n| author-link  =\n| first2       = Goodall\n| last2        = Nigel\n| author-link2 =\n| type         = Liner notes\n| publisher    = [[EMI]]\n| id           =\n| location     =\n| ref          =\n}}</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1983)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{Single chart|UKsinglesbyname|8|artist=Cliff Richard|song=True Love Ways|accessdate=30 December 2014}}\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref name=\"Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992\">{{cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]]|type = doc|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book, St Ives, N.S.W |year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|35\n|-\n{{Single chart|Flanders|24|artist=Cliff Richard with The London Philharmonic Orchestra|song=True Love Ways|accessdate=30 December 2014}}\n|-\n|Ireland ([[Irish Singles Chart|IRMA]])<ref name=\"Ireland singles charts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement|title=Ireland singles charts|publisher=Irishcharts.ie|accessdate=2014-12-30}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n{{Single chart|Dutch100|41|artist=Cliff Richard with The London Philharmonic Orchestra|song=True Love Ways|accessdate=30 December 2014}}\n|-\n{{Single chart|New Zealand|45|artist=Cliff Richard with The London Philharmonic Orchestra|song=True Love Ways|accessdate=30 December 2014}}\n|}\n\n==Other notable versions==\n[[File:True Love Ways Buddy Holly sheet music 1960.jpg|thumb|1960 UK sheet music cover, Southern Music Ltd., London.]]\n* Vi Petty, wife of co-writer Norman Petty, and pianist on many Petty productions, is believed to have recorded the first version in June, 1958, with, initially, only limited promotional pressings made.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n*[[Bobby Vee]] recorded the song on his 1963 album ''I Remember Buddy Holly''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secondhandsongs.com/performance/172936 |title=Original versions of True Love Ways by Jackson Browne |publisher=SecondHandSongs |date= |accessdate=2014-03-22}}</ref>\n* [[Frank Ifield]] recorded it in the UK as the B-side of his October 1964, hit \"Summer Is Over\", on [[Columbia Records|Columbia]] DB 7355.\n* [[Peter and Gordon]]'s 1965 Capitol remake hit #14 on the Billboard Hot 100. It also reached #2 in the UK and #4 in Ireland, released in April 1965 on [[Columbia Graphophone Company|Columbia]] DB 7524.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/peter%20%26%20gordon/ |title=Cover version of True Love Ways by Peter and Gordon |publisher=Official Charts Company |accessdate=2014-12-31}}</ref>\n* [[Dick Rivers]], a French singer, recorded an adaptation (in French) as \"Ne pleure pas\" (1965)\n* [[Jimmy Jones (singer)|Jimmy Jones]] released the song as a 45 single in 1967.\n* [[Skeeter Davis]] recorded the song in 1967.\n* [[Gary Busey]] made a cover version of this song in the [[biographical]] film ''[[The Buddy Holly Story]]'' (1978) and its album.\n* [[Ricky Nelson]]'s version is recorded in winter 1978/1979, but was left unreleased from the album ''Rockabilly Renaissance''. It was released in May 1986 after Nelson's death on the album ''The Memphis Sessions''.\n* [[Elvis Costello]] released a live version of the song in 2005 recorded in 1986.\n* [[Joan Jett]] performed the song in the film ''[[Light of Day]]'' (1987).\n* [[Johnny Mathis]] on the 1989 album ''In the Still of the Night''.\n* [[David Essex]] and [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]] made a duet on his 1994 album. The single reached no. 38 on the UK singles chart.\n* [[The Mavericks]] covered the song on their 1996 tribute album ''[[Not Fade Away (Remembering Buddy Holly)]]''.\n* [[Robson & Jerome]] recorded a version for their 1996 album ''[[Take Two (Robson & Jerome album)]]''\n* [[Erasure]] recorded the song for their 2003 album ''[[Other People's Songs]]''.\n* [[Martina McBride]] recorded the song on 2005 album ''[[Timeless (Martina McBride album)|Timeless]]''\n* [[Aaron Watson]] recorded a version of the song on his 2006 album ''San Angelo''.\n* [[My Morning Jacket]] covered the song for the tribute album ''[[Rave On Buddy Holly]]'', released in June 2011.\n* [[Jackson Browne]] recorded a cover version for his September 2011 tribute album, ''[[Listen to Me: Buddy Holly]]''.\n* [[Never Say No to Panda|A series of commercials]] for the product Panda Cheese, from the [[Egypt]]ian company Arab Dairy, uses the [[Buddy Holly]] & [[The Picks]] version of the song as the theme tune of its unpredictable and destructive panda mascot. The commercials featuring the song became an instant hit in the internet and now an [[internet meme]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Metcalfe |first=John |url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/global/2010/09/creepy-egyptian-cheese-ads-explain-geopolitics/18824/ |title=Creepy Egyptian Cheese Ads Explain Geopolitics - The Wire |publisher=Theatlanticwire.com |date=2010-09-23 |accessdate=2014-03-22}}</ref>\nAnna Nalick version 2019\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|buddy-holly|true-love-ways}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Buddy Holly}}\n{{Mickey Gilley}}\n{{Cliff Richard singles}}\n{{David Essex}}\n\n[[Category:1958 songs]]\n[[Category:1960 singles]]\n[[Category:1980 singles]]\n[[Category:Buddy Holly songs]]\n[[Category:Bobby Vee songs]]\n[[Category:Peter and Gordon songs]]\n[[Category:Mickey Gilley songs]]\n[[Category:Cliff Richard songs]]\n[[Category:Johnny Mathis songs]]\n[[Category:David Essex songs]]\n[[Category:The Mavericks songs]]\n[[Category:Martina McBride songs]]\n[[Category:Jackson Browne songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot Country Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Buddy Holly]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Norman Petty]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jim Ed Norman]]\n[[Category:RPM Country Tracks number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs released posthumously]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Coral Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Single by Buddy Holly}}\n{{about|a song associated with Buddy Holly|''True Love Waits''|True Love Waits (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = True Love Ways\n| cover      = Buddy Holly True Love Ways 45 Coral.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Buddy Holly]]\n| album      = [[The Buddy Holly Story, Vol. 2]]\n| B-side     = That Makes It Tough\n| released   = {{Start date|1960|06|29}}\n| format     =\n| recorded   = October 21, 1958, [[Pythian Temple (New York City)|Pythian Temple]], [[New York City]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=47}}\n| label      = [[Coral Records|Coral]] 9-62210\n| writer     = [[Buddy Holly]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Peggy Sue Got Married (song)|Peggy Sue Got Married]]\n| prev_year  = 1959\n| next_title = Reminiscing\n| next_year  = 1962\n}}\n\"'''True Love Ways'''\" is a song attributed to [[Norman Petty]] and [[Buddy Holly]], and recorded with the [[Dick Jacobs]] Orchestra in October 1958, four months before the singer's death. It was first released on the posthumous album ''[[The Buddy Holly Story, Vol. 2]]'' (Coral 57326/757326), in March 1960. The song was a hit in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in 1960, reaching number 25 on the pop singles chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/buddy%20holly/ |title=Buddy Holly Singles in the UK |publisher=Official Charts Company |accessdate=2014-12-31}}</ref> In an 1988 re-release of the recording by MCA, the single reached no. 65 on the UK singles chart in a 5 week chart run.\n\nIn the extended version of the song, in the first ten seconds Holly can be heard preparing to sing. The audio starts with audio saying \"Yeah, we're rolling.\" A piano player and a tenor saxophone player play some notes, and Holly mutters, \"Okay,\" and clears his throat. The producer yells, \"Quiet, boys!\" to everyone else in the room, and at the end of the talkback, the producer says, \"Pitch, Ernie\", to signal the piano player to give Holly his starting note, a B-flat.\n\nAlong with [[It Doesn't Matter Anymore]], [[Raining in My Heart]], and [[Moondreams_(Norman_Petty_song)|Moondreams]], this song was recorded at Holly's last recording session before his death on February 3, 1959.\n\nThe session took place at [[Pythian Temple (New York City)|the Pythian Temple]] on October 21, 1958.<ref>[http://www.superoldies.com/buddyholly/pythian.html The Pythian Temple Sessions. superoldies.com.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924111823/http://www.superoldies.com/buddyholly/pythian.html |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref> The musicians were [[Al Caiola]] (guitar); Sanford Block (bass); Ernie Hayes (piano); Doris Johnson (harp); Abraham Richman (saxophone); Clifford Leeman (drums); Sylvan Shulman, Leo Kruczek, Leonard Posner, Irving Spice, Ray Free, Herbert Bourne, Julius Held and Paul Winter (violins); David Schwartz and Howard Kay (violas); and Maurice Brown and Maurice Bialkin (cellos).\n\nAlthough Holly's widow, [[Maria Elena Holly]], claims that the song was written for her as a wedding gift, a listing of producer Norman Petty's productions claims that Vi Petty, Norman's wife, recorded the first version of this song on June 4, 1958\u2014two weeks prior to Buddy's first meeting with Maria.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.norvajakmusic.com/o-p.html|title=NORMAN PETTY STUDIOS Productions - Discography (O-P)|website=www.norvajakmusic.com|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref> Holly biographer Bill Griggs points out that the melody borrows heavily from the gospel song \"I'll Be All Right,\" a favorite of Holly's, and one that would be played at his funeral in 1959. According to Griggs, the framework of the melody was written by Buddy, with the remainder, and lyrics, added by Petty.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicdish.com/mag/index.php3?id=8749|title=MusicDish e-Journal - Up Close With Bill Griggs: The Number One Historian of Buddy Holly and The Crickets|website=www.musicdish.com|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref> On April 29, 2011, Mrs. Holly unveiled the never-before-seen \"True Love Ways\" photo of their wedding kiss, now displayed at P.J. Clarke's above Table 53, the table where they became engaged while on their first date, on June 20, 1958.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://truegreatoriginal.com/2011/05/true-love-ways-unveiled-buddy-hollys-great-music-great-romance/ |title=True Love Ways Unveiled \u2013 Buddy Holly\u2019s Great Music, Great Romance \u00bb Listen to Me |publisher=True Great Original |date= |accessdate=2014-03-22}}</ref>\n\nTwo albums by Buddy Holly have used the title of the song. The 1989 Telstar album reached no. 8 on the UK album chart. The 2018 Decca album with the RPO reached no. 10 on the UK album chart.\n\n==Popular Culture==\nThe song was used in a series of 2010 Egyptian commercials for Panda Cheese. They're best known as [[Never Say No to Panda]].\n\n==Single releases==\n*USA: \"True Love Ways\" b/w \"That Makes It Tough\" (Coral C62210, June 29, 1960).<ref>.[http://www.45cat.com/record/962210 True Love Ways. Buddy Holly. 45cat.com.]</ref>\n*UK: \"True Love Ways\" b/w \"[[Moondreams (Norman Petty song)|Moondreams]]\" (Coral Q72397, 20 May 1960).\n\n==Mickey Gilley version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = True Love Ways\n| cover      = True Love Ways Mickey Gilley 1980.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mickey Gilley]]\n| album      = That's All That Matters to Me\n| B-side     = That's All That Matters to Me\n| released   = [[1980 in music|1980]]\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=54}}\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Buddy Holly]]\n| producer   = [[Jim Ed Norman]]\n| prev_title = A Little Gettin' Used To\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Stand by Me (Ben E. King song)|Stand by Me]]\n| next_year  = 1980\n}}\n\n[[Mickey Gilley]], country singer, released a successful cover version in 1980 (during the height of his popularity). Gilley's version reached the No. 1 spot on the ''[[Billboard magazine]]'' [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country Singles]] chart in July 1980.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book Of Top 40 Country Hits: 1944-2006, Second edition|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=551}}</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1980)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|1|artist=Mickey Gilley}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|66|artist=Mickey Gilley}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''RPM'' Country Tracks\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n\n==Cliff Richard version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = True Love Ways\n| cover      = Cliff_Richard_True_Love_Ways_single_cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cliff Richard]] with the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n| album      = [[Dressed for the Occasion (Cliff Richard album)|Dressed for the Occasion]]\n| B-side     = Galadriel\n| released   = {{startdate|1983|04|08|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cliffrichardsongs.com/cliffuksingles/index2.htm |title=The Cliff Richard Song Database website: Discography - Singles |publisher=cliffrichardsongs.com |date= |accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n| format     = [[7 inch single|7 inch]]\n| recorded   = {{startdate|1982|11|23|df=y}}\n| studio     =\n| venue      = [[Royal Albert Hall]]\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=10}}\n| label      = [[EMI Records|EMI]]\n| writer     = [[Buddy Holly]]\n| producer   = Cliff Richard, [[Richard Hewson]]\n| prev_title = [[She Means Nothing to Me]]\n| prev_year  = 1983\n| next_title = [[Never Say Die (Give a Little Bit More)]]\n| next_year  = 1983\n}}\n\nBritish [[Pop music|pop]] singer [[Cliff Richard]] released his cover as the lead single from his ''[[Dressed for the Occasion (Cliff Richard album)|Dressed for the Occasion]]'' album in April 1983. The recording is of a live performance at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in 1982 with the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]]. Richard's version reached No. 8 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and was a hit in several other countries.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes\n| title        = Dressed for the Occasion (CD Digital Remaster)\n| others       = Cliff Richard\n| year         = 2004\n| last         = Lewry\n| first        = Peter\n| author-link  =\n| first2       = Goodall\n| last2        = Nigel\n| author-link2 =\n| type         = Liner notes\n| publisher    = [[EMI]]\n| id           =\n| location     =\n| ref          =\n}}</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1983)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{Single chart|UKsinglesbyname|8|artist=Cliff Richard|song=True Love Ways|accessdate=30 December 2014}}\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref name=\"Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992\">{{cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]]|type = doc|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book, St Ives, N.S.W |year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|35\n|-\n{{Single chart|Flanders|24|artist=Cliff Richard with The London Philharmonic Orchestra|song=True Love Ways|accessdate=30 December 2014}}\n|-\n|Ireland ([[Irish Singles Chart|IRMA]])<ref name=\"Ireland singles charts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement|title=Ireland singles charts|publisher=Irishcharts.ie|accessdate=2014-12-30}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n{{Single chart|Dutch100|41|artist=Cliff Richard with The London Philharmonic Orchestra|song=True Love Ways|accessdate=30 December 2014}}\n|-\n{{Single chart|New Zealand|45|artist=Cliff Richard with The London Philharmonic Orchestra|song=True Love Ways|accessdate=30 December 2014}}\n|}\n\n==Other notable versions==\n[[File:True Love Ways Buddy Holly sheet music 1960.jpg|thumb|1960 UK sheet music cover, Southern Music Ltd., London.]]\n* Vi Petty, wife of co-writer Norman Petty, and pianist on many Petty productions, is believed to have recorded the first version in June, 1958, with, initially, only limited promotional pressings made.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n*[[Bobby Vee]] recorded the song on his 1963 album ''I Remember Buddy Holly''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secondhandsongs.com/performance/172936 |title=Original versions of True Love Ways by Jackson Browne |publisher=SecondHandSongs |date= |accessdate=2014-03-22}}</ref>\n* [[Frank Ifield]] recorded it in the UK as the B-side of his October 1964, hit \"Summer Is Over\", on [[Columbia Records|Columbia]] DB 7355.\n* [[Peter and Gordon]]'s 1965 Capitol remake hit #14 on the Billboard Hot 100. It also reached #2 in the UK and #4 in Ireland, released in April 1965 on [[Columbia Graphophone Company|Columbia]] DB 7524.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/peter%20%26%20gordon/ |title=Cover version of True Love Ways by Peter and Gordon |publisher=Official Charts Company |accessdate=2014-12-31}}</ref>\n* [[Dick Rivers]], a French singer, recorded an adaptation (in French) as \"Ne pleure pas\" (1965)\n* [[Jimmy Jones (singer)|Jimmy Jones]] released the song as a 45 single in 1967.\n* [[Skeeter Davis]] recorded the song in 1967.\n* [[Gary Busey]] made a cover version of this song in the [[biographical]] film ''[[The Buddy Holly Story]]'' (1978) and its album.\n* [[Ricky Nelson]]'s version is recorded in winter 1978/1979, but was left unreleased from the album ''Rockabilly Renaissance''. It was released in May 1986 after Nelson's death on the album ''The Memphis Sessions''.\n* [[Elvis Costello]] released a live version of the song in 2005 recorded in 1986.\n* [[Joan Jett]] performed the song in the film ''[[Light of Day]]'' (1987).\n* [[Johnny Mathis]] on the 1989 album ''In the Still of the Night''.\n* [[David Essex]] and [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]] made a duet on his 1994 album. The single reached no. 38 on the UK singles chart.\n* [[The Mavericks]] covered the song on their 1996 tribute album ''[[Not Fade Away (Remembering Buddy Holly)]]''.\n* [[Robson & Jerome]] recorded a version for their 1996 album ''[[Take Two (Robson & Jerome album)]]''\n* [[Erasure]] recorded the song for their 2003 album ''[[Other People's Songs]]''.\n* [[Martina McBride]] recorded the song on 2005 album ''[[Timeless (Martina McBride album)|Timeless]]''\n* [[Aaron Watson]] recorded a version of the song on his 2006 album ''San Angelo''.\n* [[My Morning Jacket]] covered the song for the tribute album ''[[Rave On Buddy Holly]]'', released in June 2011.\n* [[Jackson Browne]] recorded a cover version for his September 2011 tribute album, ''[[Listen to Me: Buddy Holly]]''.\n* [[Never Say No to Panda|A series of commercials]] for the product Panda Cheese, from the [[Egypt]]ian company Arab Dairy, uses the [[Buddy Holly]] & [[The Picks]] version of the song as the theme tune of its unpredictable and destructive panda mascot. The commercials featuring the song became an instant hit in the internet and now an [[internet meme]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Metcalfe |first=John |url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/global/2010/09/creepy-egyptian-cheese-ads-explain-geopolitics/18824/ |title=Creepy Egyptian Cheese Ads Explain Geopolitics - The Wire |publisher=Theatlanticwire.com |date=2010-09-23 |accessdate=2014-03-22}}</ref>\nAnna Nalick version 2019\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|buddy-holly|true-love-ways}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Buddy Holly}}\n{{Mickey Gilley}}\n{{Cliff Richard singles}}\n{{David Essex}}\n\n[[Category:1958 songs]]\n[[Category:1960 singles]]\n[[Category:1980 singles]]\n[[Category:Buddy Holly songs]]\n[[Category:Bobby Vee songs]]\n[[Category:Peter and Gordon songs]]\n[[Category:Mickey Gilley songs]]\n[[Category:Cliff Richard songs]]\n[[Category:Johnny Mathis songs]]\n[[Category:David Essex songs]]\n[[Category:The Mavericks songs]]\n[[Category:Martina McBride songs]]\n[[Category:Jackson Browne songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot Country Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Buddy Holly]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Norman Petty]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jim Ed Norman]]\n[[Category:RPM Country Tracks number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs released posthumously]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Coral Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo/generalfixes, replaced: an 1988 \u2192 a 1988", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/True_Love_Ways"}
{"title_page": "Denise Kingsmill, Baroness Kingsmill", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:Denise Kingsmill, Baroness Kingsmill.jpg|thumb|Baroness Kingsmill in 2011]]\n'''Denise Patricia Byrne Kingsmill, Baroness Kingsmill''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 24 April 1947 n\u00e9e Byrne) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[peerage|peer]]. She was appointed as a life peer in 2006<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4896620.stm|title=New working life peers unveiled|date=11 April 2006|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref> after practising as a solicitor in personal injury, trade union and employment law. \n\nShe was born in [[New Zealand]] and emigrated to [[Wales]] during her childhood. She studied at [[Croesyceiliog School]].  Baroness Kingsmill holds a degree in Economics and Anthropology from [[Girton College]], [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]]. Baroness Kingsmill is a member of the [[Economic Affairs Committee (House of Lords)|Economic Affairs Committee]].\n\nShe was a Deputy Chairman of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission (later known as The Competition Commission), which undertook inquiries into banking, cruise liners, equity underwriting, energy supply, and other subjects during her time. She was appointed in 1996, stepping down in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/press_rel/archive/2003/jun/html/19-03.htm |title=Denise Kingsmill to Step Down from Competition Commission this Autumn |publisher=Competition-commission.org.uk |date=2003-06-09 |accessdate=2011-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203033247/http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/press_rel/archive/2003/jun/html/19-03.htm |archive-date=3 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBaroness Kingsmill undertook a number of cases relating to rights of women, while specialising in employment law and also acted in behalf of Peter Wood, founder of Direct Line and other leading business figures. She further undertook two inquiries for the government in gender equality and human capital management.<ref>{{cite news|author=Finance |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2745138/A-hammer-for-the-glass-ceiling.html |title=A hammer for the glass ceiling |publisher=Telegraph |date= 2001-12-10|accessdate=2011-11-05 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nBaroness Kingsmill was awarded a [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] for her services to competition and employment law in the [[2000 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55710 |date=31 December 1999|page=10 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nShe was created '''Baroness Kingsmill''', of [[Holland Park]] in the [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]] on 1 June 2006.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58003 |date=6 June 1006 |page=7729}}</ref>\n\nKingsmill has been awarded five honorary doctorates from universities across England, Scotland and Wales, including a doctorate from Cranfield University in 2007 in recognition of her distinguished achievements in business and in public life <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cranfield.ac.uk/alumni/graduation/hongrads/page7485.html |title=Cranfield University 2007 - Honorary Graduates |publisher=Cranfield.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-11-05}}</ref>).\n\nOther roles she holds or has held include:\n* non-executive director of IAG (International Airlines Group) \n* non-executive director of E.ON (German Energy Company) \n* non-executive director of KornFerry International (world's largest executive search firm)\n* Member of international advisory board of [[IESE Business School]]<ref>[https://www.iese.edu/about/leadership/ ''Members of IESE's International Advisory Board''], iese.edu</ref>.\n* Deputy Chairman of the Advisory board at Price Waterhouse Coopers\n* Member of the Advisory board at [[Inditex]] (Zara) \n* Member of the Board of Directors of [[Inditex]] (appointed on 19 July 2016)<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/economia/20160719/403330876475/baronesa-denise-kingsmill-inditex-consejera-amancio-ortega.html|journal=[[La Vanguardia]]|title=La baronesa Kingsmill, la nueva consejera de Amancio Ortega|date=19 July 2016}}</ref>\nKingsmill writes a monthly column for ''Management Today'' magazine. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.managementtoday.co.uk/news/1071176/Denise-Kingsmill-Getting-grip-pay |title=Denise Kingsmill: Getting a grip on pay - Leadership, business and management news, tips and features from MT and Management Today magazine |publisher=Managementtoday.co.uk |date=2011-06-01 |accessdate=2011-11-05}}</ref>\n\nPrevious roles include:\n* non-executive director of [[Betfair]]\n* Non-executive directorship of [[British Airways]]\n* Senior adviser to the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efinancialnews.com/story/2008-07-15/rbs-senior-adviser-to-review-coutts|title=RBS senior adviser to review Coutts|last=Wilkinson|first=Tara|date=15 Jul 2008|publisher=Financial News|accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref>\n* Trustee of the [[Cambridge University]] [[Judge Business School]]\n* Pro-chancellor of [[Brunel University]]\n* Trustee of [[Design Museum|The Design Museum]]\n*Chairman of the Board at [[Monzo (bank)|Monzo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monzo.com/static/docs/annual-report-2018.pdf|title=Monzo Bank Annual Report and Accounts 2018|last=Kingsmill|first=Denise|date=6 April 2018|website=https://monzo.com}}</ref>\n\nShe has held other non-executive director and advisory roles, including Laing O\u2019Rourke, Royal Bank of Scotland and Telewest Communications.  \n\nA former partner in a firm of London solicitors, Kingsmill, along with two other defendants - His Honour Judge Peter Clark and DJ Freeman & Co solicitors (the relevant firm) - was found liable for professional negligence by the Court of Appeal in 2001 for advice given in the late 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2001/934.html |title=Griffin v Kingsmill & Ors [2001&#93; EWCA Civ 934 (8 June 2001) |publisher=Bailii.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-05}}</ref>  Kingsmill has said that she defends this as a 'professional judgment' which she would take again:<ref>{{cite news|author=Jane Martinson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/jan/05/politics.genderissues |title=Interview: Denise Kingsmill &#124; Business |publisher=The Guardian |date= 2007-01-05|accessdate=2011-11-05 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kingsmill, Denise, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British solicitors]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People associated with Brunel University London]]\n[[Category:People educated at Croesyceiliog Grammar School]]\n[[Category:New Zealand emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Directors of Inditex]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:Denise Kingsmill, Baroness Kingsmill.jpg|thumb|Baroness Kingsmill in 2011]]\n'''Denise Patricia Byrne Kingsmill, Baroness Kingsmill''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (born 24 April 1947 n\u00e9e Byrne) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[peerage|peer]]. She was appointed as a life peer in 2006<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4896620.stm|title=New working life peers unveiled|date=11 April 2006|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref> after practising as a solicitor in personal injury, trade union and employment law. \n\nShe was born in [[New Zealand]] and emigrated to [[Wales]] during her childhood. She studied at [[Croesyceiliog School]].  Baroness Kingsmill holds a degree in Economics and Anthropology from [[Girton College]], [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]]. Baroness Kingsmill is a member of the [[Economic Affairs Committee (House of Lords)|Economic Affairs Committee]].\n\nShe was a Deputy Chairman of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission (later known as The Competition Commission), which undertook inquiries into banking, cruise liners, equity underwriting, energy supply, and other subjects during her time. She was appointed in 1996, stepping down in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/press_rel/archive/2003/jun/html/19-03.htm |title=Denise Kingsmill to Step Down from Competition Commission this Autumn |publisher=Competition-commission.org.uk |date=2003-06-09 |accessdate=2011-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203033247/http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/press_rel/archive/2003/jun/html/19-03.htm |archive-date=3 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBaroness Kingsmill undertook a number of cases relating to rights of women, while specialising in employment law and also acted in behalf of Peter Wood, founder of Direct Line and other leading business figures. She further undertook two inquiries for the government in gender equality and human capital management.<ref>{{cite news|author=Finance |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/2745138/A-hammer-for-the-glass-ceiling.html |title=A hammer for the glass ceiling |publisher=Telegraph |date= 2001-12-10|accessdate=2011-11-05 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nBaroness Kingsmill was awarded a [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] for her services to competition and employment law in the [[2000 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55710 |date=31 December 1999|page=10 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nShe was created '''Baroness Kingsmill''', of [[Holland Park]] in the [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]] on 1 June 2006.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58003 |date=6 June 1006 |page=7729}}</ref>\n\nKingsmill has been awarded five honorary doctorates from universities across England, Scotland and Wales, including a doctorate from Cranfield University in 2007 in recognition of her distinguished achievements in business and in public life <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cranfield.ac.uk/alumni/graduation/hongrads/page7485.html |title=Cranfield University 2007 - Honorary Graduates |publisher=Cranfield.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-11-05}}</ref>).\n\nOther roles she holds or has held include:\n* non-executive director of IAG (International Airlines Group) \n* non-executive director of E.ON (German Energy Company) \n* non-executive director of KornFerry International (world\u2019s largest executive search firm)\n* Member of international advisory board of [[IESE Business School]]<ref>[https://www.iese.edu/about/leadership/ ''Members of IESE's International Advisory Board''], iese.edu</ref>.\n* Deputy Chairman of the Advisory board at Price Waterhouse Coopers\n* Member of the Advisory board at [[Inditex]] (Zara) \n* Member of the Board of Directors of [[Inditex]] (appointed on 19 July 2016)<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/economia/20160719/403330876475/baronesa-denise-kingsmill-inditex-consejera-amancio-ortega.html|journal=[[La Vanguardia]]|title=La baronesa Kingsmill, la nueva consejera de Amancio Ortega|date=19 July 2016}}</ref>\nKingsmill writes a monthly column for ''Management Today'' magazine. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.managementtoday.co.uk/news/1071176/Denise-Kingsmill-Getting-grip-pay |title=Denise Kingsmill: Getting a grip on pay - Leadership, business and management news, tips and features from MT and Management Today magazine |publisher=Managementtoday.co.uk |date=2011-06-01 |accessdate=2011-11-05}}</ref>\n\nPrevious roles include:\n* non-executive director of [[Betfair]]\n* Non-executive directorship of [[British Airways]]\n* Senior adviser to the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efinancialnews.com/story/2008-07-15/rbs-senior-adviser-to-review-coutts|title=RBS senior adviser to review Coutts|last=Wilkinson|first=Tara|date=15 Jul 2008|publisher=Financial News|accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref>\n* Trustee of the [[Cambridge University]] [[Judge Business School]]\n* Pro-chancellor of [[Brunel University]]\n* Trustee of [[Design Museum|The Design Museum]]\n*Chairman of the Board at [[Monzo (bank)|Monzo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monzo.com/static/docs/annual-report-2018.pdf|title=Monzo Bank Annual Report and Accounts 2018|last=Kingsmill|first=Denise|date=6 April 2018|website=https://monzo.com}}</ref>\n\nShe has held other non-executive director and advisory roles, including Laing O\u2019Rourke, Royal Bank of Scotland and Telewest Communications.  \n\nA former partner in a firm of London solicitors, Kingsmill, along with two other defendants - His Honour Judge Peter Clark and DJ Freeman & Co solicitors (the relevant firm) - was found liable for professional negligence by the Court of Appeal in 2001 for advice given in the late 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWCA/Civ/2001/934.html |title=Griffin v Kingsmill & Ors [2001&#93; EWCA Civ 934 (8 June 2001) |publisher=Bailii.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-05}}</ref>  Kingsmill has said that she defends this as a 'professional judgment' which she would take again:<ref>{{cite news|author=Jane Martinson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/jan/05/politics.genderissues |title=Interview: Denise Kingsmill &#124; Business |publisher=The Guardian |date= 2007-01-05|accessdate=2011-11-05 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kingsmill, Denise, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British solicitors]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People associated with Brunel University London]]\n[[Category:People educated at Croesyceiliog Grammar School]]\n[[Category:New Zealand emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Directors of Inditex]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denise_Kingsmill,_Baroness_Kingsmill"}
{"title_page": "Rosalind Howells, Baroness Howells of St Davids", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Baroness Howells of St Davids\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1931|1|10}}\n| image = Official portrait of Baroness Howells of St Davids crop 2.jpg\n| birth_place = [[Saint David Parish, Grenada|St Davids]], [[Grenada]]\n| spouse = John Charles Howells (m. 1955)\n| children = 2\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| office = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| termstart = 21 July 1999\n| termend = 10 January 2019\n| education = [[St Joseph's College, Reading]]<br>[[South West London College]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of the District of Columbia]]\n}}\n\n'''Rosalind Patricia-Anne Howells, Baroness Howells of St Davids''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 10 January 1931) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician, who formerly served as member of the [[House of Lords]].<ref>[https://hansard.parliament.uk/lords/2019-1-10/debates/F2774523-354F-477D-97A7-094399415EFE/RetirementOfAMemberBaronessHowellsOfStDavids][[Hansard]]<span>: \"Retirement of a Member: Baroness Howells of St Davids\"</span></ref> \n\nHaving been awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] in the 1994 [[New Year's Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=53527 |date=31 December 1993 |page=12 |supp=y}}</ref> she was made a [[Life peer]] as Baroness Howells of St Davids, of Charlton in the [[Royal Borough of Greenwich|London Borough of Greenwich]] on 21 July 1999.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55564 |date=27 July 1999 |page=8076}}</ref> The name [[Saint David Parish, Grenada|St Davids]] refers to the parish in [[Grenada]] where she was brought up, to the south-east of the Island. She retired from the House of Lords on 10 January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-howells-of-st-davids/2486|title=Baroness Howells of St Davids|website=UK Parliament|language=English|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nHowells was educated at [[St Joseph's College, Reading]], [[South West London College]] and the [[University of the District of Columbia]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] In 1955, she married John Charles Howells and they have two daughters.\n\nHowells served as the Director of the [[Greenwich]] Racial Equality Council as well as a Community and Equal Opportunities Worker. Baroness Howells is a trustee of the [[Stephen Lawrence]] Charitable Trust, and served as the unofficial advisor to the Lawrence family.\n\nHowells was the first black woman to sit on the GLC's Training Board; the first female member of the Court of Governors of the University of Greenwich and was the Vice Chair at the [[London Voluntary Service Council]]. She has worked with the Carnival Liaison Committee, the Greater London Action in Race Equality, and has been an active campaigner for justice in the field of race relations. She is a Trustee of the [[Jason Roberts (footballer)|Jason Roberts]] Foundation, which aims to provide a range of sporting opportunities for children and young people in the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Grenada]].<ref>[http://jasonrobertsfoundation.com/thetrustees.htm Jason Roberts Foundation website.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809082131/http://jasonrobertsfoundation.com/thetrustees.htm |date=9 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009 she was inaugurated as the Chancellor of the [[University of Bedfordshire]] in [[Luton]].<ref>[http://www.beds.ac.uk/news/2009/mar/090319-chancellor \"Baroness Howells announced as new University Chancellor\", University of Bedfordshire, 19 March 2009.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330003954/http://www.beds.ac.uk/news/2009/mar/090319-chancellor |date=30 March 2010 }}</ref> Baroness Howells is a trustee of St George's University's UK Trust and serves on the board of the [[Windward Islands]] Research and Education Foundation (WINDREF), the research institute affiliated with [[St. George's University]].<ref>[http://www.sgu.edu/news-events/news-archives13-over-80-global-scholars-wcc.html#sthash.bFpBWp6g.dpuf St George\u2019s University.]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199899/minutes/991025/ldminute.htm Announcement of her introduction at the House of Lords] House of Lords minutes of proceedings, 25 October 1999.\n*[http://www.100greatblackbritons.com/bios/baroness_roselind_howells.html 100 Great Black Britons.]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[University of Bedfordshire|Chancellor of the University of Bedfordshire]]\n  | years  = 2009&ndash;2014\n  | before = ?\n  | after = [[John Bercow]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Howells, Rosalind Baroness Howells of St Davids}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers|Howells of St Davids, Rosalind Howells, Baron]]\n[[Category:Female life peers|Howells of St Davids, Rosalind Howells, Baron]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Grenadian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Black British politicians]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Bedfordshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Baroness Howells of St Davids\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1931|1|10}}\n| image = Official portrait of Baroness Howells of St Davids crop 2.jpg\n| birth_place = [[Saint David Parish, Grenada|St Davids]], [[Grenada]]\n| spouse = John Charles Howells (m. 1955)\n| children = 2\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| office = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n| termstart = 21 July 1999\n| termend = 10 January 2019\n| education = [[St Joseph's College, Reading]]<br>[[South West London College]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of the District of Columbia]]\n}}\n\n'''Rosalind Patricia-Anne Howells, Baroness Howells of St Davids''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 10 January 1931) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician, who formerly served as member of the [[House of Lords]].<ref>[https://hansard.parliament.uk/lords/2019-1-10/debates/F2774523-354F-477D-97A7-094399415EFE/RetirementOfAMemberBaronessHowellsOfStDavids][[Hansard]]<span>: \"Retirement of a Member: Baroness Howells of St Davids\"</span></ref> \n\nHaving been awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] in the 1994 [[New Year's Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=53527 |date=31 December 1993 |page=12 |supp=y}}</ref> she was made a [[Life peer]] as Baroness Howells of St Davids, of Charlton in the [[Royal Borough of Greenwich|London Borough of Greenwich]] on 21 July 1999.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55564 |date=27 July 1999 |page=8076}}</ref> The name [[Saint David Parish, Grenada|St Davids]] refers to the parish in [[Grenada]] where she was brought up, to the south-east of the Island. She retired from the House of Lords on 10 January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-howells-of-st-davids/2486|title=Baroness Howells of St Davids|website=UK Parliament|language=English|access-date=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nHowells was educated at [[St Joseph's College, Reading]], [[South West London College]] and the [[University of the District of Columbia]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] In 1955, she married John Charles Howells and they have two daughters.\n\nHowells served as the Director of the [[Greenwich]] Racial Equality Council as well as a Community and Equal Opportunities Worker. Baroness Howells is a trustee of the [[Stephen Lawrence]] Charitable Trust, and served as the unofficial advisor to the Lawrence family.\n\nHowells was the first black woman to sit on the GLC's Training Board; the first female member of the Court of Governors of the University of Greenwich and was the Vice Chair at the [[London Voluntary Service Council]]. She has worked with the Carnival Liaison Committee, the Greater London Action in Race Equality, and has been an active campaigner for justice in the field of race relations. She is a Trustee of the [[Jason Roberts (footballer)|Jason Roberts]] Foundation, which aims to provide a range of sporting opportunities for children and young people in the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Grenada]].<ref>[http://jasonrobertsfoundation.com/thetrustees.htm Jason Roberts Foundation website.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809082131/http://jasonrobertsfoundation.com/thetrustees.htm |date=9 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009 she was inaugurated as the Chancellor of the [[University of Bedfordshire]] in [[Luton]].<ref>[http://www.beds.ac.uk/news/2009/mar/090319-chancellor \"Baroness Howells announced as new University Chancellor\", University of Bedfordshire, 19 March 2009.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330003954/http://www.beds.ac.uk/news/2009/mar/090319-chancellor |date=30 March 2010 }}</ref> Baroness Howells is a trustee of St George\u2019s University\u2019s UK Trust and serves on the board of the [[Windward Islands]] Research and Education Foundation (WINDREF), the research institute affiliated with [[St. George's University]].<ref>[http://www.sgu.edu/news-events/news-archives13-over-80-global-scholars-wcc.html#sthash.bFpBWp6g.dpuf St George\u2019s University.]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199899/minutes/991025/ldminute.htm Announcement of her introduction at the House of Lords] House of Lords minutes of proceedings, 25 October 1999.\n*[http://www.100greatblackbritons.com/bios/baroness_roselind_howells.html 100 Great Black Britons.]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[University of Bedfordshire|Chancellor of the University of Bedfordshire]]\n  | years  = 2009&ndash;2014\n  | before = ?\n  | after = [[John Bercow]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Howells, Rosalind Baroness Howells of St Davids}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers|Howells of St Davids, Rosalind Howells, Baron]]\n[[Category:Female life peers|Howells of St Davids, Rosalind Howells, Baron]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Grenadian emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Black British politicians]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Bedfordshire]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosalind_Howells,_Baroness_Howells_of_St_Davids"}
{"title_page": "Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society|timestamp=20200403132935|year=2020|month=April|day=3|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society|date=3 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society\n| abbreviation = CHCS\n| motto = \n| predecessor = \n| formation = 2018\n| founders = {{ubl | Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig}}\n| founding_location = [[Tuguegarao City]], Philippines\n| extinction = <!-- or: | dissolved = -->   <!--e.g. use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| merger = <!-- Other organizations (if any) merged to constitute the organization -->\n| type = [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]\n| status = <!-- Organization's legal status and/or description (company, charity, foundation, etc) -->\n| purpose = Heritage conservation  <!--(humanitarian, activism, peacekeeping, etc)-->\n}}\n\nThe '''Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society''' is a non profit organization aimed at creating and spreading awareness about [[Cagayan|Cagaya]]<nowiki/>n's rich history and culture through cultural education & research, training, and policy reform.  It was founded in 2018 by Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig, a native of [[Aparri]], Cagayan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1066477&ved=2ahUKEwjpmo7axMToAhULkJQKHTQYBlEQFjACegQIAhAB&usg=AOvVaw3rvbtCbRKt_bwu_hfuarae|title=500 join Heritage Walk in Tuguegarao|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://northernforum.net/who-said-cagayano-millennials-cant-revitalize-ibanag-itawes/|title=Who said Cagayano 'Millennials' can't revitalize Ibanag, Itawes?|last=Aquino|first=Amir|date=2018-08-23|website=The Northern Forum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nWith up to 100 active members in their mid-20s, they are poised to succeed elder local experts in the preservation of Cagayanos\u2019 languages and cultures later on.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Programs and Activities ==\nThe group is widely known for their successful heritage walks around [[Cagayan Valley]] dubbed as Manalan Tera. To date, they have conducted these informative walks in [[Aparri]], Tuguegarao City, Alcala, Dupax del Sur, and Bagabag. In Tuguegarao, The group's pioneers, President Kevin Baclig and Vice President Prince Wilson Macarubbo, gave lectures after the tour on old sites that included the East Central School, [[Tuguegarao Cathedral]], Rizal Park, Horno Ruins and Tribunal de Tuguegarao, which was the old provincial jail and now Cagayan Museum's new location. These sites have been proposed as heritage zone by the Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cagayan.gov.ph/news/heritage-walk-itinampok-ng-cagayan-museum-at-heritage-conservation-society/&ved=2ahUKEwjpmo7axMToAhULkJQKHTQYBlEQFjADegQIAxAB&usg=AOvVaw13im5BNY4yay-vaKxPsi2v|title=Heritage Walk itinampok ng Cagayan Museum at Heritage Conservation Society|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|language=Filipino}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cagayan.gov.ph/news/heritage-walk-itinampok-ng-cagayan-museum-at-heritage-conservation-society/&ved=2ahUKEwi92P3igcnoAhXMEqYKHcbgDBQ4ChAWMAJ6BAgIEAE&usg=AOvVaw13im5BNY4yay-vaKxPsi2v|title=Heritage Walk itinampok ng Cagayan Museum at Heritage Conservation Society|last=Lucena|first=Gerard Josef|date=|website=Cagayan.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThey also involve themselves in  talents development and promotion with their Minas anna Zininag\u00e2 which is a stage for budding local poets and local composers and musicians. Talks and seminars are also conducted dubbed Y Zininaga Tam.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cagayan Valley]]\n* [[Cagayan Province]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations based in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Historical societies]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society|timestamp=20200403132935|year=2020|month=April|day=3|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society|date=3 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society\n| abbreviation = CHCS\n| motto = \n| predecessor = \n| formation = 2018\n| founders = {{ubl | [[Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig]]}}\n| founding_location = [[Tuguegarao City]], Philippines\n| extinction = <!-- or: | dissolved = -->   <!--e.g. use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| merger = <!-- Other organizations (if any) merged to constitute the organization -->\n| type = [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]\n| status = <!-- Organization's legal status and/or description (company, charity, foundation, etc) -->\n| purpose = Heritage conservation  <!--(humanitarian, activism, peacekeeping, etc)-->\n}}\n\nThe '''Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society''' is a non profit organization aimed at creating and spreading awareness about [[Cagayan|Cagaya]]<nowiki/>n's rich history and culture through cultural education & research, training, and policy reform.  It was founded in 2018 by [[Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig]], a native of [[Aparri]], Cagayan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1066477&ved=2ahUKEwjpmo7axMToAhULkJQKHTQYBlEQFjACegQIAhAB&usg=AOvVaw3rvbtCbRKt_bwu_hfuarae|title=500 join Heritage Walk in Tuguegarao|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://northernforum.net/who-said-cagayano-millennials-cant-revitalize-ibanag-itawes/|title=Who said Cagayano 'Millennials' can't revitalize Ibanag, Itawes?|last=Aquino|first=Amir|date=2018-08-23|website=The Northern Forum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nWith up to 100 active members in their mid-20s, they are poised to succeed elder local experts in the preservation of Cagayanos\u2019 languages and cultures later on.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Programs and Activities ==\nThe group is widely known for their successful heritage walks around [[Cagayan Valley]] dubbed as Manalan Tera. To date, they have conducted these informative walks in [[Aparri]], Tuguegarao City, Alcala, Dupax del Sur, and Bagabag. In Tuguegarao, The group's pioneers, President Kevin Baclig and Vice President Prince Wilson Macarubbo, gave lectures after the tour on old sites that included the East Central School, [[Tuguegarao Cathedral]], Rizal Park, Horno Ruins and Tribunal de Tuguegarao, which was the old provincial jail and now Cagayan Museum's new location. These sites have been proposed as heritage zone by the Cagayan Heritage Conservation Society.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cagayan.gov.ph/news/heritage-walk-itinampok-ng-cagayan-museum-at-heritage-conservation-society/&ved=2ahUKEwjpmo7axMToAhULkJQKHTQYBlEQFjADegQIAxAB&usg=AOvVaw13im5BNY4yay-vaKxPsi2v|title=Heritage Walk itinampok ng Cagayan Museum at Heritage Conservation Society|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|language=Filipino}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cagayan.gov.ph/news/heritage-walk-itinampok-ng-cagayan-museum-at-heritage-conservation-society/&ved=2ahUKEwi92P3igcnoAhXMEqYKHcbgDBQ4ChAWMAJ6BAgIEAE&usg=AOvVaw13im5BNY4yay-vaKxPsi2v|title=Heritage Walk itinampok ng Cagayan Museum at Heritage Conservation Society|last=Lucena|first=Gerard Josef|date=|website=Cagayan.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThey also involve themselves in  talents development and promotion with their Minas anna Zininag\u00e2 which is a stage for budding local poets and local composers and musicians. Talks and seminars are also conducted dubbed Y Zininaga Tam.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cagayan Valley]]\n* [[Cagayan Province]]\n* [[Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Baclig]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations based in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Historical societies]]\n", "name_user": "Jo-Jo Eumerus", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Ni\u00f1o Kevin D. Bacligclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cagayan_Heritage_Conservation_Society"}
{"title_page": "Ruth Henig, Baroness Henig", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date= August 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name               = The Baroness Henig\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]] [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]]\n| image              = official portrait of Baroness Henig crop 2.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n|office5         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start5       = 8 June 2004<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n|term_end5       =\n| birth_name         = Ruth Beatrice Munzer\n| birth_date         = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|df=yes|1943|11|10}}}}\n| birth_place        = Leicester, England\n| citizenship        = [[British nationality law|British]]\n| nationality        = English\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Wyggeston Girls School, Leicester]],  [[University of London]], [[Lancaster University]]\n| occupation         = [[Historian]]<br>[[Politician]]\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| style              = \n| opponent           = \n| awards             = [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]<br>[[Deputy Lieutenant]]\n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Ruth Beatrice Henig, Baroness Henig''' [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (born '''Ruth Beatrice Munzer''' on 10 November 1943) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] academic [[historian]] and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician.\n\n==Family==\n\nHer parents were Kurt and Elfrieda Munzer, [[Jewish]] refugees who came to the United Kingdom from the [[Netherlands]] in 1940.  Henig was married in 1966 to fellow-academic [[Stanley Henig]], who shortly afterwards became a Labour [[Member of Parliament]] (MP).  They have two children, and divorced in 1993. Their son, [[Simon Henig]], is leader of [[Durham County Council]], chair of the [[North East Combined Authority]], and a lecturer in politics at [[Sunderland University]]. She remarried in 1994 to Jack Johnstone.\n\n==Academic career==\nHenig was educated at [[Wyggeston Girls Grammar School]] in [[Leicester]], and at [[Bedford College, London]], where she graduated in 1965 with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[history]].  She was awarded a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in history from [[Lancaster University]] in 1978, where she was a lecturer in Modern European History. She has written several books and pamphlets on 20th-century international history.\n\nShe served as [[Dean (education)|Dean]] of the Faculty of Arts and Humanities from 1997 to 2000, and in April 2006, she was one of six people to receive the first Honorary Fellowships of Lancaster University.\n\n==Political career==\n\nHenig was a Labour member of [[Lancashire County Council]] from 1981 to 2005, serving as the Council's chair from 1999 to 2000.  She was also Chair of [[Lancashire Constabulary|Lancashire]] [[Police authority|Police Authority]] from 1995 to 2005 and chair of the [[Association of Police Authorities]] from 1997 to 2005, when she became the Association's president. She was also a member of the National Criminal Justice Board from 2003 to 2005.\n\nAt the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], she stood as Labour candidate for her husband's former [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliamentary]] seat of [[Lancaster (UK Parliament constituency)|Lancaster]].  She failed to unseat the sitting [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP [[Elaine Kellett-Bowman]], but reduced the Conservative majority to just under 3,000,[http://www.psr.keele.ac.uk/area/uk/ge92/i12.htm] down from 6,500 in [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]].[http://www.psr.keele.ac.uk/area/uk/ge87/i12.htm]\n\nHenig was awarded a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]] in 2000 for services to policing,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55879 |date=19 June 2000 |page=8 |supp=y}}</ref> and in 2002 was appointed as a [[Deputy Lieutenant]] for [[Lancashire]].\n\nShe was made a [[life peer]] on 8 June 2004 as '''Baroness Henig''', of Lancaster in the County of [[Lancashire]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57323 |date=14 June 2004 |page=7379}}</ref>  She became a Deputy Speaker in the House of Lords in 2015.\n\nIn June 2013 Baroness Henig was awarded with The Association of Security Consultant's Award, part of the Imbert Prize named after the former Commissioner of the Metropolitan Police and the Lord Lieutenant of Greater London.  In an industry first, the prize, awarded to the most person making the most notable contribution to the security industry in the preceding year was shared with Don Randall MBE, the head of security to the Bank of England.  It was judged that Baroness Henig's contributions to the industry as Chair of the Security Industry Authority in overseeing the regulatory overhaul and building of a new and modern, fit-for-purpose regulatory regime made he an outstanding candidate.<ref name=awards>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sourcesecurity.com/news/articles/co-5520-ga-co-1677-ga.11220.html|accessdate=18 July 2013|publisher=Source Security|title=Security Institute members honoured at Association of Security Consultant\u2019s Imbert awards 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Another feather to Baroness Henig\u2019s cap\u2026receives joint award for exceptional contributions to security industry|url=http://www.vigilance-securitymagazine.com/industry-news/3791-another-feather-to-baroness-henigs-cap-receives-joint-award-for-exceptional-contributions-to-security-industry|work=Vigilance Security Magazine|accessdate=18 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 December 2006 the [[Home Secretary]] [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|Dr John Reid]] MP appointed Lady Henig as Chairman of the [[Security Industry Authority]] (aka the \u201cSIA\u201d)[http://www.the-sia.org.uk/home/about_sia/news/nr_061220.htm], a [[non-departmental public body]] tasked with the regulation of the private security industry. Having stepped down as Chair from the SIA after six years in March 2013, the Baroness continues to work towards building a unified voice for the industry having just been appointed as President of the Security Institute in April 2016. She is now non-executive Chairman with UK firm SecuriGroup and, as of March 2019, the Chairman of the Register of Chartered Security Professionals.\n\n==Interests==\nLady Henig's main leisure activity is playing Bridge, having played for Lancashire since the early 1990s, and is currently the captain of the House of Lords team. Henig is also a keen football fan, supporting Leicester City FC for over 60 years.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*{{cite web\n |url         = http://domino.lancs.ac.uk/info/lunews.nsf/x/473AC54F7136AE8F80256E8D0033D6DD\n |title       = Former Dean Made Life Peer\n |accessdate  = 2006-09-21\n |date        = 2004-05-07\n |publisher   = [[Lancaster University]]\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110611044125/http://domino.lancs.ac.uk/info/lunews.nsf/x/473AC54F7136AE8F80256E8D0033D6DD\n |archivedate = 11 June 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n*{{cite web\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/lancashire/3675009.stm\n| title = Senior police adviser made a peer\n| accessdate = 2006-09-21\n| date = 2004-05-01\n| publisher = BBC News\n}}\n*{{cite web\n| url = http://www.sia.homeoffice.gov.uk/Pages/about-board-members.aspx?staffid=2\n| title = SIA Chairman, Baroness Ruth Henig\n| accessdate = 2007-05-29\n| date = 2007-01-15\n| publisher = The SIA\n}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henig, Ruth Beatrice}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of 